<DOCNO> AP881229-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Dissent     12-29 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Dissent,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Man Launches Crusade For Democracy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As China enjoys a marked thaw in restrictions on
cultural debate, an intense, voluble man with no political stature
and little fame has launched a one-man crusade to open up debate on
democracy and communist rule.
   Sexual themes now can be portrayed on canvas and the screen, and
economists can question the wisdom of state ownership of factories.
But suggestions for limits to the Communist Party's power are an
invitation for arrest.
   Ren Wanding, a thin, shaggy-haired accountant who rarely laughs,
knows it.
   He spent 1979-83 in prison for having advocated multiparty
democracy, and after a long silence renewed his call last month with
an open letter to the U.N. Human Rights Commission and a 22-page
essay on freedom.
   This week, he began distributing among foreign journalists four
new essays denouncing the ruling Communist Party as a narrow-minded
bully and appealing to the world at large to show concern for human
rights in China.
   ``If one just thinks about things and doesn't have the freedom to
speak out, then there's no freedom,'' Ren wrote in one essay,
explaining his motivation.
   Aware that his own arrest now would prove the point, Ren wrote in
another, ``I appeal to the power of international society for
protection.''
   Ren, an accountant, said in an interview that he spends most of
his non-working hours writing essays and plans to distribute batches
of them each month to foreign and Hong Kong media.
   He said he does not expect to persuade the government to change,
but wants to stimulate public debate and make China's political
prisoners better known abroad, as are the dissidents in the Soviet
Union.
   Ren also is indignant that, as China celebrates the 10th
anniversary of its opening to the outside world and economic reform
under senior leader Deng Xiaoping, activists who advocated many of
the same reforms remain in jail.
   Those jailed, like himself, were leaders of the 1978-79 Democracy
Wall Movement. During those few heady months, intellectuals debated
politics in home-mimeographed journals and posters pasted on a wall
in central Beijing, dubbed Democracy Wall.
   Ren insisted they had an impact, despite their eventual silencing.
   ``If one says that Chinese society has progressed over 10 years
and the economy has grown greatly, all of this is because Chinese
social reformers paid the painful price of sacrificing their freedom
and fortune,'' he wrote. ``Without their brave spirit, could Chinese
have as much freedom of discussion and modernization as they have
today? Would the ruling authorities have voluntarily granted this?''
   Such Democracy Wall themes as the need for multicandidate
elections, greater contact with the outside world and policies to
end China's backwardness have since been adopted by the government.
``Where then is the crime?'' Ren wrote.
   Despite thick glasses and a solemn manner, Ren looks younger than
his 44 years. His work at as an accountant at a Beijing equipment
installation company is not demanding, he said, but he has been
given no chances for promotion.
   Officials have refused to transfer his wife's residence permit
from Tianjin to Beijing, 75 miles away. She lives illegally in
Beijing with him, making it impossible for her to find work.
   Ren said he has not told his 12-year-old daughter that he was in
prison.
   His essays are closely argued outpourings of personal frustration
and outraged principles. In one, he denounced communist authorities
as ``narrow-minded .... They fear the general public but bully small
groups of people.''
   He also denounced the practice of bypassing the courts for
misdemeanor cases and allowing police to hand out sentences for
``labor education.''
   ``There is no way to appeal in court, and covzr-ups, false
arrests and illegalities are hidden,'' he wrote. ``Why doesn't China
even respect its own regulations?''
   Ren, who never was tried, was ordered to undergo labor education
but actually spent his four years in jail ``without labor and
without education,'' he said.
   Newly emerged from his long silence and without a wall or journal
to proclaim his views, Ren seems uncertain how to proceed. He said
he has no plans to go to campuses and address China's most volatile
and receptive sector _ the students _ or to start up a publication.
   So far, neither his employers nor police have questioned him
about his new political activity.
   ``I'm not alone. Many people agree with me,'' he said. But he is
at a loss to explain why he is the only one stepping into the
dangerous limelight. ``I've always been a free-thinker,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Trade Bjt   12-29 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Trade, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Has Powerful Weapon To Negotiate Trade
Accords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known deal between the White House and
Congress should make it easier for President-elect Bush to reach
agreements with the rest of the world on tough trade issues such as
the current dispute over hormones in U.S. beef.
   Beginning Sunday, the 12 countries of the European Economic
Community are banning all imports of meat treated with hormones _
including U.S. beef and veal worth about $100 million a year. The
Reagan administration promised to retaliate by raising duties on
European food shipped here.
   Counterretaliations and counter-counterretaliations are
threatened, in what some see as a potential trade war.
   Over the long run such conflicts can be limited by the United
States using the ``fast track'' for making trade agreements. A
series of agreements is being drafted by 96 governments in the
current ``Uruguay round'' of trade talks.
   Despite its name, the fast track is less important for its speed
than for the power its gives the president. Reagan signed the latest
version into law last August as part of a major trade bill. On
Wednesday he issued an executive order on regulations to implement
the new law.
   It associates key members of Congress closely with trade talks,
though not as actual negotiators. After an agreement is reached,
Congress is pledged to vote it up or down in 90 days _ no exceptions
or conditions, no internal bargaining over details.
   That differs from the usual relations between the White House and
Capitol Hill. Often the administration and Congress bargain for
months or even years over what goes into an important bill before it
becomes law _ or fails.
   The fast track allows the administration to make promises that
are bound to be unpopular in Congress, such as ending protection for
a small industry against foreign competition. Under the fast track
system the negotiators can gamble that Congress will accept the
entire agreement, even if many members dislike parts of it.
   Governments of other countries long have complained that they
cannot get firm commitments from a U.S. negotiator. They can make
firm promises themselves because the French or Japanese prime
ministers, for example, can threaten to dissolve parliament and
force members to fight a new election unless his promises are
supported. A U.S. president can't do that.
   Raymond Vernon, who negotiated for presidents from Franklin
Roosevelt to Jimmy Carter, tells a story about Lord Keynes, the
famous economist who came to Washington to get more aid for Britain
in World War II. Keynes was annoyed to hear one official after
another explain how Roosevelt favored many measures but Congress
would not approve them.
   Keynes dropped his usual politeness when one American, more
pompous than the others, began by saying:
   ``My government _ ''
   ``You know,'' Kenyes interrupted, ``you people don't really have
a government at all, in the usual sense of the word.''
   Many officials, Americans and non-Americans, fail to grasp the
difference between the American system and the parliamentary system.
Non-Americans often complain that the United States has gone back on
a pledge when a U.S. negotiator promises his best effort to get
something done and then Congress _ not operating on the fast track _
refuses to do it.
   Some blamed President Woodrow Wilson for World War II because he
negotiated for a League of Nations after World War I and Congress
refused to join it. Wilson failed to bring key senators close to the
negotiations.
   Vernon identified the inventor of the fast track as Richard L.
Rivers, a Washington lawyer who worked for the Senate Finance
Committee in 1973. President Nixon was trying to negotiate what was
first called the ``Nixon round'' of trade agreements. The White
House asked Congress for a law that would give him almost unlimited
power to negotiate, but allow either house to disapprove the result.
   Rivers said in an interview that he will always remember former
Sen. Herman Talmadge, D-Ga., a key member of the Finance Committee,
fiery reaction to that proposal: ``That's not the way we make our
laws in this country.''
   The Supreme Court since has ruled that such ``legislative
vetoes'' are unconstitutional.
   Rivers wrote a memorandum that devised the fast track for
Talmadge and it became law as part of the president's authority to
negotiate. It was used under Nixon and President Ford to complete
what became known as the ``Tokyo round'' after Nixon resigned.
   Later versions of the fast track have been used under Reagan to
negotiate free trade agreements with Israel and Canada.
   In a recent book, ``Beyond Globalism,'' Vernon has proposed
widening it.
   ``There is a strong temptation to look for a mechanism in which
the main lines of trade policy, monetary policy, fiscal policy and
establishment policy will have been jointly explored between the
branches in an effort to identify the key assumptions, establish the
principal goals and iron out the gross inconsistencies,'' he wrote.
   But he added that it is difficult to envision an effective
dialogue between the president and Congress on so wide a range of
issues.
   Vernon, 75 years old, has retired as a professor of international
relations at Harvard University. His book was written with Debora L.
Spar, who was studying for a doctorate there.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Hartman covers international economics for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
