<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan     12-29 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says New 12-Mile Offshore Limit Will Help Deter Spies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Reagan departure scheduled for 6:35 p.m. EST. No tops planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to extend U.S.
territorial waters an additional nine miles offshore will make it
more difficult for foreign countries to spy on American shores,
administration officials say.
   Reagan took the action Wednesday at the Bel Air home where he
will live after Jan. 20. He and first lady Nancy Reagan are spending
the holidays there, but were leaving today for three days in Palm
Springs.
   By a proclamation, the president extended U.S. ``sovereignty and
jurisdiction'' from the present three miles to 12 miles.
   Maureen Walker, a foreign affairs officer in the State
Department's Office of Ocean Law and Policy, said the extension
makes the United States the 105th country to claim a 12-mile limit.
   The 12-mile limit was called for in 1982 by the United Nations
Convention on the Law of the Sea, and the U.S. action leaves only
six countries claiming narrower bands of offshore water. Finland and
Norway claim four miles each, and the Dominican Republic, Greece,
Israel and Turkey each claim six miles, Ms. Walker said.
   ``It will make foreign intelligence-gathering more difficult and
less effective because foreign ships will no longer be able to
station themselves off our shores within the 12-mile limit,'' the
State Department officer said.
   The proclamation assures foreign ships the right of ``innocent
passage'' through U.S. territorial waters and the right to pass
through straits.
   Ms. Walker said it would not affect U.S. and state laws that
govern offshore mineral and fishing rights.
   It applies to the waters off the United States, Puerto Rico,
Guam, American Samoa, the U.S. Virgin Islands, the Northern Mariana
islands and any other territory over which the United States
exercises sovereignty. It applies to airspace over the ocean, as
well as the waters and the bed and subsoil of the ocean.
   In another action, the president extended for six months the
state of emergency that he proclaimed in 1986 between the United
States and Libya. The step was needed to continue in effect the
president's 1986 order blocking Libyan assets in the United States
in retaliation for alleged terrorist action.
   The president also signed a seven-page executive order
implementing the 1,100-page trade act passed by the last Congress.
White House deputy press secretary Leslye Arsht said the order will
enable the United States ``to continue effectively to work for more
open world markets and strengthened international institutions.''
   Ms. Arsht said the president's national security adviser, Lt.
Gen. Colin L. Powell, telephoned him at the Bel Air home to inform
him of the announcement by the British Department of Transport that
last week's crash of Pan American Flight 103 in Scotland was caused
by a bomb.
   ``The investigation will continue to determine how the explosives
were introduced into the plane,'' she said. ``The FBI and the FAA
are working closely with the British and Scottish authorities on the
investigation. We are determined to find out who did it, using all
available resources.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PlaneBombings     12-29 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Bombings,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am Investigators May Need Lucky Break To Catch Bombers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judging by previous crashes in which bombing
was suspected, authorities investigating the Pan American Flight 103
disaster may need a lucky break in the case to apprehend those who
carried out the sabotage.
   British authorities said Wednesday that from examining wreckage
they had gathered ``conclusive evidence'' that a bomb blew up the
Pan Am Boeing 747 jumbo jet over southern Scotland last week.
Spokesman John Boyd said Scotland Yard and the FBI had joined forces
in ``a criminal inquiry of international dimensions.''
   The challenge of finding those responsible is illustrated by
looking at two crashes widely blamed on bombing: the Nov. 29, 1987,
crash of a Korean Air Boeing 707 off the coast of Burma and the
plunge of an Air-India 747 into the Irish Sea on June 22, 1985. The
Korean Air crash killed 115 people, while the Air-India tragedy
claimed 329 lives.
   In the incident involving Korean Air Flight 858, suspicion
quickly focused on two passengers, a man and a woman, who were
detained for questioning about forged Japanese passports in Bahrain
as they were about to board a plane for Rome. They had left the
doomed Korean aircraft, bound from Baghdad to Bangkok, at an
intermediary stop in Abu Dhabi.
   The pair, who turned out to be North Korean agents, both bit into
cyanide capsules hidden in cigarette filters. The man, identified as
Kim Sung Il, 70, succeeded in his suicide attempt, but the woman,
Kim Hyon Hui, 25, survived and was extradited to South Korea.
   After questioning by South Korean authorities, Ms. Kim told a
nationally televised news conference on Jan. 15, 1988, that she had
been involved in bombing the Korean Air jet. She said the episode
was intended to disrupt preparations for the 1988 Seoul Olympics and
create unrest in the South.
   ``I came out here hoping such violent, meaningless incidents
would never happen again in the future and I would like to apologize
to family members of the dead and the people here by disclosing the
truth,'' she said in admitting her role in the incident.
   South Korean intelligence officers said Ms. Kim was acting on the
personal orders of Kim Jong Il, son and political heir of top North
Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
   North Korea officially denied involvement with the crash.
   By contrast, in the crash of Air-India Flight 182, lengthy
investigations by Indian, Canadian, British and Irish authorities
have failed to conclusively pinpoint blame for the tragedy.
   Soon after the crash, unidentified callers to news media said the
crash was the work of extremists associated with Sikh separatist
organizations. Spokesmen for Sikh groups, however, denied any role
and accused India of trying to foment anti-Sikh sentiment.
   According to Indian officials, tapes from the plane's cockpit
voice and flight data recorders, recovered from 6,700 feet below the
surface of the Irish Sea, neither proved nor disproved the
possibility that sabotage was involved. One official, S.N. Sharma,
told reporters the cockpit conversation was normal until it came to
a ``sudden and abrupt end.''
   A report by Canada's Aviation Safety Board, disclosed in January
1986, said there was ``considerable circumstantial and other
evidence that an explosive device'' detonated in the front cargo
compartment of the plane, which was headed from Toronto to Bombay
via London.
   The report linked the explosion to a suitcase checked onto the
flight by a man using the name Singh who did not board the plane.
Singh, meaning lion, is a name used by all male Sikhs.
   A book published in Canada in May 1987 pointed to the lack of
arrests in the Air-India case.
   ``Among the bereaved families, the call for justice is louder,
the bitterness and cynicism sharper than at any time since the
crash,'' said the book, ``The Sorrow and the Terror.''
   The book by award-winning Canadian writers Clark Blaise and his
India-born wife, Bharati Mukherjee, claimed that four members of a
Sikh terrorist cell in Vancouver, British Columbia, were suspected
by police.
   It also claimed that the principals in the case celebrated with
pizza at a Sikh temple in the Toronto suburb of Malton at about the
time the Air-India jet plunged into the sea.
   The problem is to have a case solid enough to prove in court, the
authors said. ``To lose the case on any kind of technicality would
be a political nightmare,'' according to the book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
