<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Homeless     12-29 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Identifies Public Buildings That Could Shelter
Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although they may not be available this winter,
44 ``underutilized'' government buildings and 50 land sites have
been designated by the Reagan administration as suitable for
sheltering the nation's homeless.
   Meeting a court-appointed deadline, the Department of Housing and
Urban Development on Thursday ruled that 94 of the 220 pieces of
property it reviewed in the past two weeks are suitable for
assisting homeless people.
   However, only 33 of the buildings were determined to be suitable
for overnight occupancy or for daytime activities. Another 11 were
called suitable only for non-occupancy programs such as warehousing
food and clothing.
   James E. Schoenberger, deputy assistant HUD secretary for
housing, said the unused or underutilized land parcels could be used
as sites for erecting mobile homes or modular units as temporary
shelters.
   It is problematic whether any of the facilities might be made
available for the homeless before this winter is over.
   ``This is a multi-stage process and HUD is sort of in the middle
of it,'' Schoenberger said. ``But this could be a relatively quick
process from this point on.''
   Some of the properties could be made available in less than 45
days, HUD officials said, assuming they meet local health and
building codes.
   City and state officials or private, non-profit organizations
wanting to use the buildings or land have 30 days to submit
applications. The General Services Administration and the Department
of Health and Human Services, which own the properties, then have a
maximum of 15 days to review the applications.
   HUD was under a Dec. 28 deadline imposed two weeks ago by U.S.
District Court Judge Oliver Gasch here to review at least half of
350 properties listed by GSA and HHS as being excess or surplus. He
gave HUD until Jan. 12 to survey the rest of the listed properties,
which includes some 1,000 buildings.
   The government defines excess property as buildings or land under
the authority of a particular agency that doesn't have any use for
it. Surplus property is that for which no government agency has any
use.
   Because HUD had only two weeks under Gasch's order to come up
with a list, Schoenberger said the determinations of suitability
were made solely on the basis of questionnaires filled out by GSA
and HHS.
   ``We originally intended to have HUD field office staff inspect
all properties which appeared to be suitable,'' he said. ``However,
the short amount of time allowed ... required that we omit the
on-site property inspection.''
   Gasch imposed the deadlines in response to a suit filed last
September by the National Coalition for the Homeless accusing the
administration of failing to implement a law passed in July 1987 to
make ``underutilized'' federal property available for use as
emergency shelters.
   Maris Foscarinis, an attorney for the coalition, called
President-elect Bush's support of the program encouraging but said
it is ``shameful that the Reagan administration forced a protracted
court battle before obeying a congressional mandate.''
   Of the 126 facilities found unsuitable because they lack sound
floors, foundations, roofs, walls, electric power or sanitary or
water facilities, 53 are buildings and 73 are land sites.
   The locations of unused or underutilized federally owned
buildings listed as suitable for overnight shelters were listed as:
   Bell, Point Arena, Tracy and West Los Angeles, Calif.;
Washington, D.C.; Waycross, Ga.; Oxford and Shoshone, Idaho; Dana,
Ind.; Boothville, La.; Middle River, Md.; Pontiac, Mich.; Remer,
Minn.; Vicksburg, Miss.; Tonopah, Nev.; Binghamton, N.Y.;
Smithfield, N.C.; Hauser and Klamath Falls, Ore.; Phoenixville, Pa.;
Aquadilla and San Juan, Puerto Rico; Maryville, Tenn.; Carrizo
Springs, Rockwall and San Antonio, Texas; Arlington, Va.; Elma and
Warden, Wash., and Lander, Wyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
