<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FlightDiverted     12-29 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flight Diverted,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Flight Diverted After Cabin Depressurized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight carrying 40 passengers was diverted for an
unscheduled landing at Logan International Airport Wednesday after
losing cabin pressurization, apparently due to a faulty valve,
officials said.
   Continental Airlines Flight 269 from Hartford, Conn., to
Cleveland had been airborne for about a half hour when the cabin of
the Boeing 737 aircraft depressurized, said Continental spokesman
Dave Messing in Houston. Passengers were told to use oxygen masks,
and no-one was injured, he said.
   The flight was diverted to Logan, where it landed without
incident at about 5 p.m. and passengers were put on other flights.
   The plane was to be repaired overnight, Messing said.
   ``The mechanics are looking at it. At this point it appears the
depressurization stemmed from a faulty valve in the pressurization
system,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     12-29 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Roseanne' Beats `Cosby'; NBC Might Have All-Win Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC had its first No. 1 series since 1984 when
``Roseanne'' edged NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' for the top spot in the
weekly A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   The last ABC No. 1 show that was a regularly scheduled series was
the Dec. 19, 1984, episode of ``Dynasty.''
   Due to expected low holiday week viewing, NBC loaded up its
schedule with repeats. A first-run ``Roseanne'' beat a repeat of
``Cosby.''
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Who's the Boss?''
ABC, ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC; ``A Different World,'' NBC;
``L.A. Law,'' NBC; ``Matlock,'' NBC; ``Night Court,'' NBC; and ``In
the Heat of the Night,'' NBC.
   CBS' highest-rated shows of the week were ``Designing Women'' at
17th, followed by ``Murphy Brown'' at 18th.
   NBC racked up its 27th straight weekly victory. If NBC wins the
rest of the season, it would be the first time a network has done so
since CBS won every week of the 1963-64 season. NBC came within a
week of that 39-week record last year, but the World Series on ABC
broke the streak.
   If NBC does set a record for 1988-89 it will be with an asterisk
because the writers' strike delayed ABC's and CBS' fall lineups,
while NBC began the season with the Summer Olympics.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with an average, prime-time
rating of 13.7 to ABC's 11.7 and CBS' 10.9. The season officially
began 14 weeks ago, giving NBC a season-to-date average rating of
16.0 to ABC's 13.1 and CBS' 11.9. ABC and CBS count the season as
having begun in late October, at which time they had gotten most of
their strike-delayed new shows on the air.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 households with television.
   The network news race is so close, the ratings changed ever so
slightly last week and turned the standings around. The ``CBS
Evening News'' resumed first place with an average 11.0 rating.
``ABC World News Tonight'' had 10.8, and ``NBC Nightly News'' had
10.6.
   Due to Christmas Eve and Christmas Day falling on Saturday and
Sunday, the only two nights of Fox programming, Fox ran all repeats
and suffered an expectable drop in ratings. It's lowest-rated show,
``Beyond Tomorrow,'' had a meager 1.9 rating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
