<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0713 12-29 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in the Northeast, High Temperatures Down South</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf with one graf and grafs 8-11, bgng `In
Baltimore,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more collapsed buildings and
outages reported in Baltimore-Washington region. Picks up 12 graf
pvs, `A gale....'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow continued in the Northeast on Wednesday and hurricane-force
winds blasted Maryland, blowing the roof off a terminal at a
Baltimore airport, collapsing at least three buildings and knocking
out electricity for at least 300,000 customers in the region.
   Light snow extended from the upper Ohio Valley to northern New
England, and up to 8 inches blanketed Indiana by Wednesday morning.
   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period up to 1 p.m. EST
included 3 inches at Dayton, Ohio, and 2 inches at Buffalo, N.Y.,
Cincinnati, Cleveland and Columbus, Ohio, and at Evansville, Ind.
   An inch of snow in Little Rock, Ark., established a record for
the date.
   In California, Interstate 5 was closed for hours after a gasoline
tanker truck slipped on icy pavement, crashed into other cars and
exploded with a fireball visible miles away, authorities said. There
were only two minor injuries in that wreck.
   Snow advisories were posted Wednesday night for most of Ohio,
portions of Pennsylvania, New York, Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine.
   Strong northerly winds were ushering cold air into the eastern
portion of the country.
   In Baltimore, gusts were clocked at 80 mph. The wind collapsed
three vacant buildings, blew roofs off five houses and ripped the
roofs of two buildings in Baltimore County, authorities said.
   Part of the roof on the main terminal at Baltimore-Washington
International Airport flew onto the tarmac and the wind blew out two
glass windows, said Bob Ware, advertising manager at BWI. There were
no injuries, he said.
   Other buildings also were damaged, but flights returned to normal
after a brief delay, airport officials said.
   About 185,000 customers of Baltimore Gas & Electric Co. lost
electricity in the storm, spokesman Charles Franklin said, and
99,000 remained without power late Wednesday.
   Other utility spokesmen said 30,000 customers lost power in
Delaware and more than 100,000 in Washington, D.C.
   Winds gusted at up to 77 mph in the nation's capital, blowing
trees onto houses and into crowded streets at rush hour.
   Firefighters in nearby Fairfax County, Va., reported rescuing
several people from collapsed structures such as trailers and
buildings under contruction.
   A gale warning was in effect for Lake Ontario, and a high wind
warning was posted for the mountains of North Carolina.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed ahead of the cold front in
the eastern United States. Temperatures were in the 70s over much of
the southern Atlantic Coast region, with lower 80s across much of
Florida.
   Daytona Beach surpassed its record high for the date of 81
degrees set in 1987.
   Temperatures were freezing from the northern and central high
Plains to the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes region, and were
generally below zero from eastern Montana to Minnesota.
   Parts of the Southwest had snow, including southern Utah and
Nevada. A winter storm watch was posted in New Mexico.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14
degrees below zero at Grand Forks, N.D., to 84 degrees at Fort
Myers, Fla. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 18 degrees below
zero at Dickinson and Williston, N.D.
   The forecast for Thursday called for wet weather to extend from
the northern Pacific Coast to the northern Rocky Mountains, with
snow in the higher elevations. Rain and snow showers were expected
to be scattered across much of Arizona, New Mexico and Texas. Widely
scattered snow showers were predicted from Illinois to the lower
Great Lakes region. Fair to partly sunny skies should prevail across
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast to remain below freezing all day
across much of the Plateau and Rocky Mountain region and from the
northern high Plains through the middle and upper Mississippi Valley
to northern New England. Highs in the teens and single digits were
expected from eastern Montana through the Dakotas to upper Michigan
and across northern Maine. The rest of the nation should have highs
in the 50s, 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
