<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Veterans'Benefits     12-29 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veterans' Benefits,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Study Says Criteria For Veterans' Disability Benefits Are
Outdated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many disabled veterans may be missing out on
hundreds of dollars' worth of benefits from the Veterans
Administration because the payments are calculated with outdated
medical standards, according to a congressional study.
   The VA, responding to the report Wednesday by the General
Accounting Office, said it has agreed to make the first
comprehensive overhaul of the medical standards since 1945.
   The standards have been updated on a piecemeal basis over the
past few decades, the report said, but they still fail to take into
account many medical advances.
   As a result, the GAO said many veterans may be over- or
under-compensated for injuries that occurred both during military
duty and afterward.
   ``VA cannot ensure that veterans are given accurate and uniform
disability ratings because the rating schedule has not been adjusted
to incorporate the results of many recent medical advances,'' the
study said.
   The VA paid about $14.3 billion in disability benefits to about
3.8 million veterans and their survivors in 1987, said the GAO, the
investigative branch of Congress.
   ``It is inherently difficult to achieve uniform and accurate
administration of this type of program; out-of-date rating schedules
make it almost impossible,'' according to the report.
   Some medical conditions are not listed in the schedule, which
means a VA rating specialist must use his or her own judgment to
classify the disability, the report said.
   Veterans Administrator Thomas K. Turnage, responding to the
study, said he would prepare a plan for a ``methodical review'' of
the rating schedule, and added that he agreed with a recommendation
that the schedule be reviewed regularly from now on.
   The Department of Defense said it agreed with the report's
findings.
   A 1983 internal study by the VA used 13 sample cases representing
23 separate disabilities for which veterans already had been awarded
compensation benefits. Those cases were sent to 56 of the 58 VA
regional offices to be classified.
   In one case, a veteran with hypertensive heart disease was
assigned five different ratings, ranging from 10 percent disability
to 100 percent. Twenty-five rating boards gave him a 30 percent
disability, or $202 per month in benefits, and 21 boards gave him 60
percent, or $516 in benefits.
   In another case, a veteran with post traumatic stress disorder
was rated from zero to 70 percent disabled by the various boards,
which would have meant anywhere from no benefits to $410 a month,
the report said.
   In a GAO survey of 383 VA rating specialists, 61 percent said it
was ``somewhat likely'' or ``very likely'' that in rating mental
disorders, they could reach two or more rating percentages with the
same medical evidence.
   Fifty-one percent said the same situation could occur in rating
neurological and convulsive disorders, and for all types of illness,
22 percent said it was likely to reach more than one conclusion with
the same medical evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LeadLawsuit     12-29 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lead Lawsuit,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Accuses Du Pont Of Putting Too Much Lead in Gasoline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government filed a $8.23 million suit
against E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co., accusing the chemicals giant
of helping produce gasoline containing too much lead at a New Jersey
refinery from 1983 through 1985.
   The company, a major supplier of lead compounds, said the suit
was ``without merit'' because it was not subject to the regulations
it is accused of violating.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said a complaint, filed
Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Newark, N.J., charged that a
joint venture of Du Pont and three other companies put 2 billion
grams too much lead _ 2,200 tons _ in gasoline blended at Carteret,
N.J.
   The government seeks the maximum fine of $10,000 a day for each
of the 823 days specified in the complaint.
   EPA in 1986 filed an administrative complaint against Du Pont but
was unable to reach a settlement with the company.
   In Wilmington, Del., company spokesman Tom Barry read a statement
from Jerry McCleskey, planning director of the company's chemicals
and pigments department, charging that EPA's action was ``without
merit.''
   ``The allegations are false. We will contest the novel and
strained interpretation of the regulations. We complied fully with
all regulations applicable to lead suppliers,'' and cannot be held
responsible for alleged violations by others, McCleskey said.
   Later, Barry himself said it was ``simply not a fact'' that the
operation was a ``joint venture'' as EPA said.
   Du Pont said it was only a supplier. But EPA contended that Du
Pont decided how much lead was to be used, injected the compound at
the blending plant, determined that the final product was suitable
for sale as leaded gasoline and advised the other participants in
the venture about EPA regulations.
   The activities in effect made Du Pont a refiner, subject to the
refining regulations and just as responsible for the excess lead as
any of the other parties, EPA said.
   The agency filed administrative complaints against the other
three companies, two of which are now inactive. The third, A.
Tarricone Inc., a New York petroleum marketer, is operating under
protection of the bankruptcy courts and EPA said it had filed a
claim against that company in the bankruptcy case.
   Lead is the cheapest way to increase gasoline octane, but high
concentrations in auto emissions can cause neurological damage to
children and may contribute to high blood pressure in adults. It
also damages pollution control equipment in cars not designed for
leaded gasoline.
   EPA has been ordering lower concentrations of lead in leaded
gasoline for years. The 1982 limit of 1.1 gram per gallon was
reduced to 0.5 gram on July 1, 1985 and 0.1 gram on Jan. 1, 1986.
   The 2 billion grams of excessive lead added by the Carteret plant
would amount to about 2 percent of all lead used in fuels in
1983-1985, according to EPA estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
