<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Barry     12-29 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barry,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Top Aides Refused Mayor's Plan To Blame Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry wanted to blame city police
for unfairly raising suspicions about him in connection with the
aborted drug investigation of an acquaintance, but his senior aides
refused to go along with the plan, according to a published report.
   Barry met with his aides Wednesday in an attempt to draft a
formal response to accusations that he consorted with a man police
identified as a drug suspect.
   The Washington Post reported today that Barry had planned to
suggest that his visits to a downtown hotel to meet former city
employee Charles Lewis involved no wrongdoing, and that poor police
work had unfairly raised suspicions about him. However, three of
Barry's aides refused to endorse the plan, the newspaper reported,
citing sources it did not identify.
   In advance of an expected statement by Barry today on the
incident, one official and a city council called on him to explain
publicly his relationship with Lewis.
   City Councilman James Nathanson said Wednesday that Barry is
suffering ``a credibility problem'' with various council members and
other city officials.
   ``My reaction is, it's too bad we're here again,'' said
Nathanson, referring to allegations of drug involvement that have
dogged Barry for several years. ``My only suggestion is that the
mayor make a public statement about what's happening with him, just
lay it on the line.''
   Police investigators have turned over to the U.S. Attorney's
Office the results of an internal probe into why two detectives were
stopped from attempting an undercover drug buy from Lewis last
Thursday, after Barry turned up at Lewis' hotel room.
   Barry has since acknowledged making several calls upon Lewis,
whom he described as an acquaintance, but denied any involvement
with drugs.
   The current probe was expected to determine whether Lewis was
involved in any drug activity, why the mayor was in the hotel, and
why the police officers did not search Lewis' hotel room until after
he had checked out Friday morning.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's office would not comment on
the report.
</TEXT>
