<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     12-29 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Recall Issued for Wooden Enclosures After Child's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government, spurred by the death of a
17-month-old boy in Pennsylvania, has issued a second recall for
wooden, accordion-style enclosures used as playpens for small
children.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said Wednesday that
Nu-Line Industries of Suring, Wis., is offering a $10 cash refund or
$15 coupon for anyone who returns a wooden enclosure, whether it was
manufactured by Nu-Line or another company.
   The agency said children between 10 months and 2 years of age are
at the greatest risk because their heads can become stuck in the
diamond-shaped openings in the middle of the enclosure or the
V-shaped openings at the top.
   People may reach Nu-Line by calling a toll-free number,
1-800-558-7300.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Finds 15 Percent of Vets Suffered Post-Traumatic Stress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Administration says more than 15
percent of the men who served in the Vietnam war are suffering from
post-traumatic stress disorder.
   A four-year study ordered by Congress and released Wednesday
projected that 479,000 of the 3.1 million veterans who served in the
war suffer the disorder and that about 20 percent have sought
treatment from the VA.
   The survey, based on face-to-face interviews conducted with more
than 3,000 veterans, also found that 8.5 percent of women Vietnam
veterans, or 610 out of an estimated 7,000 who served, now have the
disorder.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Forest Service Faulted For Woodlands Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee says the U.S. Forest Service's latest analysis of the
future of America's woodlands ignores problems posed to forests by
global warming.
   ``This is an inexplicable omission,'' Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
said in a statement Wednesday.
   Leahy said there is no mention of the so-called greenhouse effect
in the draft ``Analysis of the Timber Situation in the United
States: 1989-2040,'' the latest edition of a document updated every
10 years by the Forest Service.
   Leahy also released a letter to Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng to order a rewriting of the analysis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Budget Faulted For Not Inspecting Rental Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission and Budget
Rent-A-Car Corp. have settled a complaint that the firm had failed
to give timely service to rental cars for which recall notices had
been issued.
   Under a consent agreement with the FTC announced on Wednesday,
Budget agreed to inspect and repair affected vehicles within a
reasonable time.
   According to the government's complaint, Budget rented to the
general public automobiles that were subject to recall notices, and
failed to so warn customers of the potential problems. Under the
consent agreement, Budget will inspect and repair vehicles within
120 days after receiving a recall notice.
</TEXT>
