<HEAD>Highrise Fire Breaks Out; People Trapped</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with fire out. People in building being rescued. ADDS
background on First Interstate fire. No pickup. </NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire erupted on the ninth floor of a 13-story
building housing news and entertainment organizations Wednesday
night, briefly trapping an undetermined number of people above the
flames, authorities said.
   More than 80 firefighters battled the blaze, which broke out
shortly before 9:30 p.m. and was put out within an hour, said
Firefighter Jim Wells.
   Office and maintenance workers trapped by the flames at the
Cahuenga Sunset Building on Hollywood's Sunset Boulevard fled to the
roof while firefighters entered the building and hosed down the fire.
   No injuries were reported.
   After the blaze was doused, firefighters rappelled to the roof
from a hovering helicopter and escorted people down the stairs from
the upper floors.
   ``Everything's out and everything's OK,'' said Wells. ``That's
the bottom line.''
   The cause of the fire, which was contained to the ninth floor,
was being investigated.
   Among the building's tenants are the American Society of
Composers, Authors and Publishers; Cable News Network; Paramount
Pictures; Actors Equity Association; radio stations KJOI and KIQQ
and a modeling agency.
   The fire broke out as renovation continued on the 62-story First
Interstate Bank building, where a spectacular May 4 fire on the 12th
through 16th floors killed one person and injured 40.
</TEXT>
