<HEAD>Dollar Moves Slightly Higher In Early Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS two grafs with dollar closing. Picks up graf 2 pvs, `The
Tokyo ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose for the third consecutive day
against the Japanese yen Thursday in Tokyo.
   The dollar ended the year's trading at 126.03 yen, up 0.76 yen
from Wednesday's close and up 4.03 yen from its 1987 year-end
closing. It had opened Thursday at 125.42 yen.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange finished its last trading day of the
year Wednesday and will be closed through Jan. 3.
   An exchange dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar
``strengthened after the market interpreted Wednesday's intervention
by the West German Bundesbank as a signal of concern over
inflation.''
   The Bundesbank was reported to have sold about $100 million in
support of the West German mark during Wednesday's trading, the
official said, speaking anonymously.
   He said, however, that the dollar and yen were likely to remain
around the same levels for the remainder of the year due to sparse
staffing of dealing offices in Japan and elsewhere prior to the New
Year holiday period.
</TEXT>
