<DOCNO> AP881229-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Crash-Suspects     12-29 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Suspects,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Extremists Among List Of Suspects In Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM MINEHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian extremists motivated by a desire to undermine PLO
chairman Yasser Arafat's peace initiative are among the possible
suspects in the downing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   Perhaps No. 1 on the list of suspects is Abu Nidal, followed by a
Palestinian faction headed by a rival to Arafat, pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslems, a group of Protestant extremists in Northern Ireland,
terrorists opposed to U.S. forces in Europe and even Mafia hitmen
for hire, terrorism experts say.
   ``Abu Nidal is the top suspect because he's the most capable of
undertaking a mission of this type,'' said Ian Geldard, director of
research at the private Institute for the Study of Terrorism in
London.
   Abu Nidal heads the Fatah Revolutionary Council, a Palestinian
guerrilla group opposed to Arafat's recognition of Israel and talks
with the United States. The group, allied with Libya, has been
blamed for hijackings, bombings and assassinations since it broke
with Arafat in 1976.
   ``Such an act of terrorism by Abu Nidal would be a message to the
world that Arafat cannot bring peace to the Middle East. ... It's a
message to the United States and a slap in the face for Yasser
Arafat,'' Geldard said.
   On Tuesday, Abu Nidal's group said from Beirut that it was
``painfully saddened'' by the Dec. 21 crash of Flight 103, which
originated in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Yonah Alexander, director of the Institute for Studies in
International Terrorism at the State University of New York, said
Abu Nidal does not always take responsibility for attacks his group
has been blamed for, including the 1986 attack on a synagogue that
killed 22 people in Istanbul, Turkey.
   Abu Nidal's guerrillas also were held responsible for
commandeering a Pan Am jumbo jet the day before in Karachi,
Pakistan. About 20 people were killed.
   One alleged member of the group, Mohammed Rashid, is wanted by
the United States in the 1982 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner flying
from Tokyo to Honolulu. One person was killed and 15 injured in the
attack.
   Rashid, 39, is serving a seven-month sentence for entering Greece
with a false passport. Greece's Supreme Court last month
indefinitely postponed a decision to extradite him to the United
States.
   Alexander also speculated that pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
terrorists may have planted the bomb.
   On Dec. 22, an anonymous caller to The Associated Press in London
claimed a pro-Iranian group called Guardians of the Islamic
Revolution was responsible. The caller said the motive was revenge
for the July downing of Iranian jetliner in the Persian Gulf by the
USS Vincennes, which the Navy said was a case of mistaken identity.
   But U.S. officials said the group was probably was not involved.
   Geldard said the group has claimed responsibility for just one
incident: an attack on a leading Iranian dissident in London in
September 1987.
   Last week, L. Paul Bremer, director of the State Department's
office of counterterrorism, said callers claimed two other groups
were responsible. He said they were Islamic Jihad, another
pro-Iranian Shiite group; and a group of Protestant extremists in
Northern Ireland whose name he did not have.
   Geldard said other Palestinian suspects include the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, led by Ahmed
Jibril, and the May 15th Organization led by Mohammad Amri.
   The Popular Front was the first terrorist organization to bomb an
airliner in flight when it attacked a Swiss airliner in 1970, he
said. Forty-seven people were killed.
   Geldard said the group is closely associated with Syria, whose
president, Hafez Assad, may ``feel that he has been marginalized
from the Middle East peace process.''
   Ariel Merari, a senior researcher in terrorism at Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies, said Jibril's
group often uses tourists and other unsuspecting carriers to plant
its bombs.
   He said a sophisticated bomb was found concealed in a radio when
13 members of the group were detained in October in raids in West
Germany.
   Geldard said the May 15th Organization was responsible for the
attack on a TWA airliner over the Mediterranean in April 1986 that
killed four peole and injured nine.
   Alexander said European terrorists, including the Red Army
Faction, may have staged the Pan Am attack to press their demands to
pull U.S. forces out of West Germany.
   Other possibile culprits include Mafia assassins ``recruited by
Libya or Syria to perpetrate this kind of crime,'' he said. ``They
use these soldiers of fortune, terrorists for hire, to erase any
footsteps.''
</TEXT>
