<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SinkingShip 6thLd-Writethru a0467 12-29 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sinking Ship, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0467,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cargo Ship Sinks In Rough Seas Off East Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf with two grafs and SUBS 7th graf, `Three of ...'
with two grafs to UPDATE with Coast Guard now saying that at least
two were rescued, sted three; the other crew member is missing at
sea.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 250-foot cargo ship with 11 people sank in rough
seas off the mid-Atlantic coast late Wednesday, leaving at least one
person missing after he slipped through his life jacket during a
rescue, authorities said.
   A merchant ship rescued two other crew members, the Coast Guard
said early Thursday.
   After searching the Atlantic for two hours, a Coast Guard jet
spotted a life raft with an unknown number of survivors. A
helicopter was dispatched to assist, said Coast Guard Petty Officer
Kenneth Arbogast.
   ``There were people on the raft waving flashlights, but we don't
know how many,'' he said.
   The crew of the Lloyd Bermuda abandoned ship in two rafts about 7
p.m. when the ship's load shifted, causing the vessel to sink about
160 miles south of Nantucket and 200 miles off New Jersey, said
Coast Guard Lt. j.g. Jonathan Trumble.
   Searchers were hampered by 40- to 45-mph winds and 20- to 25-foot
seas. Despite the heavy seas and poor visibility, Arbogast said the
crew's chances of survival were good.
   A merchant vessel, the Eagle, which was nearest to the Lloyd
Bermuda when the ship went down, was guided to one of the rafts by a
Coast Guard plane, said Coast Guard Lt. Paul Wolf.
   Two Lloyd Bermuda crew members were pulled aboard the Eagle, said
Wolf, who earlier reported that at least three were saved.
   ``The Eagle recovered two and in the process of trying to get the
third guy on board, he slipped through the life jacket and back into
the water and they can't see him now,'' Wolf said early Thursday. He
said didn't know about the others.
   Two helicopters, a jet from the Coast Guard air station on Cape
Cod and a C-130 aircraft from Elizabeth City, N.C., arrived in the
vicinity about 10:20 p.m. and immediately began the search. But the
helicopters ran low on fuel after about 90 minutes and returned to
Cape Cod, Trumble said.
   When the life raft was sighted about 12:15 a.m., another
helicopter was sent out, Arbogast said.
   The Lloyd Bermuda, registered in Cyprus, is a container ship that
makes a regular weekly passage from New York to Bermuda, Arbogast
said. He said it probably was carrying textiles, rubber and various
small goods.
   He said the Lloyd Bermuda's captain sent a distress signal at
7:10 p.m. and lost communication about five minutes later.
</TEXT>
