<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Nudes     12-29 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Nudes,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Models Angered by Nude Art Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Controversy over Beijing's first exhibition of
nude paintings has taken a new turn with models theatening to sue an
art institute for exposing them to the public eye.
   Reporters for the official China Youth News told The Associated
Press today that two of the six nude models of the Central Fine Arts
Institute will file suit because the institute did not obtain their
permission to allow a publishing house to print postcards and a book
of paintings sold at the exhibition.
   The 18-day exhibition at the China Art Gallery opened Dec. 22 and
has drawn crowds of 10,000 a day, many of them young men willing to
pay 10 times the usual admission price for their first look at
officially sanctioned nude art.
   The reporters said the models also stayed off the job Monday, a
claim denied by an official at the Fine Arts Institute.
   Chinese sources also said that the husband of one of the models
was seeking a divorce after learning his wife had been posing in the
nude without his knowledge. Another woman is also facing marital
difficulties because of the show, they said.
   The painting of nudes has traditionally had a very minor role in
Chinese art history, and the use of nude models was banned for a
long time under Communist China's puritanical commissars of art.
   Modeling in the nude was revived in 1984, but women models have
often been subject to social ostracism. The official press earlier
this year carried stories of a female model at the Nanking Institute
of Fine Arts who went insane after neighbors accused her of being a
prostitute.
   The English-language China Daily said Wednesday that one model
for the Beijing exhibition was so terrified her husband would find
out about her secret job that she kept him away from home so he
wouldn't see the opening day of the event on the television news.
   Models at the Fine Arts Institute are paid about five times what
an average Chinese worker earns per hour.
   The show, 128 paintings by 21 artists, has drawn high praise from
people who say it is a breakthrough in Chinese society's ability to
differentiate art from pornography.
   It has also been criticized by others who say the paintings
appeal to the prurient interests of young Chinese and are out of
step with Chinese artistic and social values.
</TEXT>
