<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-29 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges On Inflation Concern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against the Japanese yen today as
life insurance companies bought dollars actively ahead of the New
Year, pushing the U.S. currency up for the third consecutive day,
dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 126.03 yen, up 0.76 yen from Wednesday's
close and up 4.03 yen from its 1987 year-end closing. It opened
today at 125.42 yen.
   ``Life insurance companies are on stage,'' said Kaneo Ogino, a
dealer at Goldman, Sachs in Tokyo. He said other traders, reluctant
to make large moves ahead of the New Year, largely reacted to active
buying and selling by the life insurance firms.
   The dollar began the day on a strong note following overseas
gains due partly to intervention Wednesday in the market by the West
German Bundesbank, dealers said.
   The dollar ``strengthened after the market interpreted
Wednesday's intervention by the West German Bundesbank as a signal
of concern over inflation,'' said one dealer, speaking anonymously.
   The Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, reportedly sold
about $100 million in support of the West German mark on Wednesday,
he added.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to remain around the
current level for the remainder of the year due to current sentiment
toward the U.S. currency. It has gained 1.31 yen in the last three
days.
   ``I think it could go higher,'' Ogino said.
   The foreign exchange market in Tokyo will end 1988 trading with a
full day of business Friday and will resume trading on Jan. 4.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange closed for the year on Wednesday. It
will begin the New Year with a half-day session Jan. 4.
</TEXT>
