<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Crash-Security     12-29 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Security,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders U.S. Carriers To Tighten Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. carriers using British airports were ordered
by the government to tighten security just hours after it announced
that a bomb had downed Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland.
   The directive Wednesday said especially close attention should be
paid to the handling of baggage stored in aircraft cargo bays.
   It was issued by the Department of Transport after consultation
with the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration, which the British
agency said was ``also considering further security requirements for
U.S. airlines worldwide.''
   The decision on the same day investigators announced that a bomb
caused the Dec. 21 crash of Flight 103, killing all 259 people
aboard the Boeing 747 and at least 11 on the ground.
   Officials said evidence of the explosion, believed to have been
caused by hard-to-detect plastic explosives, was found in wreckage
from a cargo hold of the New York-bound jumbo jet.
   The Department of Transport statement said: ``We have reviewed
the security arrangements for flights by U.S. carriers in the light
of this incident, in consultation with the FAA, and are immediately
directing U.S. airlines to take additional measures in Britain, in
particular in relation to hold baggage.''
   A spokesman, who by custom was not identified, refused to
elaborate or give any details on the additional security measures it
wants taken.
   The announcement followed calls by British lawmakers and aviation
experts for increased security following the crash, Britain's worst
aviation disaster.
   ``The question that now has to be asked is how and where did a
bomb get on board?'' said David Wilshire, an aviation expert and
lawmaker from Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's governing
Conservative Party.
   Wilshire said there were three sources of passengers on the
flight: those who got on at Frankfurt where the flight originated;
those who joined at Heathrow Airport; and 12 in transit from other
flights.
   ``We are not therefore just talking about Heathrow or
Frankfurt,'' he said.
   The luggage of the 12 transit passengers went through the
Heathrow security system, but luggage belonging to the Frankfurt
passengers did not, although it was transferred under supervision of
Pan Am guards, said Wilshire.
   Opposition lawmakers have protested angrily that the Department
of Transport never informed British airports or travelers about a
U.S. warning of a terrorist threat to bomb a Pan Am airliner on the
Frankfurt-New York route in December.
   The government said that after receiving the threat, it had
reviewed security for U.S. flights at British airports _ which
already is higher than for some other destinations _ and decided it
was adequate.
</TEXT>
