<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Corruption     12-29 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Corruption,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Chun Ministers Arrested On Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former government ministers were
arrested today on corruption charges stemming from an investigation
into widespread abuses under former President Chun Doo-hwan,
officials said.
   Government prosecutors said Kim Chong-ho, the former construction
minister, was arrested on charges of taking bribes from construction
companies in the massive urban redevelopment projects in central
Seoul.
   Also arrested was Cha Kyu-hun, who once served as transportation
minister under Chun. Cha was charged with taking bribes from
businessmen for helping them obtain permits to build and operate
golf courses.
   Prosecutors are investigating allegations of widespread
corruption under Chun, including extortion of money from businesses,
diversion of government funds, influence peddling and forced
political donations. The National Assembly is investigating
corruption and human rights abuses under Chun.
   Some of Chun's relatives and associates have been arrested or
convicted of corruption, but it was the first arrest of former Chun
ministers. The former ministers are also ex-generals.
   There have been allegations the former president collected
illicit political donations through the licensing of golf courses.
Licenses to build golf courses are highly profitable and much
sought-after.
   Chun has denied any personal corruption, but has admitted he
managed political donations.
   A former general who took power with military backing in 1980,
Chun went into voluntary rural exile last month after apologizing to
the nation for abuses under his seven-year rule, which ended in
February.
   President Roh Tae-woo, a former general and once close ally of
Chun, has asked the nation to forgive his disgraced predecessor. Roh
opposes punishing Chun, but the opposition demands the former
president appear before the National Assembly's probe into his
government.
   Opposition parties say they will not agree to consider a pardon
for Chun until he appears before National Assembly. Roh says Chun
must be forgiven to promote national unity.
   Some opposition leaders hope nationwide furor over Chun and
revelations of abuses under his rule will hurt Roh's chances of
winning a referendum sometime next year on his rule.
   Roh promised to hold the referendum after the Seoul Olympics,
which ended in October. The government is identified with Chun in
the eyes of some South Koreans and Roh, who was elected a year ago
when two candidates split the opposition vote, faces a major
challenge in winning the referendum.
   The government has not said what Roh will do if he loses the
referendum. Roh would not be obliged to resign, but a defeat would
signal a lack of public confidence and the government would be under
pressure to call elections.
   No date has been set for the referendum, which is expected in the
spring.
</TEXT>
