<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-29 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little girl who called the 911
emergency telephone number to find out why Santa Claus missed her
home got a late Christmas delivery from some of his law-and-order
elves.
   The call from 8-year-old Brenda Cervantes came in Tuesday
afternoon, said police Sgt. Richard Grodt in this Los Angeles suburb.
   ``A little girl came on and said she wanted to know where Santa
was because mommy told her Santa didn't come to the house because he
was helping the Police Department,'' Grodt said.
   The girl, one of four children, made the call while her mother
was seeing a doctor, Grodt said.
   When police called back later to talk to the mother about her
daughter using the emergency telephone number they learned that the
family was financially burdened.
   The department raised $175. Gifts were purchased and delivered
Wednesday morning to the family's apartment, Grodt said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazelnut growers can't wait to get cracking on
a new promotion to make Oregon the only state with an official nut.
   Government and industry representatives said Wednesday that
Oregon's dominance in the nation's hazelnut production needs more
recognition.
   Oregon already has a state fish, rock, dance and flower. And
Richard Fritz, an assistant director of the state Agriculture
Department, said lawmakers in 1989 will be asked to designate the
hazelnut as Oregon's official nut.
   He said Oregon in 1987 produced 21,000 tons of hazelnuts, or 98
percent of the domestic harvest. Washington state grows the rest of
the domestic crop of hazelnuts, which are also called filberts,
Fritz said.
   The crop generated $20.5 million for Oregon's economy last year
and has yielded up to $38 million annually, he said.
   The Hazelnut Marketing Board in Portland says the state has more
than 1,100 hazelnut growers tending 3.2 million trees on 25,000
acres.
   Fritz said the designation of an official nut is likely to be the
brunt of jokes. But that will help increase recognition of the crop,
Fritz said.
   ``I'm sure it will bring smiles to some faces, but that's what
you want,'' he said.
</TEXT>
