<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Africans     12-29 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Africans,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Issue Appeal For Calm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials appealed today for an end to
the daily anti-black demonstrations that have followed a Christmas
Eve fight between African students and Chinese. The embattled
Africans remained sequestered.
   Two foreign reporters were barred from talking with the roughly
140 African students, who were being held under virtual house arrest
in a guest house 1{ hours by car outside this east-central city.
   The Africans, accompanied by students from Pakistan, Nepal,
Bangladesh, Japan and Western Europe, were not allowed to make
telephone calls or leave the guest house other than to return to
their universities in Nanking.
   Chinese police forced virtually all of Nanking's black African
students to the guest house Monday after thousands of Chinese
marched through the city's streets throwing rocks and destroying
property at the African students' dormitories.
   The Chinese youth chanted ``down with black devils'' and ``black
devils go home.''
   The Africans, fearing for their lives, tried to leave for
Beijing, but were stopped Sunday by armed police at Nanking's train
station.
   The clash and demonstrations are the latest in a series of
incidents between Chinese and the 1,500 African students invited
here to show Beijing's solidarity with the Third World.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, asked in Beijing whether
Nanking authorities had the right to hold the African students,
called ``groundless'' charges that the Africans were being held
illegally.
   Li added, ``The incident that has occurred in Nanking is an
isolated one having nothing to do with racial discrimination.''
   He said students from 40 African nations are studying in China
and, ``They always get on quite well with the Chinese students. Of
course, because of the difference of the customs of life, it is
sometimes unavoidable for some misunderstanding and even something
unpleasant.''
   Today, the only African student to leave the guest house and
return to Nanking said he wanted to leave China as soon as possible.
   ``I am very fearful,'' said a 23-year-old from Comoros who
identified himself only as Bourhane in an interview in his dormitory
at Nanking Polytechnical Institute. ``I won't leave this building.
Even seeing a Chinese outside the window makes me cold with fright.''
   In a front-page editorial, the Xinhua Daily, Nanking's largest
newspaper, urged students to stop demonstrating. Students, youths
and workers have been marching by the thousands since the Saturday
night fight between Chinese officials and students who refused to
register the names of their Chinese female companions they were
taking to a campus party.
   Eleven Chinese were reported injured, including one critically.
   On Wednesday, more than 2,000 youths jammed a major city
intersection as hundreds of police gathered nearby. Riot police
charged the crowd sporadically, hitting youths with rubber
truncheons.
   Other police placed demonstrators in an unmarked van.
   American witnesses said protests earlier this week were highly
racist in nature, with Chinese yelling, ``Kill the black devils!''
   In demonstrations Tuesday and Wednesday night, however, Chinese
began calling on the government to punish those involved in the
fight, ``according to the law.''
   ``In the beginning it was `down with the black devils,' but we're
not calling for that,'' said Lin Min, a 23-year-old Nanking
University student. ``We want matters to be settled according to
law.''
   At the guest house, at a chemical fiber factory to the northwest,
Chinese officials refused to let Western reporters talk with the
students.
</TEXT>
