<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BostonBusing     12-29 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boston Busing,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Adopts New School Enrollment Plan After Years Of Forced
Busing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 14 years of court-ordered busing that
triggered riots and white flight, the city has approved a school
assignment plan that allows parents to shop around for schools
closer to home.
   ``Clearly, it's time for change,'' school Superintendent Laval S.
Wilson said at a meeting Wednesday night in which the Boston School
Committee endorsed 10-1 the new student assignment plan in
principle. Two committee members did not vote.
   The panel stopped short of full approval. It ordered Wilson to
complete a review of the plan, which was devised by consultants, and
develop ways to put it into effect, at least in part, by September.
   The plan would split the school system into three zones of 14,000
parents each, with parents permitted to choose any school in their
zone. Students would be allowed to go to the school unless the
racial balance was upset. If a school was oversubscribed, a lottery
would be held, said School Committee President John Nucci.
   Backers say the plan would cut the long bus rides many students
now endure. They also hope the resulting inter-school competition
will spur improvements and lure back whites who fled to private
schools or the suburbs when the desegregation order was imposed in
1974.
   Critics say the plan won't work without more money and that it
would hurt some people, such as those without access to special
magnet schools. Boston school woes include rundown buildings, a
perennial budget crunch and a 40 percent high-school dropout rate.
   ``Nowhere in this plan do I see a commitment from this city to
pay for choice,'' said Jean McGuire, one of the two abstaining
committee members.
   Nucci said he doesn't believe money will make or break the plan.
   The 1974 desegregation order by U.S. District Judge W. Arthur
Garrity Jr., stemmed from a 1972 lawsuit filed by black parents who
said their children were receiving lower quality education than that
at predominantly white schools.
   In 1975, Garrity imposed the busing plan, triggering
rock-throwing protests.
   ``We've put that kind of violence and racial strain behind us,''
committeeman John P. Grady said. ``We want all of our children to
have the best education we can give them. As a city, we've grown
up.''
   When the lawsuit was filed, public schools served 96,000
students, 60 percent white. Today there are 59,000 students, but
only 24 percent are white, although whites comprise 60 percent of
Boston's population. Forty-eight percent of students are black, 19
percent are Hispanic and 8 percent are Asian.
   As a result, some schools effectively have been resegregated, and
nearly 90 percent of their pupils belong to minority groups, Grady
said.
   Garrity returned some control of the system to the committee in
1985. Two years later, a federal appeals court ruled that Boston
schools had integrated and that increased minority influence would
prevent a return to segregated classrooms.
   Garrity has since left the bench. His orders require only that a
racial balance be maintained, freeing the committee to come up with
a plan of its own.
   Any change in the student assignment plan would require approval
by the state Board of Education.
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn, who once was a fervent busing foe,
supports the plan. He has said that schools could tap into existing
funds to help fund it.
   Wilson said he did not know how much the new plan might cost, but
said he expected there would be a request for funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
