<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     12-29 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov's Wife Says Gorbachev OK'd Ethnic Peace Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and a close
confidant approved a trip to Armenia and Azerbaijan by Andrei
Sakharov to seek a compromise in the republics' bitter ethnic
dispute, the human rights activist's wife said today.
   Yelena Bonner said in a telephone interview that she and her
husband, winner of the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize, were in a five-member
delegation that visited the capitals of the southern republics and
Stepanakert, the largest city in the region at the center of the
dispute.
   She said the group returned to Moscow on Monday and may make
another trip to the region, which has been wracked by 10 months of
violence. Armenia demands annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh, a
predominantly Armenian enclave in Azerbaijan.
   Bonner said the mission had the backing of Gorbachev and
Alexander Yakovlev, the member of the ruling Politburo considered
closest to Gorbachev.
   Asked whether the officials or Sakharov, a 67-year-old nuclear
physicist, proposed the mission, and how the leaders had expressed
their backing, Bonner said: ``If he wanted to publicize this, he
would.''
   Gorbachev's approval of the Sakharov mission, however, is further
evidence of the gaining official stature of a man exiled to the
closed city of Gorky in 1980 for criticizing the Soviet intervention
in Afghanistan.
   In December 1986, Gorbachev telephoned Sakharov and said he could
return to Moscow. Sakharov was restored to good graces at the
Academy of Sciences and has been quoted frequently in the official
press.
   Bonner declined to say who the group met with during its trip or
what was discussed.
   The mission was aimed at resolving a protracted dispute over
control of Nagorno-Karabakh. The district has been part of
predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan since 1923. Armenians, who are
mostly Christian, insist that the region should be annexed to the
Armenian republic.
   The central government has refused to side with the Armenians,
and strikes, riots and demonstrations have plagued both republics
since February.
   Gorbachev has said the dispute threatens his reform effots and
has expressed anger at activists who continually raise the issue.
   During a visit to the United States earlier this month, Sakharov
proposed a compromise. He recommended that Nagorno-Karabhk be taken
out of Azerbaijani hands and placed temporarily under a central
administration. Sakharov has also called for U.N. observers to
investigate the ethnic unrest.
   In the Armenian capital of Yerevan, Vigen Sarkisyan, a journalist
for the Communist Party newspaper Kommunist, said Sakharov ``tried
to find compromises'' in a meeting with Armenian scientists at their
Academy of Sciences. None of the scientists familiar with the
meeting was available today, said an academy secretary.
   Rafael Popoyan, a former Armenian political prisoner and literary
critic, said by telephone from Yerevan that Sakharov also visited a
center for Armenians who fled Azerbaijan because of violence in
connection with the territorial dispute. At least 60 people have
been killed.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, asked about the
trip Wednesday, said, ``As far as I know he went there as a member
of a group of academics and scholars. That trip had nothing to do
with any authority whatsoever.''
   In Nagorno-Karabakh, the group met with the Kremlin's negotiator
in the ethnic dispute, Arkady Volsky, according to Popoyan.
   It appeared the group's ostensible reason for visiting the region
was to review conditions at a controversial nuclear power plant near
Yerevan, Popoyan said. The Soviet leadership has asked the Academy
of Sciences to study the power station.
   Many Armenians feared the plant was damaged in the Dec. 7
earthquake, which claimed about 55,000 lives and left a half million
people homeless.
   Soviet officials have repeatedly said the plant, which is built
on a fault, was not damaged. Nevertheless, Premier Nikolai I.
Ryzhkov says it will be closed in two years because of the
earthquake danger.
</TEXT>
