<DOCNO> AP881229-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DogFlap     12-29 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dog Flap,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Fate Of Bucky, A `Super Pit Bull Dog'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some say Bucky is mutt, others say it's a
``super pit bull.'' A judge's decision on the matter ultimately
could cost the dog its life under the state's new anti-vicious-dog
law.
   Lucas County Dog Warden Thomas Skeldon said Wednesday that Bucky
apparently is a ``super pit bull'' _ part pit bull, part Rhodesian
ridgeback _ making it extremely dangerous.
   A Rhodesian ridgeback is known as an African lion hound because
of its ability to hunt lions, Skeldon said. Bucky, he said, has the
aggressiveness of a ridgeback and the tenacity of a pit bull.
   Skeldon said mixed breeding is on the rise because some people
see it as a way of circumventing Ohio's new vicious-dog law, which
was passed in 1987 after a Dayton-area doctor was fatally attacked
by two pit bulls. The law singles out only pit bulls.
   ``We can foresee larger pit bulls coming into the pound, and pit
bull crosses with larger breeds. We've never seen one this large
before,'' Skeldon said about Bucky, who weighs about 90 pounds.
   ``We hear there's an attempt to cross pit bulls with breeds so
that it doesn't look like a pit bull, and there also is the tendency
to breed the dog with a larger animal. This is frightening,'' he
said.
   County deputy dog wardens on Dec. 15 confiscated Bucky, who is
licensed, after the dog was seen running loose from its yard, which
had an open gate.
   Ron Cannon, a deputy dog warden, said the pound was notified by
the U.S. Postal Service, which complained that the dog chased one a
letter carrier, who had to use a spray deterrent to keep the dog at
bay.
   The owner, Amy Adkins, was cited for having a vicious dog
improperly confined and for having no liability insurance.
   Her attorney, Christopher Park, disputes Skeldon's contentions
that Bucky is a pit bull.
   ``It is my understanding that it is not a pit bull. I know the
owners say it isn't,'' he said.
   He said talking about the case would be premature because of a
Jan. 12 pretrial conference in Municipal Court.
   If a judge determines the dog is a pit bull, he can order it
destroyed.
   The previous attack classifies Bucky as a dangerous dog under the
law, but the question remains whether he is a pit bull, the only
breed listed in the state statue as a vicious dog.
   Penalities for violations involving dangerous dogs and vicious
dogs are similar, but the law requires the owner of a vicious dog to
carry proof of liability insurance, which is often difficult to
obtain.
   Skeldon said he thinks the dog is a threat to the public.
   ``I am willing to euthanize the dog if that's the case. But if I
am told by the court to return the dog to its owners, I will comply
with that also,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
