<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Justice Minister, Now Embroiled In Scandal, Refuses To Step
Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs with Takeshita to retain minister,
details. Picks up 6th pvs, `Hasegawa, 76 ...' TRIMS to edit and
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said today that he
would keep his new justice minister despite the man's history of
donations from a company at the center of a stock scandal that
reaches deep into Japanese politics.
   Opposition parties demanded the resignation of Takashi Hasegawa
because he has admitted receiving donations for 12 years from
Recruit Co., which his office is probing for suspected bribery.
   Hasegawa was named to the justice portfolio on Tuesday as
Takeshita reshuffled his Cabinet and launched an ethics reform drive
in a bid to put the Recruit scandal behind him.
   But Takeshita's attempts to restore confidence in his government
seemed to be falling apart Wednesday night when the justice minister
confirmed he had taken money from Recruit.
   Takeshita, after consulting leaders of his Liberal Democratic
Party, said he would keep Hasegawa even though the new justice
minister had not been prudent in accepting the donations.
   ``But I fully trust that his ability will allow him to fulfill
his responsibility as justice minister,'' Takeshita said.
   Hasegawa, 76, told a news conference this afternoon he had
learned only Wednesday that Recruit Co. had been paying membership
dues since 1976 in an organization called Hakusenkai, which helps
finance Hasegawa's campaign and political activities.
   He said it was ``truly careless'' of him not to have known about
the donations, and he apologized.
   But, he continued, ``As justice minister I don't think this
matter will be an impediment. Accordingly, I will carry out my
duties as justice minister in the future.''
   Hasegawa had told reporters Tuesday he had no links to the
Recruit Co. ``and that's why I can appear before you'' as the new
justice minister.
   But news reports Wednesday night said Recruit had been giving
money to Hasegawa for 12 years, and that the last donation had been
in October, when the Recruit scandal was front-page news every day.
The donations totaled $46,000.
   The donations were legal and quite different from the
transactions in shares of a Recruit subsidiary called Recruit-Cosmos
that so far have brought the resignations of 17 politicians and
businessmen.
   Hasegawa told a late-night news conference Wednesday that he had
asked his aides, including his son, Akira, whether they had received
Recruit-Cosmos shares, and when they said no, he felt able to take
the justice portfolio. But he said he hadn't asked whether Recruit
had given him political donations.
   Mitsuhiro Kaneko, head of the Japan Communist Party's
secretariat, told a news conference that Hasegawa should resign and
``the prime minister's responsibility in appointing him should not
be escaped as well.''
   Leaders of the Socialist Party, the Democratic Socialist Party
and the Komeito (Clean Government Party), said Hasegawa was
inappropriate to serve as justice minister.
   Prosecutors have questioned Recruit founder Hiromasa Ezoe as well
as officials of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Co., Japan's giant
telephone utility, about business links between Recruit and the
utility.
   The scandal has been developing since last summer, when it
emerged that Ezoe had sold bargain-priced shares in Recruit-Cosmos
to influential politicians and business figures before the shares
were listed.
   Another Recruit subsidiary gave interest-free loans to finance
some of the transactions, and when the shares were listed in 1986,
the price rose sharply and the shareholders made hefty profits.
   The sales were not illegal under the securities law but they
appeared to be ethically dubious ways for a company to give
donations above the limit of one million yen ($8,000) a year, if not
bribes, to have the officials give advantages to Recruit, a huge
conglomerate based on employment services.
   The Recruit-Cosmos subsidiary deals in real estate.
   Some of the shareholders made over $80,000 in tax-free profits.
   Heading the list of those who have resigned in the scandal is
ex-Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, who repeatedly changed his
story of how an aide had used Miyazawa's name to buy Recruit-Cosmos
shares. His Dec. 9 resignation was interpreted as a sacrifice by
Takeshita.
   The most prominent casualty in the business world is Hisashi
Shinto, who resigned as chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
on Dec. 14. He had denied any involvement in an aide's purchase of
shares but some of money from the eventual sale went into Shinto's
personal bank account.
</TEXT>
