<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0632EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan     12-29 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Idles Most Of Sudan; Coalition's Junior Partner
Quits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's main international airport and
seaport were idled and its key cities paralyzed today by a general
strike in protest of the government-decreed price hikes in basic
commodities.
   Telephone and Telex operators in Cairo, Egypt, said all lines to
Khartoum were out of order, indicating telecommunications workers
had made good their threat to join the strike and cut Sudan's links
with the outside.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi called an emergency cabinet meeting
for today, and hinted he might give in to the strikers' demands.
   Meanwhile, the governing coalition's junior partner, the
Democratic Unionist Party, quit the government Wednesday in sympathy
with the strikers. The unionists dominate the powerful
2-million-member Sudan Workers' Trade Union Federation, which called
the strike.
   The Unionists had been under grass-roots pressure for some time
to quit the government because it failed to follow through with a
plan party leader Mohammed Osman Mirghani negotiated to end a
5{-year civil war in the south.
   Mirghani handed Mahdi resignations of the six unionist cabinet
members, including Foreign Minister Hussein Suleiman Salih.
   In a statement, the Unionists called for ``a national
reconciliation government'' to roll back the price increases,
implement the peace agreement and prepare for elections.
   Cairo's Middle East News Agency said Mahdi had called on the
Sudanese not to engage in ``destruction and rioting,'' adding, ``The
democratic system is capable through its institutions to take
decisions, then study them and reform them if necessary through
democratic means.''
   On Monday, Mahdi's financially strapped government increased the
price of sugar by 600 percent and cigarettes by 50 percent and
levied a 15 percent sales tax on all commodities.
   Ministers explained the increases were to finance subsidies as
well as salary increases of 50 percent to 500 percent decreed two
days earlier for public and private employees. The edict covered 1
million government workers.
   Newspapers and the official Sudan News Agency reported that many
of the country's major cities were at a standstill today.
   Reports from Port Sudan, the principal Red Sea port, said a
strike began last Saturday and that police had arrested several
people. The shutdown apparently was to protest the government's
alleged reneging on a promise to make pay increases retroactive to
July 1. They were made effective Dec. 1.
   On Wednesday, all union workers at Khartoum International Airport
left their posts.
   Officials in Cairo said flights that normally crossed Sudanese
airspace were being rerouted because of the lack of communications
with Khartoum air traffic controllers.
   Other major central Sudan towns _ Dongola, Atbara, Wad Medani and
Sennar _were reported in complete paralysis because of the work
stoppage.
   The general strike took hold after two days of demonstrations in
the capital. Thousands remained on the streets Wednesday night. One
group, as it passed the Ministry of Information, shouted: ``The head
of the prime minister is a public demand!''
   Similar unrest in March 1985 ended the 16-year authoritarian rule
of President Gaafar Nimeiri. His defense minister led a coup in
early April that began a process leading to the return of civilian
rule a year later.
</TEXT>
