<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-29 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased against most major currencies in
quiet early European trading today, but dealers said the outlook was
bullish. Gold prices fell.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.76 yen to a closing 126.03. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.77 yen.
   But the dollar was lower in Europe, except against the British
pound, which was quoted at $1.7887, cheaper for buyers than $1.7900
Wednesday.
   ``There was a bit of (a dollar) surplus in the market Wednesday
in New York which brought it down and seemed to have an effect all
the way into the beginning of the Tokyo day,'' said one London
trader.
   ``But the dollar seems to have come back pretty well from that.
It's looking very resilient.''
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7862 West German marks, down from 1.7960
   _1.5127 Swiss francs, down from 1.5177
   _6.1005 French francs, down from 6.1225
   _2.0220 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0255
   _1,317.50 Italian lire, down from 1,320.90
   _1.1940 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1963
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $413.75 a troy ounce,
down from $413.95 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $413.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $411 bid at noon, down from $412.25
bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.38 to close at a bid $416.07.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.06 a troy ounce,
down from Wednesday's $6.07.
</TEXT>
