<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Soviet-Jews     12-29 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Jews,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Will Open Up Soviet Jewish Grave Sites, Activist Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish cemeteries in the Soviet Union will be
preserved and visitors will have greater access to historical and
religious documents under a new agreement, a Jewish activist says.
   ``The Soviets have gone out of their way to work with us to
preserve many of the traditions that exist in the Soviet Union,''
City Councilman Noach Dear said Wednesday, a day after his return
from Moscow.
   Many Jewish leaders are buried in the Soviet Union, including the
founder of Hasidism, Rabbi Israel ben Eliezer, or the Ba'al Shem
Tov, who is buried in the Ukrainian town of Medzhibozh, said Dear,
co-chair of the private Joint Committee for the Preservation of
Jewish Heritage in the Soviet Union.
   ``The history of the Jews is basically in the Soviet Union at the
present time,'' said Dear.
   Under the agreement with Soviet officials, cities and historical
sites that had been closed to outsiders would be opened to Jews from
around the world, Dear announced Wednesday.
   The Soviets also agreed to assist visitors and preserve Jewish
grave sites and historical documents, Dear said.
   He said the agreement also would help keep Jewish life alive in
the Soviet Union as outsiders visit the burial sites and ``give a
little life to the Jewish community that exists in many of these
cities and towns which probably have never seen outside Jewish
leaders.''
   Dear said many Jewish cemeteries and grave sites are in poor
condition and that members of the committee would return soon to the
Soviet Union to catalogue the sites.
   ``These are significant steps in a world that was closed off to
us,'' said committee co-chair Aaron D. Twerski. ``As the doors open
up and as their attitudes become more positive we will be pressing
for additional rights for Soviet Jews.''
   Another sign of improvement in the way Jews are treated under
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's reforms is increased Soviet
Jewish emigration. In November, 2,284 Jews left the Soviet Union,
slightly lower than the 2,480 figure for October that marked the
highest monthly total since 1980 but still a high level. Soviet
authorities also have loosened restrictions on the teaching of
Hebrew and are planning a Jewish cultural center in Moscow.
</TEXT>
