<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 0656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AmazonEcologist     12-29 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amazon Ecologist,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Brothers Captured In Connection With Slaying Of Famed Ecologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sons of a cattle rancher who
favored clearing the Amazon for grazing have been arrested in
connection with the killing of an ecologist who fought to preserve
the jungle, police say.
   Brothers Aleci and Oloci Alves da Silva were captured after a gun
battle with police Tuesday night on their family ranch in Xapuri,
the jungle town where Francisco Mendes was gunned down last week,
Deputy Minister of Justice Luis Fernando Eichenberg said. Oloci was
wounded in the shootout.
   The two are sons of Darly Alves da Silva, a rancher who was angry
over Mendes' campaign to save the rain forest. Mendes had said the
rancher threatened to kill him.
   The internationally known ecologist, who organized jungle workers
to try to stop destruction of the rain forest by plantation owners,
was fatally shot Thursday outside his home in Xapuri, 2,650 miles
northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   The issue of how to develop the Amazon jungle, an expanse of rain
forest about two-thirds the size of the continental United States,
has often erupted in violent conflicts between landowners, landless
peasants, politicians, clergymen and ecologists who defend the
peasants.
   In Brazil, about 4 percent of the population owns half of the
arable land.
   Cattle ranchers, eager to clear forest lands for grazing, often
order the killings of squatters and ecologists who oppose them.
   Some experts say uncontrolled burning of the Amazon is
aggravating the greenhouse effect _ atmospheric warming caused by
the buildup of carbon dioxide.
   Federal police were still looking for five other members of the
rancher's family in connection with Mendes' death, Eichenberg said.
   A third son, 21-year-old Darcy Pereira, turned himself in to
police Monday and claimed he hired someone to kill Mendes. Officials
said they did not believe the confession.
   ``Our impression is that Darcy's confession is a smoke screen,''
said Eichenberg. ``We won't stop our search until we get to his
boss.''
   On Wednesday, police began a 48-hour operation to confiscate
illegal weapons in the region in an effort to halt widespread
violence in the western Amazon.
   Two years ago, federal police carried out a similar campaign in
the Parrot's Beak region of Brazil, a rural area 1,800 miles north
of Rio torn by land disputes.
   They set up roadblocks, searched vehicles, raided ranches and
confiscated hundreds of unregistered arms, but the violence
continued unchecked.
   Violent conflicts over land have increased since President Jose
Sarney, the first civilian president since a 21-year military regime
ended in 1985, announced a sweeping agrarian reform program.
   Since 1985, about 250 deaths a year have resulted from land
conflicts. In 1971, just 20 people were killed in 109 battles,
according to government figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
