<2ND_LINE>PM-Sinking Ship, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0538,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cargo Ship Sinks; Three Saved, One Dead, Seven Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with another man spotted in water,
to
correct times of rescues, to ADD name and condition of one crewman,
further background on ship; No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers plucked four seamen from the stormy
Atlantic after their 250-foot cargo ship sank, but one died and
seven others were missing today, including a crewman who slipped
through his life jacket, authorities said.
   An aircraft flying over the area spotted one of the men on a life
raft, but rescuers found the raft empty when they reached it.
Rescuers later spotted another man in the water, but they were
unsure whether he was alive.
   The rescue effort was hampered by heavy rains, 40- to 45-mph
winds and 20- to 25-foot seas, the Coast Guard said.
   The 11-member crew abandoned the Lloyd Bermuda in two rafts after
the ship's load shifted during the storm Wednesday night, said Coast
Guard Lt. j.g. Jonathan Trumble. The ship sank about 160 miles south
of Nantucket and 200 miles east of New Jersey, Trumble said.
   The captain sent a distress signal at 7:10 p.m. and lost
communication about five minutes later, the Coast Guard said.
   A merchant vessel, the Eagle, which was nearest to the Lloyd
Bermuda when it went down, was guided to one of the rafts by a Coast
Guard plane, said Coast Guard Lt. Paul Wolf.
   Two Lloyd Bermuda crew members were pulled aboard the Eagle about
1:45 a.m. today, but a third was lost at sea during a rescue
attempt, he said.
   ``The Eagle recovered two and in the process of trying to get the
third guy on board, he slipped through the life jacket and back into
the water and they can't see him now,'' he said.
   The two men aboard the Eagle were conscious and alert, Wolf said.
They were treated for mild hypothermia but were otherwise unharmed.
Their identities were not released.
   About 4 a.m., Coast Guard frogmen jumped from a helicopter and
saved two men who were drifting without rafts in the water, Wolf
said.
   They were taken by helicopter to Falmouth Hospital, where nursing
supervisor Kathy Correia said one was dead on arrival at about 6:45
a.m., apparently of hypothermia. The other, identified as Dario
Macio-Lopez, 35, was in fair condition in the intensive care unit.
   An aircraft flying over the area spotted a man on a life raft
about 7:30 a.m., but rescuers later found the raft empty, Chief
Petty Officer Bill Ball. Rescuers saw another man in the water but
could not reach him because of rough seas.
   Two helicopters, a jet from the Coast Guard air station on Cape
Cod and a C-130 aircraft from Elizabeth City, N.C., began searching
for survivors late Wednesday. But the helicopters ran low on fuel
after about 90 minutes and returned to Cape Cod, Trumble said.
   Another C-130 was dispatched from Cape Cod shortly after the
first two crew members were rescued.
   The Lloyd Bermuda, registered in Cyprus, is a container ship that
makes a regular weekly run from Port Elizabeth, N.J., to Bermuda,
Arbogast said. It was believed to be carrying general cargo,
including food and building materials, and is one of the three main
supply vessels to the island nation off North Carolina.
   The ship's captain was American, while the crew was mostly from
Central America, said John W. Moore of the Meyer Agencies Ltd. in
Hamilton, Bermuda, the ship's agent.
</TEXT>
