<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BaseClosings-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0583 12-29 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Base Closings Announcements Greeted with Resignation, Dire
Predictions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 16th graf, `I'm sure...,' to UPDATE with
reax from South Carolina, where one base was recommended for
expansion. Pickup 17th graf `Although the...' CORRECTS spelling of
Fort Devens in penultimate graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Base Closings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Military base spokesmen today reacted with a stiff upper lip to a
government commission's cost-cutting proposal to close 86 bases
nationwide, but civilians decried the effects the closings would
have on their economies.
   Politicians declared victory in areas where bases were spared by
the measure, which would save an estimated $5.6 billion over 20
years.
   ``We're not going to fight with anybody. It's not our decision.
Things are going to fall where they're going to fall,'' said Lt.
Col. Ron Yacovelli, a spokesman for Fort Sheridan outside Chicago.
   Fort Sheridan serves as headquarters for the 4th U.S. Army, which
includes reservists in Illinois, Indiana, Ohio, Michigan, Wisconsin,
Iowa and Minnesota. It employs about 1,500 civilians and 1,500
military personnel.
   ``The decision has been made and like any decision, we'll press
on and carry it out,'' said Maj. Dave Sutherlin, a spokesman for
Chanute Base, about 15 miles north of Champaign, Ill. ``I want to
stress that it's only a recommendation. ... We're not going to shut
our gates tomorrow.''
   The base employs about 7,000 people in Rantoul, a town of 20,000.
   Plans to shut down the Presidio in San Francisco, where the Sixth
Army is headquartered, was a surprise to Mayor Art Agnos' office.
   ``What we heard was that it will close partially,'' said mayoral
spokeswoman Eileen Maloney. She said the announcement will have to
be studied and run through ``a number cruncher'' before the mayor
would be ready to comment on what it means to the city in terms of
lost jobs and money.
   ``It will depend, I guess, on how many people will be gored by
this,'' she said. ``We're not pleased it's closing. (Agnos) has
already signed onto the Committee to Save the Presidio.''
   In addition to the complete closure of 86 bases, 59 others were
slated for partial closing or realignment.
   Among those was Fort Dix, New Jersey's largest military base. The
panel recommended that it be reduced to ``semi-active status'' for
an annual savings of $84.5 million. The base, now one of the Army's
eight basic-training posts, would lose that function entirely.
   The announcement was bad news for the Pemberton Township Board of
Education, whose schools are attended by children of Fort Dix's
military personnel.
   Mark Cowell, business administrator for the district, said
children of base personnel comprise 38 percent of its student body.
   ``We are in the middle of adding an addition to our high school
because they have been expanding the base,'' he said.
   A historic fort built to protect stagecoach travelers from Indian
attack also fell under the ax. Fort Douglas, built in 1862 in the
foothills of Utah's Wasatch Mountains, had long been criticized by
congressional foes as contributing little to national defense.
   ``I'm sure there's going to be people disappointed who work
here,'' said Army Maj. Bill Auer, the fort's spokesman. ``One of the
things we have to contend with is 44 of our buildings here are also
registered national historic landmarks.''
   Not all the news from the report was bad. Several communities
were elated by the panel's recommendation to expand several
facilities.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., welcomed the proposal to add 661
military and 126 civilian personnel at Fort Jackson, the Army base
in Columbia.
   ``Fort Jackson is one of our nation's finest and most vital
military training facilities and I am enthusiastic about the
increase of its role in providing for our nation's defense,'' he
said.
   Although the commission report spelled doom for the Philadelphia
Naval Hospital, which the Navy had long anticipated closing, the
announcement brought relief to supporters of the Philadelphia Naval
Shipyard.
   ``We won,'' said U.S. Rep. Thomas Foglietta, standing with
workers at the gate of the Navy base and shipyard, which employs
about 8,500 people.
   ``We are going to stay open,'' he said. ``I am happy. In fact I
am thrilled the Philadelphia Naval Base and Naval shipyard is not on
the list of defense facilities that are to be closed around the
country. The workers won. This is their victory.''
   Residents of Ayer, Mass., site of Fort Devens, New England's only
Army base, also rejoiced at being spared.
   ``It's the best news we could have for a New Year's,'' said Ed
Kelley, owner of a local card shop and a director of the town's
chamber of commerce. ``It's the life and blood of the town. It would
have been devastating if Fort Devens had been closed.''
</TEXT>
