<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     12-29 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Officials Cool to Sakharov Mediation in Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Armenian official on Thursday dismissed the
mediation effort by human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov in the
bloody Caucasus ethnic dispute, saying authorities can settle the
matter on their own.
   ``I think we have sufficient help and advice from the government
and party on the Karabakh issue,'' said Vardges Artsruny, a deputy
premier of the Armenian republic, when asked if officials welcomed
Sakharov's mission.
   Sakharov, a 67-year-old physicist and Nobel Peace Prize winner,
returned Monday from a trip to Armenia and the neighboring republic
with which it is feuding, Azerbaijan. Armenians familiar with the
mission said it was aimed at seeking a compromise in the
10-month-old rift over control of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Armenians began strikes and demonstrations in February to press
their demand that the territory, part of Azerbaijan since 1923, be
incorporated into the Armenian republic. Azerbaijanis have refused
to cede the district, and Moscow authorities have sided with them.
Clashes between Armenians and Azerbaijanis over the dispute have
left at least 60 people dead.
   Bonner, who accompanied Sakharov on the trip with three other
people she declined to identify, said President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
and his closest ally, Alexander Yakovlev, a member of the ruling
Politburo, had approved the trip.
   She said the group visited the Armenian capital of Yerevan, the
Azerbaijani capital of Baku, and Stepanakert, the main city of
Nagorno-Karabakh, but declined to say whom they met or exactly what
they discussed.
   Asked whether the officials or Sakharov proposed the mission, and
how the leaders had expressed their backing, Bonner said: ``If he
wanted to publicize this, he would.''
   Artsruny, the deputy premier, was asked about the Sakharov
mission in a television hookup in which Moscow-based reporters put
questions to Armenian officials in Yerevan. He said Sakharov's help
was not needed and then lashed out at journalists who raised the
Nagorno-Karabakh issue while Armenia was suffering from the Dec. 7
earthquake.
   Another deputy premier, Yuri Hojamiryan, said he met with
Sakharov in Yerevan but that they only discussed earthquake relief
efforts, not the ethnic dispute.
   Also in the news conference, Armenia's Interior Minister, Usik
Arutunyan, said his forces had restored order to the republic and
that there had been ``no conflicts stemming from racism'' recently.
   Authorities imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew and sent tanks and
troops into many parts of Armenia and Azerbaijan late last month to
quell ethnic unrest. Several Armenian political activists have been
arrested.
   Gorbachev has said the ethnic dispute threatens his reform
program known as perestroika and has expressed anger at activists
who continually raise the issue.
   During a visit to the United States earlier this month, Sakharov
recommended the disputed territory be taken out of Azerbaijan's
hands and placed temporarily under a central administration.
Sakharov also called for United Nations observers to investigate the
ethnic unrest.
   Gorbachev's approval of the mission reflects Sakharov's improving
official standing.
   Sakharov won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his human rights
campaigning, but was exiled to the city of Gorky in 1980 for
criticizing the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan. In December
1986, Gorbachev telephoned Sakharov and said he could return to
Moscow. He was restored to good graces at the Academy of Sciences
and has been quoted frequently in the press.
</TEXT>
