<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Murder-Suicide     12-29 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder-Suicide,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife Killed By Husband in Second Murder-Suicide This Week on Long
Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLIP, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was shot to death by her estranged
husband Thursday as she ran from him with her 2-year-old daughter in
her arms, police said. The man then killed himself in Long Island's
second murder-suicide this week.
   In both cases, the woman was killed despite a court order of
protection.
   In Thursday's shooting, Elizabeth Croff, 30, of Central Islip,
had dropped her mother off at work and started to drive away when
her husband, William Croff, pulled up behind and rammed her car,
said Suffolk County police Officer Mark Ryan.
   Croff then jumped out with a shotgun and began firing at his
wife, who fled down the street carrying their daughter, Bernadette.
The volley hit the woman in the head, killing her, and struck the
child in the hip, police said.
   Croff returned to his car and shot himself in the head, Ryan said.
   The toddler, who also suffered cuts, probably when the mother
fell, was in stable condition at Southside Hospital in Bay Shore,
authorities said. No vital organs were damaged, said hospital
spokesman Clifford Steward.
   Police said Mrs. Croff had obtained a protection order against
her husband, but they had no information on when it was issued or
why.
   On Monday, Joseph Grohoski, 34, kicked in the door to his
estranged wife's home in Cutchogue, police said. Grohoski chased his
wife, Lydia, to the basement, where he killed her with a shotgun
blast to the head.
   He then killed himself while their 2-year-old son sat in the
kitchen.
   Police said Mrs. Grohoski obtained a protection order after he
threatened her Dec. 2.
</TEXT>
