<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DRUMMOND ISLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domino's Pizza owner Tom Monaghan
wants to help the 500 residents of this bucolic island make some
dough, and he's not just talking pizza.
   Monaghan, who owns a vacation home and corporate retreat on the
island, plans to create a bank to serve residents, a spokesman said.
The island has a credit union but no commercial bank, aide Dick
Brunvand said Wednesday.
   The entrepreneur will apply next month with the state and hopes
to open the bank by mid-1989, Brunvand said. Monaghan, who also owns
the Detroit Tigers baseball team, expects to be chairman of the bank.
   Monaghan owns 1,700 acres on the island off the eastern tip of
Michigan's Upper Peninsula. The land is mainly used as a vacation
spot for Domino's employees and includes a golf course and compound
for three orphaned bear cubs.
   The pizza magnate is dredging the harbor to make room for his
sailing ship, the Domino Effect.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight champion Mike Tyson's former trainer
was arrested after hitting another car and scuffling with two police
officers, police said.
   Kevin Rooney was charged with drunken driving, leaving the scene
of an accident and resisting arrest following the fender-bender
Wednesday night, said Sgt. Peter Sweeney, a police spokesman. No one
was injured in the accident.
   Rooney kept going after hitting the other car, but the driver
pointed out Rooney's car, which was stopped in traffic, to police,
authorities said.
   Rooney scuffled with the officers as they arrested him, Sweeney
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moved on the financial wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tim Matheson, one of the actors who starred in
the hit movie ``Animal House,'' is among a group of investors that
served notice it may seek control of struggling National Lampoon
Inc., which made the film.
   Matheson, who played Otter in the 1978 movie, is part of
Grodnik@Matheson Co., a Los Angeles-based independent production
company said to represent about one-fifth of the shares of publicly
traded National Lampoon.
   The group may seek to take over the New York-based magazine and
film company, according to documents filed this week with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   National Lampoon Chairman Matty Simmons said Matheson and two
other individuals of the group have told him they may not pursue a
takeover if they are given representation on the board.
   Simmons said National Lampoon is recovering from a four-year
slump that he blamed in part on opposition from fundamentalist
religious groups and the Justice Department's Commission on
Pornography.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Armand Hammer, well known for
his good works, wants a pardon for a black mark on his record:
conviction on three charges of making secret contributions to a
presidential campaign.
   Hammer pleaded guilty in 1976 to the misdemeanors during
President Nixon's 1972 re-election campaign. He was fined $3,000 and
placed on a year's probation.
   He has spent several years seeking a pardon and has approached
President Reagan about it, the Los Angeles Times reported Thursday.
   The 90-year-old head of Occidental Petroleum Inc. has donated
millions of dollars to cancer research and other charities and has
used his contacts with the Soviet Union to promote world peace.
</TEXT>
