<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Romero     12-29 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Romero,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Criticizes Ending Of Romero Case In El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department criticized the Supreme
Court of El Salvador on Thursday for deciding against the
extradition of a former air force captain who was arrested last year
in Miami in the investigation of the 1980 assassination of
Archbishop Oscar Romero.
   The Salvadoran government withdrew its request for the
extradition of Alvaro Saravia after the Central American country's
court ruled last week there were no grounds for arresting him on
charges he had violated his visa and that the extradition request
itself was illegal.
   Romero, an outspoken critic of rightist death squads, was killed
March 24, 1980, while saying Mass. In November 1987, President Jose
Napoleon Duarte, who is opposed by rightist political forces in El
Salvador, released testimony by the driver of the getaway car that
he worked for Saravia.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the United
States was concerned whether Salvadoran judicial authorities were
vigorously pursuing human rights cases regardless of the political
persuasion of violators.
   ``We are still seeking a full explanation of the implications of
this decision by the Salvadoran court,'' she said. ``Our embassy
will indicate our strong disatisfaction with the decision to the
Salvadoran government.''
   The Salvadoran government said Wednesday the case would remain
unresolved because of the ruling.
</TEXT>
