<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Africans Bjt   12-29 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Africans, Bjt,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Likely To Punish African Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese officials said Thursday they
probably would punish at least seven African students for a brawl
with Chinese workers, students and teachers that set off days of
anti-black demonstrations.
   They said no Chinese students would be punished for participating
in the clash and subsequent demonstrations, or for sacking the rooms
of some African students.
   ``We know who the Africans are that carried out the beating,''
said Yang Ruiju, president of Hehai University where the clash took
place. ``The African students did this in a planned way.''
   But the Chinese students ``demonstrated out of anger. They didn't
hurt anybody so none of them will be punished,'' Yang said in an
interview.
   About 140 African students, joined by about a dozen other foreign
students, remained in isolation at a guest house about a 90-minute
drive outside of this eastern China city. Yang said the seven
``suspects'' were at the guest house.
   The students have been at the house since Monday night, when
Chinese police forced them there from the Nanking train station. The
students wanted to travel to Beijing because they fear for their
safety.
   Officials said Thursday that all the students except the seven or
eight Africans involved in the fracas could leave the guest house as
long as they returned to their schools in Nanking.
   Two Western reporters who went to the guest house Thursday were
refused permission to speak with the students. Chinese officials at
the Jiangsu provincial foreign affairs office also refused to let
reporters talk with the students.
   Young Chinese took to the streets for the fifth straight day
since Saturday, when 11 Chinese and two Africans were injured in the
Hehai clash.
   A crowd of about 800, well below the figure on previous nights,
gathered at Gulou, an old drum tower on a main Nanking intersection.
Some 600 later marched peacefully from there to the city center,
escorted by hundreds of police.
   The students again called on the government to deal with the
Hehai clash ``according to law.''
   Earlier demonstrations on Sunday and Monday were markedly racist
in tone, with youths chanting ``Down with black devils!'' and
``Black devils go home!''
   Some Chinese students also protested preferential conditions
given to foreign students.
   On Wednesday night, riot police wielding clubs charged a crowd of
thousands. Officers hit youths and drove some off in unmarked vans.
   Thursday's Xinhua Daily, the city's main paper, called for peace
in the streets. The front-page editorial also called for Chinese to
be friendly to foreigners.
   In the interview, Yang claimed the African students at Hehai
planned the bloodshed.
   He said the Africans started the fight because they were unhappy
about a wall that was being built around their two dormitories at
the university. If the wall was erected, he said, the Africans
``couldn't play with girls freely.''
   He also accused the African students of consorting with
prostitutes.
   African students, mostly men who spend up to six years in China,
say their social contacts with Chinese women frequently are the
catalyst for racial confrontations. Although China has close
relations with most black African states, deep-seated prejudices
against blacks are common among Chinese, they say.
   Huang Jie, division chief of the Jiangsu provincial foreign
affairs office in Nanking, said no arrests have been made so far.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing stressed at a weekly news
briefing that ``the incident that has occurred in Nanking is an
isolated one having nothing to do with racial discrimination.''
   He said charges the Africans are being illegally held were
``groundless.''
   On Thursday, the only African student to leave the guest house
and return to Nanking said he was afraid for his life and wanted to
leave China as soon as possible.
   ``I am very fearful,'' said a 23-year-old from the Comoro Islands
in the Indian Ocean.
   ``I won't leave this building. Even seeing a Chinese outside the
window makes me cold with fright,'' said the student, who identified
himself only as Bourhane and spoke in an interview at Nanking
Polytechnical Institute.
   At the guest house, located at a chemical fiber factory northwest
of the city, Chinese officials refused to let two Western reporters
talk with the students.
</TEXT>
