<DOCNO> AP881229-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1416EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan Bjt   12-29 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan, Bjt,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Reportedly Gives in to Strikes, Rolls Back Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government rolled back huge price
increases Thursday after a general strike cut off communications,
shut down a main airport and seaport and virtually paralyzed major
cities, reports said.
   Police fired on anti-government demonstrators in Khartoum who
continued to press for greater reforms after hearing that the
government had agreed to cut prices, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
   In Baghdad, the official Iraq News Agency transmitted a report
from Khartoum that said ``intensified'' shooting flared up shortly
after dark, ``especially near the headquarters of the council of
ministers.''
   There was no word on casualties in either incident, the first
reported violence in three days of protests in this financially
strapped northeast African country.
   The demonstrators who were fired on reportedly were demanding
that in addition to the economic concessions, the government work
toward cementing a tentative plan to end a 5{-year civil war in
southern Sudan.
   The peace pact was negotiated by John Garang, leader of the rebel
forces, and the leader of the Democratic Unionist Party.
   The party, junior partner in the ruling coalition, dominates the
2 million-member Sudan Workers' Trade Union Federation, which
organized Thursday's general strike. The party announced on
Wednesday it was resigning from the government in sympathy with the
strikers.
   The reported price rollback was decided in an emergency cabinet
session chaired by Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi. It canceled increases
imposed Monday of 600 percent for sugar and 50 percent for
cigarettes and a 15 percent sales tax for all commodities.
   A statement reported by the Middle East News Agency reaffirmed
salary increases of up to 500 percent that the government had
decreed on Saturday. It also said people immediately could buy sugar
at old prices and that subsidies would be applied to sorghum,
Sudan's staple food.
   The government's had said he it needed the price increases to
finance the salary increases and subsidy program.
   The Egyptian agency also quoted Abdullah Mohammed Ahmed, the
information minister, as saying work would begin ``in the coming
hours'' on forming a new government in light of the Democratic
Unionists' pullout.
   The Sudan News Agency quoted Information Minister Abdullah
Mohammed Ahmed, the government's chief spokesman, as promising
immediate steps to form a new Cabinet.
   Ahmed presumably meant Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi would keep his
post, since his Umma Party has the largest number of parliamentary
seats.
   Meanwhile, Sudanese newspapers and the Sudan News Agency reported
many of the country's major cities were at a standstill Thursday.
   Communications were cut at midmorning, the time designated for
the strike, apparently the result of telecommunications workers
walking off their jobs.
   Coupled with the shutdown of Khartoum International Airport and
Port Sudan, the country's main Red Sea port, Sudan was virtually
isolated. Aircraft that normally fly over Sudan were being rerouted
because of the lack of radio contact with Khartoum air traffic
controllers.
   The trouble is similar to widespread unrest over high prices that
brought down former dictator Gaafar Nimeiri in 1985 after 16 years
in power. Then, however, powerful professional associations of
doctors and lawyers were in the forefront rather than workers and
students leading the current protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
