<DOCNO> AP881229-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HairControversy     12-29 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hair Controversy,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy's Hair Dispute Nets Fine For Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who refused to force his son to cut his hair
to bring the teen-ager into compliance with a high school's grooming
code has been convicted of violating the state's compulsory school
attendance law.
   Jurors deliberated about 45 minutes Wednesday before convicting
Dub Wilkinson of the misdemeanor and fining him $25, the maximum.
   With court costs, Wilkinson, 48, will have to pay $100.
   Wilkinson, who said he will appeal, was found guilty of not
requiring his 14-year-old son Travis to attend Northbrook Senior
High School.
   Travis and his brother Brian, 16, have not attended class since
Oct. 28, when they were barred for failing to adhere to the school
district's dress code, which prohibits boys from having hair that
falls below their shoulders.
   Wilkinson had said it was his sons' right to wear their hair the
way they wanted. His position remained unchanged after the verdict.
   ``I will not ask my sons to cut their hair. That is their
decision,'' he said.
   ``My dad wouldn't keep me from school,'' Travis said Wednesday.
``I love him.''
   Texas' compulsory attendance law only applies through the
academic year a student turns 16, so Brian's non-attendance was not
part of the charges against his father.
   During the two-day trial, Wilkinson's attorney, Darrell
McAlexander, argued that the hair-length rule is enforced
selectively. He also questioned its purpose and said it held the
potential for sexual discrimination.
   Assistant District Attorney David Furlow said the verdict is a
reminder to students that the school ``is not a Burger King _ Travis
can't go there and demand he have it his own way.''
   District Superintendent Hal Guthrie and Principal James King said
the boys still must cut their hair before they are admitted to class.
</TEXT>
