<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-29 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAHOPAC, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to pronouncing the name of
this tiny community, the official ruling is hold the ``MAY-o.''
   The Town Board of Carmel _ which includes the hamlet of Mahopac _
has ruled that the proper pronunciation is Mah-HO-pak, rather than
MAY-o-pak.
   The vote Tuesday night was 3-2, reflecting the division on the
long-debated issue in this community about 35 miles north of New
York City.
   Carmel Supervisor Richard Othmer said that in his experience _
which includes going door-to-door in the past 10 elections _ half
the residents call the community Mah-HO-pak and half said MAY-o-pak.
   Surveys conducted in 1986 came to opposite conclusions _ one
found 74 percent saying MAY-o-pac, and another found Mah-HO-pac
preferred 113 to 23.
   The name is believed to stem from an American Indian word, but
its original pronunciation is lost in history.
   Dorothy Jewell of the Carmel Historical Society presented each
board member at the meeting with a copy of the March 13, 1929, issue
of the old Lake Mahopac weekly, which bears the headline
``Mah-HO-pak is the Right Pronunciation.''
   Thomas Carey, a lifelong Mahopac resident who is the town
comptroller, seconded that pronunciation. He pointed out that the
Mahopac high school song includes the phrase ``High above the
Mah-HO-pak's waters.''
   ``It's the out-of-towners _ those city folk _ who moved in over
the years and changed the name of the community,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As part of its centennial celebration,
the Tournament of Roses Parade will feature a first Monday, a
wedding aboard one of the flower-studded floats.
   Carie Humphries, 21, and Ron Simms, 23, will exchange vows aboard
the Romance in California float before the millions who watch the
televised New Year's Day spectacle.
   Humphries, a student at California State University Long Beach,
and Simms, a student at the Los Angeles College of Chiropractic in
Whittier, were chosen among entrants in the Search for the Most
Romantic Couple in Southern California contest.
   Officials estimate that the 60 floats, 22 musical units and more
than 250 equestrians will be viewed by 300 million people worldwide,
about 1 million of them at the parade site.
   The grand marshal for the 100th Tournament of Roses parade is
Shirley Temple Black. Mrs. Black, 60, also was grand marshal in
1939, when she was the child star of such classics as ``Heidi'' and
``Curly Top.''
   ``I can't imagine a more appropriate person to symbolize the
tradition and history of the Tournament than Shirley Temple Black,''
said John H. Biggar III, president of the Tournament of Roses
Association.
</TEXT>
