<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeamstersLawsuit     12-29 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters Lawsuit,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Files Suit Seeking New Election In Teamster Official's
Local</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has filed a lawsuit seeking to void
the 1987 re-election of Teamsters secretary-treasurer Weldon L.
Mathis as president of his Atlanta local, saying the voting may have
been rigged.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court Wednesday by the U.S. Justice
Department, seeks to invalidate Mathis' re-election as president of
Local 728 and the election of his son, W. Lamar Mathis Jr., and
other local officers.
   It also asks that a new election be conducted under federal
supervision.
   The elder Mathis, general secretary-treasurer of the
1.3-million-member Teamsters union, lost his bid to succeed Jackie
Presser as Teamsters president in July. The lawsuit would not affect
his position in the international.
   He resigned as Local 728 president in June after 21 years on the
job and created Local 928. He then transferred more than half of
Local 728's 8,000 members to the new local and appointed his son to
head it.
   Another son and a nice also joined Local 728, the son as business
agent.
   Two groups of candidates who ran against the Mathis slate in 1987
filed petitions with the Labor Department this year challenging the
election.
   They also accused the elder Mathis of forming the new local to
protect his relatives' jobs if he lost his re-election bid.
   If a federal judge grants the government's request, Local 728
officers appointed by the elder Mathis must stand for re-election.
   ``It's long overdue that we get a fair election,'' said Donald S.
Scott, who ran against Mathis in the disputed election. He said he
would run again.
   Weldon Mathis and Lamar Mathis were on vacation and unavailable
for comment, their secretaries said.
</TEXT>
