<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Infiltration     12-29 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Infiltration,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Three Infiltrators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed three
infiltrators who crossed the border from Egypt, and mounted searches
Thursday in the Negev Desert for a fourth man who escaped, a
military spokesman said.
   It was not immediately clear if the infiltration Wednesday
involved guerrillas or possibly smugglers. The army withheld reports
of the incident until Thursday, apparently to prevent panic among
the public.
   An army spokesman said no identification papers or weapons were
found on the bodies. One military official said, however, that the
possibility they were terrorists ``has not been ruled out.''
   The infiltration came on the heels of three attempts earlier this
week by Palestinian guerrillas to enter Israel from Lebanon.
   Nine guerrillas were killed in those attacks, which were seen as
attempts by dissident Syrian-backed groups to disrupt the PLO's
dialogue with the United States.
   Speaking to reporters, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the
U.S. decision earlier this month to open a dialogue with the
Palestine Liberation Organization had created a climate for
increased attacks.
   ``It is a fact that the latest American decision to have talks
with the PLO has encouraged the tendency of violent acts against
Israel,'' he said.
   The last major infiltration from Egypt was in March, when three
Palestinian guerrillas hijacked a bus and killed three Israeli
civilians before they were shot to death. The PLO's Force 17 claimed
responsibility.
   Soldiers first detected the infiltration Wednesday when they
found footprints leading across Israel's southern border with Egypt,
said a military spokesman, who cannot be identified by name under
army rules.
   He said troops followed the tracks to a small truck south of the
town of Mitzpe Ramon, 10 miles from the border with Egypt.
   The soldiers opened fire when the driver ignored an order to stop
and killed three men. A fourth escaped, he said.
   Military helicopters circled above the Negev desert Thursday as
searches for the missing man continued, Israel army radio said.
   State radio said the resort town of Eilat, 90 miles south of
Mitzpe Ramon, was cut off from the rest of the country for most of
the day after the army closed the road for its searches.
   On Monday, Israeli troops killed three suspected Palestinian
guerrillas not far from Israel's northern border with Lebanon. Three
more guerrillas were killed in the same area on Wednesday.
   Also Monday, three guerrillas drowned when their boat capsized
off the coast of southern Lebanon as they made their way to the
northern Israeli coast.
   The army spokesman denied rumors that two Israeli soldiers were
injured in the gunfight.
</TEXT>
