<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Radar     12-29 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Radar,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Academy Wants Radar Station to Monitor Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists have recommended a Siberian radar
station that the United States says violates the Antiballistic
Missile Treaty be turned into an ecological center, Radio Moscow
reported Thursday.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev previously offered to turn over
the giant, phased-array radar in Krasnoyarsk to a civilian agency,
but the United States had rejected anything short of dismantling the
station.
   Disputes over the observance of the 1972 ABM Treaty are among the
differences that have stymied superpower negotiations on a treaty to
halve U.S. and Soviet arsenals of long-range, offensive nuclear
weapons.
   The Soviet Academy of Science suggested that the Krasnoyarsk
radar center would make a good international ecological center
because its equipment is capable of closely measuring atmospheric
processes caused by air pollution, the official radio said.
   On Sept. 27, Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said at the
United Nations the radar should become part of an international
space organization. He did not specifically say it would be
dismantled. He also said U.S. radars in Greenland and Britain should
be converted.
   The Kremlin announced in October that it was giving the station,
which is in central Siberia, to the Academy of Sciences, and Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said it would be turned over
to international space study.
   But the U.S. government said the move was unsatisfactory because
it did not include the complete dismantling of the radar.
   The United States says the plant violates provisions of the ABM
treaty that specify that radar stations capable of giving advanced
warnings of missile attacks may only be located on the periphery of
U.S. or Soviet territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1530EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BaseClosings Bjt   12-29 1145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings, Bjt,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Proposes Closing 34 Military Installations; Approval Likely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government commission called Thursday for
closing 34 military installations, including five major Air Force
bases and the Army's second-largest basic training site, in a
recommendation that could send economic shock waves to communities
across America.
   In addition, the Commission on Base Realignment and Closure
recommended closing 52 military housing units in 13 states that date
back to the construction of Nike missile bases in the 1950s, and
partially closing five military facilities and changing the mission
_ and the manpower levels _ at 54 other facilities.
   The panel's recommendations appeared to have a good chance of
taking effect. If Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci approves them,
as expected, Congress would have to reject the whole list in order
to save any of the facilities. And even such a resolution of
disapproval could be vetoed by President-elect George Bush after he
moves into the White House on Jan. 20.
   Carlucci, who has strongly supported the work of the bipartisan
commission, has until Jan. 15 _ five days before leaving office _ to
either accept or reject the entire list.
   The first overhaul in 11 years of the nation's web of 3,800
military installations could save an estimated $693 million a year
without hindering the national security, said Abraham Ribicoff, a
former Democratic senator from Connecticut and co-chairman of the
panel.
   The $693 million savings is minuscule when compared with the
Pentagon's annual budget of $300 billion.
   The states hit hardest by the panel's recommendations were
California, which would lose five major installations; and Illinois,
which would lose two. The area of the nation faring best was the
South, which wouldn't lose any major facilities.
   The five Air Force bases recommended for closure include Chanute
in Illinois; George, Mather and Norton in California, and Pease, in
New Hampshire. Their missions would be shifted to other bases.
   Also closed would be the Presidio, a major Army administrative
base in San Francisco; and Fort Douglas in Utah, a facility built in
1862 to protect Pony Express riders from Indians. It has often been
cited as a prime example of unneeded bases.
   The five bases that would be partially shut down include Fort
Dix, N.J., where 33,490 recruits underwent basic training in the
year that ended Sept. 30. Only Fort Jackson, S.C., trains more
recruits. Fort Dix would go on semi-active status at a loss of 4,686
military and civilian jobs.
   Fifty-four other bases should be realigned, meaning they would
either gain or lose personnel, the commission said.
   Also closed would be part of Fort Meade, Md.; and the
Philadelphia Naval Hospital, which the Navy has long wanted to shut
down.
   The panel called for halting construction at three sites where
the Navy wanted to built new ports for its growing fleet of ships
and closing the sites. They are the Hunters Point Naval Station in
San Francisco; the Galveston, Texas, Naval Station; and the Lake
Charles, La., Naval Station.
   The early reaction from Congress was generally positive. Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, said
``the odds are heavily in favor'' of the list becoming law.
   ``My general feeling is this will be well received by the
Congress,'' he said. Nunn's state would not lose any major bases.
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., ranking Republican on the Armed Services
Committee, agreed. ``I think the recommendation will make it all the
way through,'' he said.
   But Sens. Alan Dixon and Paul Simon, both Illinois Democrats,
noted their state is losing Chanute Air Force Base and the Army's
Fort Sheridan. They complained that overseas bases should be closed
before any U.S. facilities are mothballed.
   Ribicoff and panel co-chairman Jack Edwards, a former Republican
congressman from Alabama, predicted some legislators would be
unhappy but said Congress isn't likely to overturn the decision.
   Legislators with bases on the reduction list are ``going to be
unhappy and we understand that,'' said Edwards. ``But we feel like
the majority of the House and Senate will support what we have
done.''
   Local communities will be unhappy, Edwards said. ``Of course,
they will have a hard time swallowing'' the decision. In some
communities, a military base provides a source of employment and a
sure source of income in good times and bad.
   Edwards said he was sympathetic with communities that would lose
facilities because an Air Force base closed in his district 25 years
ago, costing 14,000 jobs. ``I certainly understand the impact,'' he
said.
   Closed bases mean lost jobs and Congress has refused to permit
any major closures since 1977, when the first of a thicket of rules
and regulations was enacted to make it hard for the Pentagon to pare
down the installation list.
   The 12-member panel was created this year as a way to circumvent
such congressional roadblocks and there were predictions the annual
savings might be as high as $2 billion to $5 billion.
   The savings estimate provided by the commission ``does fall short
of the savings estimates which many had predicted,'' Nunn said.
   But Hayden B. Bryan, executive director of the panel, said those
early estimates ``were just pulled out of the air.''
   The panel, working in strict secrecy, considered a number of
factors, including military utility and whether a base's functions
could be better carried out at another location.
   Another requirement was that the one-time costs of closing a
base, such as severance pay and waste clean-up, would be offset
within six years by the money that would be saved.
   ``Our report represents an opportunity to reduce training costs
in terms of manpower, overhead costs and fuel, to improve command
and control, consolidate training and improve economies of scale and
to remove unnecessary administrative burdens to our defense
managers,'' Edwards said.
   Two installations _ Loring Air Force Base in Maine and Virginia's
Fort Monroe _ escaped even though they have long been included on
critics' lists of unneeded bases. It was the Air Force's attempt to
close Loring in 1977 which prompted the congressional roadblocks to
the Pentagon's base realignment efforts.
   Fort Monroe was originally built with a moat to protect U.S.
forces from British attack in the War of 1812.
   Edwards said Loring and Fort Monroe escaped the ax because they
have developed new uses in recent years, meaning they didn't met the
commission's complicated set of criteria for closing a base.
   While some of the 34 bases that would be closed are major
installations with big payrolls, others are far smaller
installations.
   The latter include such places as Fort Wingate, a New Mexico site
where the Army stores ammunition and which employs only 92 people;
the Army's Tacony Warehouse in Philadelphia; and Hamilton Army
Airfield near San Francisco, which employs only 29 people and is
used only as a training center for reservists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1533EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0608 12-29 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0608,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans Four More Anti-Apartheid Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to ADD more organizations, ADD reax. Pick
up 10th graf pvs, ``The 17 ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The law and order minister
Thursday banned four anti-apartheid groups, using state-of-emergency
regulations that have shut down 28 other organizations this year.
   Two of the latest targets were teachers' unions and a third was a
student group that coordinated anti-government protests this year in
mixed-race townships near Cape Town.
   The fourth banned group was the National Detainees Forum,
established in July to carry on monitoring work that had been
conducted by the Detainees Parents Support Committee before its
banning in February.
   Both watchdog groups have played a major role in providing
information on the thousands of activists, most of them black,
detained without charge for varying periods during the 30-month-old
state of emergency.
   A statement issued on behalf of Law and Order Minister Adriaan
Vlok said the predominantly black Democratic Teachers Union and the
predominantly mixed-race Western Cape Teachers Union had promoted
``people's education'' _ an effort by non-white communities to exert
greater control over curriculum in their schools.
   A year ago, the Cabinet minister for black education, Gerrit
Viljoen, said the government saw important positive elements in
people's education. But Lt. Peet Bothma, a spokesman for Vlok, said
Thursday that the concept was inspired by the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla movement.
   The two teachers' unions, both founded in 1985, were
``politicizing education and discrediting the education system,''
said Bothma. ``Both are involved in the broad revolutionary
onslaught against South Africa which could escalate into strikes,
boycotts, terror and unrest incidents.''
   Bothma said the government had similar concerns about the
predominantly mixed-race Western Cape Students Congress, one of a
dozen youth and student groups banned this year.
   Thousands of mixed-race students around Cape Town, in some cases
supported by faculty, staged a widespread classroom boycott in April
to protest detentions and harassment of students and teachers.
   The latest bannings were denounced by South Africa's Human Rights
Commission. It described the government as ``power-drunk'' and said
that only 24 organizations had been banned in a 37-year period
before 1988.
   The newly banned organizations ``have never been accused in court
of any illegal actions,'' the commission said in a statement.
``Their bannings are a result of their steadfast opposition to
apartheid policies.''
   The 17 groups affected by the initial banning orders in February
included the largest anti-apartheid coalition, the United Democratic
Front, and a nationwide black-consciousness group, the Azanian
People's Organization.
   The main anti-apartheid labor federation, the Congress of South
African Trade Unions, was prohibited from political activity as part
of the crackdown, although it has not muted its criticism of the
government.
   But much of the above-ground leadership of the anti-apartheid
movement has shifted to an alliance of clergymen, including Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu and the Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the
World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   The country's main mixed-race political party Thursday ended its
annual conference with a pledge to seek contacts with the African
National Congress.
   Labor Party delegates rejected a proposal to quit Parliament as a
protest against apartheid, but resolved to take more initiative in
working with non-parliamentary groups to undermine the white
government's racial policies.
   Parliament has chambers for whites, Asians and people of mixed
race, but the black majority is excluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
