<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AmazonKilling     12-29 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amazon Killing,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Police Step Up Manhunt For Killer of Ecologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they have
located five more cattle ranchers who may be linked to the slaying
of a prominent ecologist who fought to protect the Amazon forest.
   Three other cattlemen already have been arrested in the death of
Francisco Mendes, 44, who was gunned down Dec. 22 outside his home
about 50 miles outside of Brasilia.
   About 80 officers from Brasilia and Sao Paulo were transferred
Wednesday to the western Amazon state of Acre to search the jungles
for suspects in the death, said Deputy Justice Minister Luis
Fernando Eichenberg.
   ``Overnight, the police located five ranchers who may be suspects
in the Mendes case but nothing has been confirmed,'' Eichenberg
said. He gave no further details.
   Eichenberg, contacted by telephone in Brasilia, refused to
confirm press reports that said five suspects _ all cattle ranchers
_ had been arrested by police on a ranch near the jungle village of
Xapuri, where Mendes was slain. Xapuri is about 2,600 miles
northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   Police already were holding in custody three sons of Darly Alves
da Silva, a cattle rancher who Mendes had said sent him death
threats. Mendes led a local rubber tappers union that fought against
clearing the Amazon for cattle grazing.
   Mendes last year received a United Nations Global 500 prize given
to top ecologists worldwide.
   Eichenberg said police had found several clues indicating that
Oloci Alves da Silva, captured Tuesday after a gun battle on the
family ranch in Xapuri, was at the scene of the Mendes shooting.
   ``The police have analyzed several cigarette butts found in front
of Mendes' house, and Oloci is known to have smoked the same
brand,'' said the Justice Minisitry official. ``This and other clues
lead us to believe he was present when Mendes was killed.''
   Also being held were 21-year-old Darcy Pereira da Silva, who
claims to have killed Mendes, and his brother Aleci Alves da Silva.
Police have said they doubt Darcy da Silva participated in Mendes'
slaying and that he is being used as a decoy by his father, whose
whereabouts is unknown.
   Eichenburg said the police would extend ``possibly throughout the
month of January'' a ``sweep operation,'' begun Wednesday to find
and confiscate illegal weapons in the region in a push to halt
land-dispute violence in the western Amazon.
   For the second day, police flew over the jungle in helicopters
and search planes. They set up road blocks along highways and the
state's border with Bolivia in the search for da Silva and any
unregistered weapons.
   ``The atmosphere in Acre is extremely tense and it is up to the
police to control any further outbreaks of violence,'' said
Eichenburg.
   The battles over the Amazon jungle, an expanse of rainforest
about two-thirds the size of continental United States, has often
erupted in bloody clashes.
   Cattle ranchers, eager to clear forest lands for grazing, often
order the killings of squatters and ecologists who oppose them.
</TEXT>
