<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     12-29 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Blocked By North Korea's Demand On U.S.-South Korean
Maneuvers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between South Korea and North Korea
on easing tension suffered a sharp setback Thursday when North Korea
demanded an end to U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
   The five-member delegations of both sides agreed to meet again
Feb. 10 at this truce village inside the Demilitarized Zone
seprating the two nations.
   The three-hour meeting plunged into stalemate a few minutes after
it opened when North Korea issued a new demand for an end to annual
U.S.-South Korea ``Team Spirit'' exercises it says threaten its
security.
   The chief North Korean delegate, Chon Kum Chul, said this was a
precondition for the parliamentary talks and other proposals for
inter-Korea contacts.
   ``Team Sprit war exercises have created a state of quasi-war and
affected South-North talks in progress. The exercises have been the
biggest obstacle blocking the progress of dialogue,'' Chon said.
   His South Korean counterpart, Chai Mun-shick, accused North Korea
of laying a new obstacle before the talks and insisted the issue be
addressed at other government-level talks expected early next year.
North Korea rejected the idea.
   South Korea and the United States hold annual spring military
exercises to practice their joint command system in the event of a
North Korean invasion. About 200,000 troops of both sides took part
in last year's exercises from February to April.
   South Korea had hoped before Thursday's meeting, the seventh
since August, that agreement was near on setting terms for
full-scale talks between each side's legislatures after making
progress at a Nov. 17 meeting.
   Chai expressed ``surprise and suspicion'' at North Korea's new
demand and asked that it be dropped, saying the exercises are annual
and defensive.
   ``North Korea's demand is very disappointing. I suspect that
their resolve to make the talks a success has weakened,'' Chai said
after the meeting.
   Chon declined to withdraw the demand and suggested the military
exercises could be an obstacle to the parliamentary talks and
proposals for separate government and sports talks.
   Rep. Park Kwan-yong, an opposition member on the South Korean
delegation, said North Korea used the same tactics three years ago.
   Park, a member of South Korean negotiating team in talks with
North Korea in 1985, said lawmakers of both sides were close to
agreement and scheduled to meet in mid-February in 1986. North Korea
unilaterally suspended all dialogue to protest the ``Team Spirit''
exercises.
   The meeting was held the day after Seoul sent a message to North
Korea agreeing to separate political and military talks on arms
reductions and other tension-easing measures.
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon wrote his North Korean
counterpart, Yon Hyung Muk, that they head delegations to
alternating talks in Seoul and Pyongyang to discuss
non-interference, cooperation in select areas and building ``mutual
trust in military matters.''
   South Korea has yet to respond to three more North Korean
proposals for political, military and sports talks. One proposal
seeks the withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed here under
a mutual defense treaty.
   Talks have been held on and off since the early 1970s with little
progress. Both sides have tended to stress their respective
initiatives and play down the other's proposals.
   The two Koreas have hundreds of thousands of troops facing each
other along the 150-mile border. The border is sealed and there are
no communications except for a hot line.
   U.S. and Soviet forces divided the Korean peninsula when they
ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War II in 1945.
North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950 to start the Korean War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
