<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Transmitters     12-29 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Transmitters,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Warns of Misuse of Emergency Aircraft Locators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission issued a
warning Thursday about the unauthorized use of emergency locator
transmitters used to aid in the search and rescue of downed or
disabled aircraft.
   The warning was directed at users of emergency personal locators,
for which ``misleading advertisements'' imply that these devices are
authorized for use by backpackers and hikers to alert search and
rescue personnel, the FCC said.
   Emergency locator transmitters are authorized for use only by
aircraft in distress or in an aeronautical emergency. Their use for
any other purpose is prohibited because it would jeopardize the
effectiveness of the transmitters in aeronautical search and rescue
operations, the FCC said.
   The frequencies allocated to emergency locator transmitters
``cannot accommodate an additional large number of personal users
such as backpackers and hikers,'' the commission said in its warning.
   The penalty for unauthorized use of these transmitters includes
fines up to $10,000 and possible imprisonment, it said.
   The FCC said ads for emergency personal locators have appeared in
sales catalogs, but it did not identify the publications. Officials
at the agency said they did not know whether unauthorized use of
these transmitters has hampered any aeronautical search and rescue
operations.
</TEXT>
