<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0646 12-29 0980</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0646,1001</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heightened Airport Alert as Search Mounts for Pan Am Bomber</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 24th graf, ``In a ...'' to ADD brother's name.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers traveling on U.S. airlines were
questioned about their luggage and had their bags X-rayed Thursday
in a security clampdown at British airports prompted by the bombing
of Pan Am Flight 103.
   The disclosure that plastic explosives blew up the Boeing 747 on
Dec. 21, killing all 259 people and 11 on the ground, set off a
worldwide hunt for the perpetrators.
   The British foreign secretary called for the cooperation of
governments in the Middle East, where Palestinian and Iranian
extremists are key suspects.
   President-elect George Bush said he would ``severely punish'' the
bombers if they were found.
   At Britain's four airports that handle U.S. carriers, passengers
fed their checked luggage through X-ray machines and were asked
about who packed their bags, when they were packed, whether the bags
had been out of their sight since, and whether strangers gave them
parcels to carry.
   The X-rayed suitcases were bound in a tough plastic strip to
prevent them from being opened between the check-in desks and the
plane. Anything arousing suspicion was opened and searched by hand.
   At Heathrow Airport's busy Terminal 3, used by U.S. carriers Pan
Am and TWA, police patrolled with submachine guns issued to them
after 1986 terrorist incidents in Europe.
   ``Sure there's a risk, but you've got more chance of getting
killed on a street in New York,'' said Sam Fleischacker, a
Philadelphia college professor rushing to catch a TWA flight to New
York.
   He said he flew to London on vacation the day after the Pan Am
crashed into the Scottish village of Lockerbie, and ``I was worried
then.'' Gesturing to the X-ray machine, he said: ``What worries me a
lot too is that they didn't have all this then.''
   As he spoke, he drifted a few feet away from his bags and was
promptly upbraided by ground staff for leaving them unattended.
   On Wednesday, the Department of Transport ordered the four
British airports handling U.S. carriers to step up security. Hank
Auerbach, Pan Am's chief in northern Europe, said the airline had
met ``all the requirements set by the Department of Transport.'' He
refused to elaborate.
   In France, police said security was heightened at Paris' Charles
de Gaulle and Orly airports, with undisclosed measures for U.S.
carriers. Officials at Rome's Leonardo da Vinci airport also said
they had increased security.
   The British directive took effect a few hours after Wednesday's
disclosure that a bomb blew Flight 103 out of the sky. The directive
was aimed at Heathrow, neighboring Gatwick, Manchester in northern
England and Prestwick in Scotland.
   Amid a now familiar debate about what else can be done to protect
airlines from terrorists, analysts speculated that the bomb could
have been smuggled aboard in a suitcase, or into the cargo hold by
ground staff.
   Many looked to El Al, Israel's national carrier, which has had
long experience fighting terrorism and hand-searches all baggage.
British lawmaker David Wilshire, whose constituency includes
Heathrow, said El Al also puts freight through simulated pressure
procedures, so that any bomb set to be detonated by altitude changes
would explode on the ground.
   Brian Jenkins, a U.S. terrorism consultant, said key tasks for
the investigators were to check the background of every passenger on
Flight 103 and look for false identities; to discover whether any
had connections that could make them ``witting or unwitting''
accomplices; and to trace every item of cargo back to its origins.
   The investigation involves Scottish police, the British
anti-terrorism squad, the FBI and West German federal police.
Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe asked for the cooperation of
Middle East governments.
   ``This may well be a long, painstaking, structured matter,''
warned Detective Chief Superintendent John Orr of the Glasgow area
police, who is heading the criminal investigation.
   Police officers flew to West Germany Thursday as part of the
investigation, Orr said in Lockerbie. He said officers also would be
sent to ``other parts of the world.'' He declined to elaborate.
   Washington has offered a $500,000 reward for information leading
to those responsible for the crash.
   Bush, asked for his reaction to the air tragedy, said Thursday:
``Well, horror. And seek hard and punish firmly, decisively, those
who did this, if you could ever find them.''
   But Charles Price, the U.S. ambassador to Britain, said the U.S.
government was unlikely to retaliate if the killers were identified.
   ``I don't know of any contingency plans that involve some form of
retaliation on our part and I can't imagine that it is very
likely,'' Price told reporters at Heathrow before boarding a British
Airways Concorde jet en route to California for New Year's. He said
he would return to Lockerbie Jan. 4 to attend a memorial service for
the victims.
   In a field outside a church in the countryside near Lockerbie,
engineers sawed up the plane's nose section for removal. John
Wagner, the brother of co-pilot Raymond Wagner, visited the church
and asked for and was given two Bibles as mementos for the family,
said the minister, the Rev. Cameron Gibson.
   Relatives laid wreaths by the cockpit, while in Lockerbie, a
crane lifted one of the engines out of the 15-foot-deep crater in
which it had lain for eight days.
   So far, 241 bodies have been found but only 16 have been
identified and released for burial. Six Americans and a Briton were
identified Thursday.
   They are the plane's pilot, James Bruce MacQuarrie, 55, of
Kensington, N.H., co-pilot Wagner, 52, of Pennington, N.J., Melina
Hudson, 16, of Albany, N.Y., Joseph Kenneth Miller, 56, of Woodmere,
N.Y., Douglas Eugene Merlicote, 22, Army Post Office, N.Y., Martin
Bernard Christopher Simpson, 52, of Brooklyn, N.Y., and Elyse Jeanne
Saraceni, 20, of London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
