<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CommunistPresident     12-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Communist President,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Stays Out Of Dispute Over Communist Student Government Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Thursday declined to get
involved in a dispute over the election of a communist student body
leader at the University of Massachusetts, saying the students and
university should resolve the matter.
   The student, Jason Rabinowitz, was elected co-president of the
student government last spring with Shari Silkoff, a self-described
progressive.
   But they had been barred from taking office by a student judicial
body on the ground that the student constitution prohibited
co-presidents.
   Rabinowitz and Silkoff contended they were barred because of
their political beliefs, and they asked Superior Court Judge
Elizabeth Porada to issue an injunction assuring their right to take
office.
   In turning down the request, Porada wrote that the matter is
``best left to the decision of the students, student senate and
university judiciary without the intervention by the courts or
trustees of the university.''
   The judge also said an injunction was unnecessary because the
school's Student Supreme Court had recently lifted its own ban
against the two students taking office.
   The students' election still must be ratified by the Student
Government Association's Senate.
   Edward Etheredge, an attorney for Rabinowitz and Silkoff, said
the students were away for the holidays but that he had expected the
judge's decision.
   He added that because of the recent ruling by the Student Supreme
Court, his clients had moved back into their offices.
   ``The issue now is whether the university pays Jason and Shari
their back compensation and attorney's fees. If they don't, we'll be
back in court,'' he said.
   University attorney Terrence O'Malley was reported to be out of
his office Thursday afternoon and could not be reached for comment.
   Running as a team, Rabinowitz _ a founding member of the Young
Communist League _ and Silkoff were elected in March by 1,454 votes,
a 361-vote margin over a conservative candidate at the
19,000-undergraduate school.
   A month after the election, the Student Supreme Court barred the
two from the post.
   The presidency of the Student Government Association is a paid
position with the power to hire and appoint other students to the
government body.
   Rabinowitz and Silkoff argued that bylaws allow for
co-presidents, and that the student judicial tribunal consisted of
conservatives hand-picked by a student attorney general, who was
chief among their political foes.
   The Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts sued on their behalf,
alleging that their civil rights were violated by campus
conservatives intent on keeping them from office.
</TEXT>
