<DOCNO> AP881229-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1631EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BaseClosings-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0644 12-29 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Armed Services Leaders Like Recommendations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 2nd graf with Aspin comments; picks up
3d graf pvs, ``This is;'' minor editing in 4th graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the military committees in Congress
said Thursday they like the base-closing recommendations made by a
special commission and predicted the proposals will be accepted by
Congress.
   ``I have a positive reaction,'' Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, said at a news conference.
``This process is a step forward. ... I would have liked to have
seen more.''
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, told reporters he supports the plan and will urge
colleagues to do likewise.
   Aspin said his only criticism was that the commission's report
was ``too modest'' and that the list of targeted bases could have
been up to about 30 percent larger. He did not specify what other
bases could have been included.
   ``This is a good start,'' said Virginia Sen. John Warner, a
former Navy secretary who is the ranking Republican on Nunn's
committee. He said the commission's report ``confirmed that there
are inefficient aspects of our defense budget.''
   The three lawmakers said they believe the panel's recommendations
to close 86 installations and reduce or alter operations at 59
others will be accepted by Congress, which would face an
all-or-nothing decision once the report reaches Capitol Hill after a
review by Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
   ``My general feeling is this will be well received by the
Congress,'' Nunn said. ``The odds are heavily in favor of this
becoming the law of the land.''
   Warner told reporters he believes ``the recommendation will make
it all the way through'' Congress, which created the commission this
year to break the impasse that has prevented lawmakers from agreeing
on any major closings since 1977.
   Warner and Nunn said budget deficits require the Defense
Department and Congress to look toward further base closings and
consolidations to generate more economies than the $693 million a
year the commission says its plan would save.
   ``I think this ought to be a continuous source of study by the
new (defense) secretary,'' said Nunn, who wants overseas basis
included in such a review. ``There's still a way to go in terms of a
complete review based on the new budget circumstances.''
   Rep. Bill Lowery, R-Calif., said his initial reaction to the plan
was positive. Lowery is the ranking GOP member of the Appropriations
subcommittee on military construction, which would have the initial
House say on financing the closure plan.
   Lowery represents San Diego, which would be a winner under the
plan, gaining five Navy ships, 1,473 military personnel and 22
civilian jobs _ all of which had been slated for San Francisco.
   ``There is no question in these tight budgetary times we are
going to have to do more with less,'' Lowery said in a statement.
   Sen. Bill Roth, R-Del., one of the principal authors of the law
that created the commission, said the recommendations are ``a
crucial step towards achieving real savings for the American
taxpayer.'' Delaware had no bases on ths hit list.
   But Illinois did _ Fort Sheridan and Chanute Air Force Base _ and
its two Democratic senators issued a joint statement saying the
commission should have looked at overseas bases before targeting
domestic installations.
   ``How can we justify closing military bases in our own back yard
when we don't even consider a single one of the 1,500 overseas U.S.
military facilities for the same treatment?'' said Sen. Alan Dixon,
chairman of the Armed Services subcommittee on readiness.
   ``The overseas bases ought to be looked at first to make sure the
need is still there,'' Sen. Paul Simon said.
   Nunn and Warner said they thought the commission had done the
best job it could under various constraints, some imposed by the
Pentagon and others, like a relatively short study period, imposed
by Congress.
   Nunn said the panel had to use current Pentagon budget figures,
even though the new spending plan going to Congress next month is
expected to be lower, changing the parameters for evaluating the
need for some bases.
   He specifically said the commission approached Navy installations
with the assumption the U.S. battle fleet would have 600 ships, a
goal he said is not attainable in the forseeable future.
   Nunn also questioned wby the Pentagon prevented the commission
from studying the need for defense facilities owned by the
government and operated by private contractors.
</TEXT>
