<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GayMidshipman     12-29 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Midshipman,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Midshipman Sues For Reinstatement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gay midshipmen who says he was forced to
resign from the Naval Academy, after admitting his homosexuality two
months before his scheduled graduation, asked a federal court on
Thursday to order his reinstatement.
   Joseph C. Steffan, 24, of Moorhead, Minn., claimed in the suit
filed in U.S. District Court that his ``forced separation'' from the
academy violated his constitutional rights of free speech, due
process and equal protection under the law.
   Paula L. Ettelbrick, legal director for the Lambda Legal Defense
and Education Fund, a homosexual rights advocacy group acting as
Steffan's legal counsel, said that, to her knowledge, the suit is
the first of its kind against a service academy.
   Steffan, now employed by a computer software company in Fargo,
N.D., acknowledged that he was aware of a provision in the
midshipmen's manual that homosexuals would be dismissed from the
academy.
   Although Steffan said that he realized by the end of his
sophomore year that he was homosexual, he tried to keep it apart
from his life as a midshipman until he was informed in March 1987
that he was being investigated by the Navy.
   At the time Steffan was a battalion commander in charge of
one-sixth of the academy's 4,500 midshipmen, a solo performer with
the academy glee club, and in the top 10 percent of his class,
according to the suit.
   Upon learning of the Navy investigation, Steffan said he admitted
to a chaplain and then to the academy's commandant, Capt. H.W.
Habermeyer Jr., that we was a homosexual.
   Within eight days, a brigade performance board and an academic
board on the Annapolis, Md., campus recommended Steffan's discharge
after determining that he had an ``insufficient aptitude'' for a
Navy officer's commission, according to the suit.
   ``The boards said my evaluations were completely irrelevant,''
Steffan said at a news conference here Thursday. ``All they needed
to have was that I was gay. They never even looked at my record.''
   Steffan said he agreed to submit a qualified resignation rather
than fight a dismissal because of stress that his situation was
causing his family and because his father was suffering from high
blood pressure at the time.
   The suit names Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and Navy
Secretary William Ball in addition to the Naval Academy's
superintendent and commandant as defendants.
   Jay Fromer, a spokesman for the Naval Academy, said the school
only abided by Navy regulations.
   ``Since we are a part of the Department of the Navy, we are bound
by Navy regulations which state homosexuality is incompatible with
military service,'' Fromer said.
   In the suit, Steffan is seeking re-admission to the academy, a
diploma from it and a commission in the Navy, but he conceded the
unlikelihood of winning the latter by the time the case winds its
way through the courts.
   ``If I'm 30 years old at the time, I'm not going to be in much of
a position to go in as an ensign,'' he said. ``My goal is not only
to get a diploma but to have this policy of discimination reversed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1720EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ThePresidio Bjt   12-29 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Presidio, Bjt,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closure Of Historic Base Could Be Birth of Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The closing of the Presidio Army base on a
hillside overlooking the Golden Gate Bridge could transform one of
the city's loveliest spots into a park _ at the cost of thousands of
civilian jobs.
   The Presidio was one of 34 military bases recommended for closing
by a government commission Thursday. The panel also said the Navy
should not base the USS Missouri at Hunters Point, an issue that has
divided the city for years.
   The recommendation to close the Presidio surprised and
disappointed city officials and neighborhood businessmen, even
though the commission said the move would have minimal impact on
local employment.
   Founded by the Spanish in 1776 and operated as an Army base since
1846, the Presidio is one of the most important spots in San
Francisco history. Now headquarters of the 6th Army, it employs
about 3,000 civilians and 2,700 servicemen.
   ``I think it will have a significant effect on the economy unless
the commission is definite in recommending that there be economic
assistance to communities near bases,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, a
Democrat whose district is next to the Presidio.
   The base, she said, is the third-largest employer in San
Francisco and has an annual payroll of $600 million.
   ``It's bad. We need this (base). I hope it doesn't happen,'' said
Bill Wakileh, a delicatessen owner who estimated that half his
business over the past 20 years has come from the nearby base.
   Mayor Art Agnos said the commission's decision had ``very grave
consequences'' for the city. He planned to meet with the local
congressional delegation to evaluate the effect of losing the base.
   ``For 112 years the Presidio has been an integral part of San
Francisco. It was here before San Francisco was a city. It's been a
very good neighbor and ... an important part of our economy,'' he
said.
   The site's future is restricted by the 1972 law that established
the Golden Gate National Recreation Area, which includes most of the
base.
   Except for 36 acres belonging to the Letterman Army Medical
Center, all 1,490 acres would come under the control of the park.
The hospital also is slated for closing.
   Commercial development would not be allowed on the property, said
Brian O'Neill, the park area superintendent. Open space,
recreational and educational use and preservation of historic
buildings at the base would be the most likely uses, he said.
   Servicemen and civilians at the Presidio were apprehensive about
the prospect of leaving what many consider the most beautiful
military base in the nation, the site of last year's film ``The
Presidio,'' starring Sean Connery and Mark Harmon.
   ``It's long been considered a prime assignment. ... It's sort of
a combination military office building, museum and park all rolled
into one,'' said Jim Hudgins, Presidio chief of community relations.
   The base is mostly open to the public and is often the scene of
bicycle races, running events and picnics. Thousands of people
gather there every Fourth of July to watch fireworks over San
Francisco Bay.
   In its proposal to close the base, the commission said the
Presidio has no space for expansion and the Letterman hospital needs
structural repairs. Closure would save $74.1 million a year, the
committee estimated.
   The panel also said Hamilton Army Airfield in Marin County, the
airfield for the Presidio and a training center for reserve units,
should be shut down.
   The Navy, it said, should drop plans to base a battleship at the
Hunters Point Naval shipyard on the bay. A base was to be built
there if the Navy decided that the area should be the home port for
the Missouri and its group.
   The proposal to make San Francisco the battleship group's base
generated heavy debate. In November, voters narrowly passed a
proposition supporting the basing plan.
   Missouri supporters said the battleship group would pump millions
of dollars into the city's economy and provide hundreds of jobs.
</TEXT>
