<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1844EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Apparel-Homework     12-29 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apparel-Homework,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearings on Home Production of Apparel Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department will hold hearings in
February and March on lifting a World War II-era regulation that
bars apparel manufacturers from employing seamstresses in their
homes, officials said Thursday.
   The department will publish in Friday's edition of the Federal
Register an advanced notice of proposed rulemaking as the first
formal step for lifting the ban, said Allan McMillan, a deputy
assistant labor secretary in charge of enforcing the prohibition.
   President-elect Bush urged the action last October after the
Labor Department won approval from the White House budget office to
remove homework prohibitions in five other apparel fields effective
Jan. 8.
   In a letter to Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin two weeks before
the election, Bush said he had been assured ``that the last piece of
this rulemaking will be given top priority for clearance.''
   McMillan said the Labor Department will hold hearings on the
proposal in Miami on Feb. 22-23; in San Antonio, Texas, on March
2-3; and in Chicago on March 8-9.
   ``The department believes that changing demographics such as more
women working demand increased workforce flexibility, including the
option to work in one's home,'' he said. ``The current ban
forecloses that possibility.''
   The prohibitions on apparel industry homework were imposedin 1942
to combat widespread exploitation of immigrants and other low-wage
workers. Lifting them has been the Reagan administration's top
deregulatory proposal in the labor relations area for the past
several years.
   The administration succeed in 1984 in removing the ban on knitted
outerwear but was thwarted by court rulings in response to suits
from unions in lifting the prohibitions in six other apparel fields.
   However, two days after the election, the Labor Department
announced it was removing the prohibitions, effective Jan. 8, in
five apparel fields: gloves and mittens, embroideries, buttons and
buckles, handkerchiefs and some jewelry.
   The Labor Department estimates between 9,000 and 100,000 workers
are employed in those five industries, compared with up to 500,000
in women's apparel.
   The International Ladies Garment Workers Union, which represents
some 170,000 workers, said last week it will seek a court injunction
next week to prohibit the further removal of any of the remaining
bans on homework.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
