<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0665,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Children on Way Home After 13 Months Captivity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Gadhafi calling for release
of all hostages; CORRECTS spelling of Gadhafi in 5th graf pvs,
`Libyan leader...' PICKS UP 7th pvs, `The guerrilla...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two French girls held hostage in Lebanon for 13
months returned home Thursday night, six days after their captors _
the Palestinian guerrilla group commanded by Abu Nidal _ first
promised them freedom.
   Left behind in the hands of Fatah-Revolutionary Council were the
girls' mother, Jacqueline Valente; five Belgians also captured
aboard the yacht Silco; and a baby sister born in captivity.
   Marie-Laure Betille, 7, and her 6-year-old sister, Virginie,
landed at a military base in Istres, near Marseille, in a government
plane with their father, Pascal Betille, a spokeswoman for the
Foreign Ministry said.
   They came from the Libyan capital of Tripoli, where the girls
were handed over to French officials.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, who bankrolls the guerrilla
faction, had called for the girls' release on Christmas Eve.
   Later Thursday, Libya's official JANA news agency quoted Gadhafi
as calling for the release of all hostages.
   ``Once again, I ask the Fatah-Revolutionary Council and the rest
of the liberation movements in the Middle East to respond to my
appeal for the release of the remaining hostages on this holy
occasion,'' Gadhafi was quoted as saying, in apparent reference to
Christmas.
   In Paris, the Foreign Ministry said ``France ... welcomes this
humanitarian gesture in appropriate measure'' and ``it thanks
foreign authorities who contributed.'' The statement did not
elaborate.
   The guerrilla group's spokesman, Walid Khaled, said in a
statement issued in Beirut, Lebanon, that the release was a ``gift
to the French authorities, all French political parties, the French
people and President (Francois) Mitterrand in the name of the
children of Palestine, the children of the revolution of the stones,
on the occasion of Christmas and New Year.'' He was referring to the
year-old uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   JANA said the girls received medical examinations and were found
to ``enjoy good health.''
   Betille, the girls' divorced father, told Radio-Television
Luxembourg in Tripoli that his children would undergo medical
examinations at a Marseille hospital.
   The girls arrived Thursday in the Libyan port of Benghazi, JANA
reported earlier, but it did not say from where.
   On Monday, Khaled said the girls were freed and on their way to
Paris, but they didn't turn up and the Palestinian group issued
contradictory statements.
   Two official cars were placed at the disposal of the girls'
family in Lyon, southeastern France, and the relatives were to leave
for Paris to welcome the children home.
   ``That's 14 months that we have been fighting for the release of
the hostages,'' said Andre Metral, brother-in-law of the girls'
mother. ``I remain reserved as long as I have not seen the two
little girls in the arms of their father.''
   His wife, Anne-Marie, sister of Ms. Valente, said: ``After hope
disappointed ... all these false joys have upset us. Now we know
that they are free, we want to see them and above all to continue
the fight for the other hostages.''
   Fatah Revolutionary Council announced the capture of the hostages
on Nov. 8, 1987, saying the yacht was seized off the coast of the
Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip. It accused the captives of spying for
Israel, a charge that family members and Israel have denied.
   The group has been blamed for hijackings, bombings and
assassinations since it broke with PLO chief Yasser Arafat in 1976.
   Ms. Valente gave birth to a third child in captivity and said in
a recent videotape that she is pregnant again.
   The case is considered unrelated to the 15 Westerners held
hostage in Lebanon by pro-Iranian factions.
</TEXT>
