<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1846EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtifactFraud     12-29 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Artifact Fraud,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Artifact No Fact, Says Reasearcher: In Fact, It's `Mammoth
Fraud'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A piece of shell jewelry once hailed as a
10,000-year-old Indian relic depicting a woolly mammoth is really
about 1,000 years old and was found in the last century by a shady
amateur archaeologist, an anthropologist says.
   David Meltzer of Southern Methodist University called the carving
resembling the animal that became extinct 10,000 years ago a
``mammoth fraud.'' He spent eight years researching the history of
the piece, a hand-size whelk shell pendant, and used carbon 14
dating to determine its age.
   The pendant was rediscovered in the 1970s by Smithsonian
Institution researchers who found it in a drawer, where it
apparently had lain since the end of the 19th century.
   It had been produced by Hilbourne T. Cresson as a discovery he'd
made in northern Delaware, near Holly Oak. But for some reason, the
artifact, known as the Holly Oak pendant, was forgotten about for
decades, Meltzer said.
   By the time it was noticed again, archaeologists had proven that
humans lived with woolly mammoths in the Western Hemisphere, at
least in the New Mexico area. It had been known since 1864 that man
lived at the same time as the beasts in Europe; that was the year
that a mammoth tusk was found at La Madeliene, France, with etchings
on it.
   In May 1976, Science magazine carried an article attributed to
John C. Kraft, a geologist at the University of Delaware, that the
pendant could be authentic, but one year later he told another
journal the piece might be a fraud.
   When Metzler began his investigation in 1981, he found Cresson
claimed to have found the pendant in 1864 but told no one about it
until 1889. The researcher checked newspaper microfilms that might
have clues about Cresson.
   ``When the microfilm came back, I was flabbergasted,'' Meltzer
said. According to front-page stories, Cresson ``blew his brains
out'' in a New York City park. One report quoted his suicide note as
saying he was suspected of counterfeiting and was being followed by
Secret Service agents.
   Metzler learned that Cresson had studied art and archaeology in
France about the time of the La Madeliene discovery. ``The more we
learned about Cresson, the more suspicious we got,'' he said. The
carbon dating, measuring the amount of radioactive carbon 14 left in
the pendant, was the final confirmation.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
