<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Israel-PLO     12-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embassy Charges Terrorist Groups Learned From Arafat Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli government said Thursday that the
Palestine Liberation Organization set the examples for all terrorist
groups which attack civilian airplanes and their passengers.
   A statement titled ``PLO: The first of its kind,'' did not
directly link Yassar Arafat's group to the bombing of Pan Am Flight
103, the Boeing 747 jetliner that crashed last week in Scotland and
killed all 259 aboard and an estimated 11 people on the ground.
   But the statement, released by the Israeli embassy, said all
terrorist groups that have targeted civil aviation in recent years
``learned from one source _ the PLO.''
   Arafat's organization was the first to hijack an airplane, an El
Al fight in 1968; the first to destroy a plane in midair, a Swissair
flight to Israel in 1970; and the first to carry out a
gun-and-grenade attack on passengers, an El Al plane in Greece in
1968, the statement said.
   ``Internationalist terrorist organizations have learned from the
PLO in other areas as well,'' the embassy said. It cited the murder
of 11 Israeli athletes at the Olympics in Munich, West Germany, and
the seizure of the Israeli embassy in Bangkok, Thailand, also in
1972.
   U.S. investigators so far have been unable to pinpoint the person
or group that placed a bomb aboard the Pan Am plane. At least two
radical Palestinian organizations, both outside the PLO, are among a
wide spectrum of possible suspects. These are The Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, and the Al Fatah
Revolutionary Council headed by Abu Nidal.
   ``The PLO has throughout the years develped links and cooperated,
at times very closely, with other terror organizations,'' the
Israeli statement said, ``providing them with funds, arms, training
and operational assistance.''
   In the Middle East, it said, Abu Nidal and others used terror
methods which they first learned from the PLO before breaking away
to form their own groups.
   The PLO itself ``has not ended its own campaign of terror, but
has only redefined the direction, range and tactical form of the
`armed struggle,' which is another definition of terror and violence
sanctioned by the PLO,'' the statement said. ``From earlier years to
more recent attacks, PLO violence shows that when it comes to
terrorism, the PLO wrote the book.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz accused the PLO of terrorism
last month as he denied Arafat a visa to speak to the U.N. General
Assembly in New York. He called the PLO chairman an ``accessory'' to
terrorism.
   Subsequently, Arafat said he renounced terrorism ``in all forms''
and Shultz approved U.S. talks with the PLO, the first authorized by
the United States in 13 years.
   The first session was held Dec. 16 in Carthage, Tunisia.
Afterward, Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy and other
senior Reagan administration officials cautioned the PLO the
``substantive dialogue'' would be terminated if acts of terrorism
were traced to Arafat's organization.
   There have been no U.S. accusations against the PLO since.
</TEXT>
