<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Economy     12-29 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Economy,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Soar After Devaluation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates soared in Israel on Thursday as
skepticism grew over the government's decision to devalue the shekel.
   The Bank of Israel, the central bank, raised its lending rate to
banks and other large financial institutions to 48.25 percent a
year, compared to 32.8 percent a week ago.
   The rate is high because of Israel's high inflation rate.
   Bank Leumi, the nation's largest commercial bank, raised its
basic lending rate to 2 percent a month from 1.5 percent. Other
financial institutions were expected to follow suit.
   Israel radio said people are ``panicked'' and many believe
further devaluation is imminent.
   The Central Bureau of Statistics published more bad news at a
news conference Thursday.
   It estimated that Israel's gross national product _ the value of
all goods and services produced in the economy _ grew 1 percent this
year, down from 5.2 percent in 1987. Figures were adjusted for
inflation.
   Ezra Hadar, director of the bureau's national accounts division,
told reporters the slowdown reflected declines in industrial
production and agricultural output as well as side-effects from the
year-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories.
   Palestinians boycotted Israeli-made products and some quit jobs
in Israel, reducing the output of industries like textiles and
construction.
   Hadar estimated the uprising cost $300 million in sales, and
cancellation of the Israeli-built Lavi fighter jet reduced sales
another $300 million.
   Israel' s unemployment rate was above 7 percent compared to 6.1
percent last year, he said.
   The government on Tuesday devalued the shekel by 5 percent in an
effort to stem a speculative buying binge of foreign currencies.
   That lowered the currency to 1.680 shekels to the dollar from
1.599.
   Purchases of foreign currencies, especially the dollar, slowed to
$70 million from $80 million on Wednesday and a record $135 million
on Tuesday, said Bank of Israel spokesman Amnon Yakobi.
   Critics say the devaluation is inflationary and badly timed,
throwing off year-end closing of corporate balance sheets.
   Business leaders believe a larger devaluation is needed next year
to bring the shekel more in line with U.S. and European currencies.
   Zvi Amit of the Federation of Chambers of Commerce said companies
with foreign currency debts have had to revalue them upward by 5
percent in shekels, reducing their profits for the year.
   ``It hurts their credit lines, it hurts their efforts to attract
investment, it hurts all around,'' Amit said.
</TEXT>
