<DOCNO> AP881229-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eastern     12-29 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Using New Inspections Of Boeings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, trying to counter a wave of
negative publicity, said Thursday it will regularly use electrical
current devices to detect the tiniest of gaps in the bodies of older
Boeing 727s.
   ``We had an unfortunate incident and we are responding,'' said
Joseph B. Leonard, executive vice president, referring to Monday's
emergency landing of an Eastern Boeing 727 in Charleston, W.Va.,
with a 14-inch tear in its fuselage.
   After the incident, in which two people suffered minor injures,
the airline visually inspected the 46 oldest of its 111 727s _ those
with 30,000 or more landings.
   Ed Upton, Eastern vice president for maintenance and engineering,
said that currently, the airline inspects its planes visually. When
it suspects a crack in an obscure place, it uses electrical
detectors known as eddy-current devices.
   Upton said the devices have been recalibrated to go deeper into
the metal and detect a gap of one-130,000th of an inch, and will be
used on older Boeings on a regular basis.
   How often depends on results of the electrical inspection of the
46 oldest jets, he said.
   The rivet-to-rivet testing will be conducted on a 100-inch-long
stretch of the planes, from about the last row of seats to the rear
door. The 22-year-old plane that tore open Monday developed the hole
in the roof near the tail.
   A Boeing 727 was grounded in Boston on Monday after a three-inch
crack was discovered near the tail. On Wednesday Eastern maintenance
workers in Miami found corrosion near fuselage rivets on a 727. The
company also disclosed that cracks were found in a McDonnell Douglas
DC-9 during an unrelated, previously begun industrywide inspection
of DC-9 planes with 55,000 or more landings.
   Leonard said tiny, nonhazardous cracks are found in aircraft
every day during routine inspections.
   ``This is not an Eastern-exclusive problem. It's absolutely
consistent with the industry,'' Leonard said.
   He also said the age of the aircraft was being overemphasized and
he said a plane's age doesn't necessarily affect its safety.
   The tear on the flight Monday was from inside an overlap of
aluminum on the fuselage, ``a new twist,'' Upton said. The routine
visual inspections conducted after 1,100 landings couldn't detect
such ``inside-out'' tearing, he said.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said it will take about a
month for the electrical testing to be completed on the 46 planes.
   By then, the company would know better the cause of the tear that
forced Monday's emergency landing and will adjust its maintenance
program accordingly, she said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration will propose in January that
operators of older 727s be required to replace some rivets, agency
spokesman Dave Duff said Wednesday. Duff said it had not been
determined how many airplanes would be covered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
