<DOCNO> AP881229-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1837EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Scene 2ndLd-Writethru a0685 12-29 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Scene, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0685,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Calls at Church Where Crewman's Body Fell</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs explaining why brother wanted Bible,
PICKS UP 3rd pvs `The country...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LOC7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brother of a Pan Am crewman came
seeking a Bible on Thursday from the church near the spot where the
cockpit of Flight 103 fell.
   ``I said he could take the Bibles or take anything else he
thought might help,'' said the Rev. Cameron Gibson of Tundergarth
Parish Church. ``He had free rein to take what he wanted.''
   The brother wanted to take the Bible ``to his old mother in
America as a memento of near where her son had died,'' Gibson said.
   The country church is three miles east of Lockerbie, where the
jumbo jet crashed Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and leaving
11 people on the ground missing and presumed dead.
   Investigators said the crash was caused by a bomb in the cargo
hold.
   John Wagner, brother of First Officer Raymond Wagner, 52, of
Pennington, N.J., had approached police in Lockerbie about obtaining
two prayer books.
   Gibson said there were no prayer books in the Calvinist Church of
Scotland, but that he was welcome to take King James Bibles.
   The bodies of Wagner and pilot James Bruce MacQuarrie, 55, of
Kensington, N.H., were among the first to be released this week to
next-of-kin.
   Royal Engineers using circular saws cut the nose of the plane
into sections for transport to the Air Accident Investigation
Branch's facility in Farnborough in southern England.
   The nose, still displaying the plane's designation Clipper Maid
of the Seas, is the largest piece of wreckage and one of the few
immediately recognizable as part of an aircraft.
   The engineers and members of the Royal Highland Fusiliers are
billeted in the Tundergarth church. The nose fell just beyond the
churchyard wall.
   Several relatives of the dead came to the site with flowers on
Thursday.
   Despite the disaster, the church went ahead with its Christmas
service, ``one of the most difficult I have ever had to prepare in
the 26 years of my ministry,'' Gibson said.
   ``The only thing I could possibly tell them was God was with us.''
   Gibson, like other ministers and priests in the area, has taken
on an unexpected burden of counseling grief-stricken parishioners
and relatives of the dead.
   Social workers who have also been counseling townspeople say they
have encountered some who refused to face up to the disaster.
   ``We are experiencing a typical part of the Scots' personality
which says `We don't want help,''' said Tom McMenamy, director of
the regional department of social work.
   ``People are denying the event happened at all and we have got to
make sure they don't stay like that. ...
   ``The fact it was a bomb gives them a focus for anger. They know
now how it happened, but they don't know who did it; but it is much
healthier to know how something happened.''
   It may be months before the town of 2,500 people regains its
normal appearance. John Orr, the detective who is heading a criminal
investigation based in Lockerbie, said he was prepared for a long
and painstaking operation.
   As the search continues, helicopters are frequently overhead, and
military and rescue vehicles jam the streets.
   Outside the Town Hall, being used as a temporary morgue, the pile
of flowers from relatives of the dead and from sympathizers in
several countries has grown daily.
   In private meetings arranged for residents of damaged areas,
several people have complained about being questioned by some of the
dozens of reporters on the scene, according to a local newspaper,
the Annandale Herald.
   ``There's been no Christmas in Lockerbie,'' one young man said
Wednesday night as he edged away from a camera crew. ``I don't want
to talk about it. No one wants to talk about it.''
   Leslie Jardine, a spokesman for the social work department, said
nearly $360,000 had been collected for relief work in Lockerbie.
More than half that amount came from Pan Am and its insurer.
   The local parish of the Church of Scotland is planning a memorial
service Jan. 4, and arrangements have been made to seat expected
overflow crowds in other halls and churches.
   The Rev. John Owen, a Church of Scotland minister from nearby
Lochmaben, wrote in the ``Reflections'' column of the Annandale
Herald, that there were no easy answers to the disaster.
   ``If you want truth, take your coat off and sit down. This will
take whatever time truth takes,'' he wrote.
   ``There is a time for everything, and when the time comes to
speak of other things we will. Now we need to give ourselves a time
to mourn.''
</TEXT>
