<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eliana'sReunion     12-29 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eliana's Reunion,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child With AIDS To Get Visit From Brothers, Sisters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven-year-old AIDS victim Eliana Martinez
will be reunited with her two brothers and two sisters next week
when the siblings are flown here from Puerto Rico by the Make-A-Wish
Foundation.
   The visiting children are 8 to 12 years old and live with two
sets of adoptive parents. They will be accompanied by their mothers
and stay at a hotel for about five days, officials said.
   Eliana, who acquired AIDS through blood transfusions shortly
after her premature birth, has become widely known through her
mother's court battles to enroll her in a public school.
   School officials barred the girl from class, saying she might
transmit the AIDS virus because she is mentally impaired and not
toilet trained. A federal judge ruled Eliana could attend classes if
she were isolated in a glass booth.
   The child's adoptive mother, Rosa Martinez, fought that decision,
saying she refused to let the girl ``sit in a cage.'' A federal
appeals court has ordered hearings to determine whether the
youngster poses a health threat.
   Eliana, who speaks through sign language, may not understand that
the four children coming to visit are her biological brothers and
sisters, her mother said Wednesday.
   ``I'm going to tell her she's going to have children playing with
her,'' said Ms. Martinez. ``She doesn't know what to think of little
people. I don't even know if she realizes she is one.''
   All but the eldest of the children were taken from their parents
in Puerto Rico at birth, said Ms. Martinez, who adopted Eliana in
1982 after hearing a radio appeal for someone to take in a homeless
toddler.
   ``Their parents were the equivalent of the homeless people here.
The oldest got to live with them about three months'' but was
neglected and then placed with a welfare agency.
   Eliana's siblings know who their baby sister is from seeing her
on television and in the newspapers, said Ms. Martinez. She said
their mothers have encouraged them to write Eliana.
   The little girl was hospitalized with pneumonia and congestive
heart failure for a week in early December but has recovered, said
Ms. Martinez, who added, ``She's into everything.
   ``I just want her to have children to play with. I don't know how
she'll react,'' said Ms. Martinez. ``She's got no social skills.''
   The children and their adoptive parents are expected to arrive on
Jan. 2.
   The group plans a trip to Walt Disney World, outings to parks
``and quiet evenings at home with Eliana,'' said Ms. Martinez.
   The Make-A-Wish Foundation tries to made dreams come true for
dying children.
</TEXT>
