<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-AirSecurity     12-29 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Air Security,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Official Blames U.S. for Encouraging Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's deputy foreign minister on Thursday
sought to tie the PLO to the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 and blamed
the U.S. decision to talk to the guerrilla organization for
encouraging international terrorism.
   The statement by Binyamin Netanyahu, a leading member of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc, follows repeated Israeli
criticism of the United States for including Yasser Arafat and the
Palestine Liberation Organization in the Middle East peace process.
   ``By having these kinds of talks ... you are sending a message, a
very clear message, that terrorism pays,'' Netanyahu told a news
conference. ``The American talks with the PLO have seriously
weakenened the American effort against terrorism.''
   He said suspicion in the Dec. 21 Pan Am bombing focused on groups
experienced with the type of explosives used in the blast, including
the PLO and Syria.
   However, he said he had no firm information on who was to blame
for the bombing, and an Israeli security expert said Arafat's
mainstream PLO faction was ``not a likely candidate.''
   Netanyahu's comments echoed Shamir's, who suggested Tuesday that
Washington's decision was encouraging renewed infiltration attacks
along the Israeli border. Shamir said the American move ``encouraged
the tendency of violent acts against Israel.''
   A government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
earlier this week that a major Israeli foreign policy goal would be
to reverse Washington's decision to talk to the PLO.
   On Thursday, Netanyahu called the PLO ``the foremost practitioner
of aviation terrorism.'' It was responsible for the first airliner
hijacking, the first destruction of a passenger plane in midair and
the first gun and grenade attack on passengers, he said.
   ``I say the PLO, I mean Fatah, I mean Arafat,'' he said,
referring to the PLO chief's mainstream guerrilla group.
   Netanyahu spoke at a news conference called to announce an
international seminar on airline security in February in Tel Aviv.
The conference focused on the bombing of the Pan Am jet over
Scotland in which more than 260 people died in the air and on the
ground.
   Ariel Merari, an Israeli terrorism expert, told reporters at the
news conference that he doubted the mainstream PLO would have
carried out the attack when Arafat is making statements about peace
with Israel.
   ``I don't think the present political situation is such that the
PLO would sponsor such an attack,'' he said. ``My guess is at least
for a while they'll refrain from international terrorism because it
is politically counterproductive.''
   Merari, director of a project on terrorism at Tel Aviv
University, said earlier he believed the Pan Am attackers probably
were radical PLO factions opposed to Arafat's more moderate stands.
   He said it was such splinter groups that actually carried out the
first hijacking and first blowing up of a plane in midair, not
Arafat's Fatah.
   Israel began criticizing the United States after Secretary of
State George Shultz announced Dec. 14 that the PLO had met American
demands for inclusion in the peace process by recognizing Israel and
renouncing terrorism.
   Israel's new government included in its political program a
refusal to negotiate with the PLO, which it views as a terrorist
organization.
</TEXT>
