<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SowetoStudents     12-29 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soweto Students,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No `A' Students in Soweto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thabo Moloi, 17, had his
picture printed on the front page of The Sowetan newspaper Thursday,
the only high school student in the township of 2.5 million to
graduate with a ``B'' grade average.
   There were no ``A'' students among the 4,508 who took their final
examinations in Soweto. Only five of all South Africa's black
students had ``A'' averages.
   Nationwide, 57.4 percent of the 170,966 full-time black high
school students who wrote final exams passed, a slight improvement
over last year's 56.9 percent. In Soweto, 37.8 percent of all high
school seniors passed, an increase over last year's 32 percent.
   ``There is no reason to believe that black children are less
intelligent than whites. ... But year after year the black
matriculation results are disastrous,'' said The Sowetan in an
editorial.
   ``The sensible view surely should be to improve black education.
Blacks will outnumber whites in ever-increasing numbers as we reach
the turn of the century. Black skills will be needed with
ever-increasing desperation,'' The Sowetan said.
   In the 1950s, under legislation supporting the apartheid system
of race separation, the white government instituted an inferior
education system for blacks and prohibited them from attending
missionary and other private schools where most of today's black
leaders received their education.
   Today the government says its standards for black education are
the same as for whites. But since resources are allocated by race,
the amount of money spent on a white child's education is five times
that spent on a black.
   Black schools also have been wracked by boycotts since nationwide
unrest broke out in 1984. Although there was no boycott this year,
graduating students had years of material with which to catch up.
Another disadvantage is that many of their teachers themselves have
not passed the high school graduation examination.
</TEXT>
