<HEAD>With AM-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan pledged Thursday that the
United States would make ``every effort'' to discover who was
responsible for last week's bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 that killed
259 people in the air and 11 on the ground in Scotland.
   ``Now that we know definitely that it was a bomb, we're going to
make every effort we can to find out who was guilty of this savage
and tragic thing and bring them to justice,'' Reagan said at Los
Angeles International Airport before he boarded Air Force One to
head to Palm Springs.
   Asked whether he thought the Pan Am attack was perpetrated by
terrorists, Reagan said it seemed to be, ``but we're going to have
to have more details. We're doing everything we can to find them.''
   As his wife, Nancy, stood off the side, Reagan expressed sympathy
for the families of those who died and said that whoever was
responsible for the deaths would be charged with murder.
   The Reagans were headed for the desert estate of publisher Walter
Annenberg, the former ambassador to Britain. The Reagans will remain
there until Monday, when they are to return to Los Angeles to
complete their two-week California vacation.
