<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Economy     12-29 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Economy,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Premier Warns of Economic Doldrums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski told
Poland in a televised address that fighting inflation will be the
government's top priority next year, and he appealed to consumers
not to hoard scarce goods.
   He also noted in a Wednesday night broadcast that the country's
economic reform policy is based on competition. Some people would be
better off under the reforms, but others would lose ground, he
cautioned.
   ``We of course have to be aware of this problem. We have to put
on the agenda the problem of caring for the weakest,'' he said.
   Rakowski said the government hopes to limit inflation to 20
percent next year. However, officially published estimates have
projected an overall inflation rate of 50 percent in 1989, compared
with 60 to 70 percent in 1988.
   Incomes have outstripped available supplies. Consumer hoarding of
limited goods, such as gasoline and paper supplies, exacerbates
shortages in stores.
   Rakowski appealed to Poles to observe ``the principle of reason.''
   ``It is necessary to limit demand in our conditions,'' he said.
``I think I should ask citizens not to stock up needlessly. It
really makes no sense.''
   Rakowski was making the fifth in a series of informal TV
addresses since he became premier Sept. 27.
</TEXT>
