<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide says Experts Studying Provisional Palestinian Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO's official spokesman said Thursday
that a special committee of experts has started discussing possible
formation of a provisional Palestinian government.
   Spokesman Ahmed Abdul Rahman told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview that the Palestinian experts in international
law and government will report their findings to the Palestine
Liberation Organization's Executive Committee within a month.
   He said a provisional government could be expected to represent
the Palestinians at the proposed international conference on Middle
East peace.
   ``Everything depends on the outcome of the effort to form a
preparatory committee for the international conference. If all goes
well we will immediately proclaim the provisional government,'' he
said.
   The Palestinian National Council, the PLO's legislature, declared
an independent Palestinian state at its meeting in November. It
passed a resolution authorizing the Executive Committee, the PLO's
governing body, to look into the feasibility of forming a
provisional government.
   In Helsinki, Finland, the Foreign Ministry said Thursday that the
government has officially invited PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat to
visit, a move seen by some newspapers as signalling a policy shift
toward the PLO.
   An official of the PLO information office in Helsinki, who spoke
to the AP on condition his name not be used, said Arafat accepted
the invitation and was likely to go to Finland within a month.
   But Foreign Ministry official Pertti Torstila said a formal reply
was still awaited and details had not been worked out yet.
   Israeli Embassy spokesman Ehud Eitam said the invitation ``does
not contribute to the Middle East peace process.''
   The PLO official said Arafat was expected to meet President Mauno
Koivisto, Prime Minister Harri Holkeri and Foreign Minister Kalevi
Sorsa.
   Finland has refused to officially recognize the PLO, although it
allowed the Palestinian umbrella group to establish an office in
Helsinki five years ago.
   King Hussein of Jordan meanwhile was quoted as saying in an
interview released Thursday that the U.S. decision to begin a
dialogue with the PLO was ``a good start.''
   The London-based magazine Al-Hawadeth also quoted the monarch as
saying he expects President-elect George Bush to make more headway
in the Middle East because Bush has more experience and interest in
world problems.
   ``The world is beginning to face solving the Palestinian problem,
which is the most dangerous problem. I think the world will try to
solve it through an international peace conference,'' Hussein was
quoted as saying.
   ``America during ... Bush's term will be different from America
during President Reagan's term.
   ``President Reagan did not care for the Middle East problem, he
knew little about it, but Bush I think has a good experience in
world problems.''
   The interview in Arabic was translated by the AP in Cyprus.
   In Jordan's capital of Amman Thursday, Foreign Minister Marwan
Kassem met with PLO Executive Committee members Mahmoud Abbas and
Yasser Abed-Rabboo to discuss efforts for Arab-Israeli peace, the
official Jordan news agency Petra reported.
