<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia-Dissident     12-29 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Dissident,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Gets Passport After Eight Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Yugoslav human rights
activist and dissident, Dobroslav Paraga, said he was granted a
passport to travel abroad on Thursday, eight years after his
passport was taken away from him.
   He told The Associated Press the passport was delivered to him in
this Slovenian capital following his 16-day hunger strike and
appeals by Yugoslav intellectuals, including Cardinal Franjo
Kuharic, head of the Roman Catholic Church of Croatia.
   The last time Paraga requested the passport was when West German
President Richard von Weizsaecker invited him to attend a Dec. 12
meeting in Bonn organized by Amnesty International to mark the 40th
anniversary of the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights.
   Asked about his travel plans, Paraga said in his telephone
interview: ``Now that I missed the meeting with Weizsaecker, I have
no other invitation or financial means to travel abroad.''
   He was arrested in 1980 and sentenced to four years' imprisonment
for collecting signatures on a petition calling for authorities to
free political prisoners.
   After his release, he published an account of his prison
experiences in which he claimed political offenders routinely are
mistreated by prison guards.
   In April 1987, he received a 6-month suspended sentence on
charges of spreading false information about treatment of political
prisoners.
   Paraga said his brother Domagoj has not yet received a passport
taken away when Paraga was arrested eight years ago.
   ``Hundreds of former political prisoners are still being denied
that right,'' he said.
   In an apparent easing of restraints, Yugoslavia's collective
federal presidency on Tuesday granted amnesty to 25 prisoners jailed
for political offenses.
   Tanjug, the state news agency, said 68 such prisoners were freed
this year.
   The vast majority of Yugoslavs routinely get passports and are
free to travel abroad.
</TEXT>
