<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunken Ship, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0709,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Search For Crewmen Missing From Capsized Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to clarify that one seaman was dead when
pulled from the water; updates with post-mortem; picks up 7th graf
pvs: `The container ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers plucked five seamen from 25-foot swells in
the stormy North Atlantic on Thursday, but one was dead and another
died and six others were missing after their 254-foot ship sank, the
Coast Guard said.
   The ship Lloyd Bermuda sank Wednesday night 160 miles south of
Nantucket and 200 miles east of New Jersey when its cargo shifted in
weather that was ``nothing short of horrendous,'' said Coast Guard
spokesman Lt. Paul Wolf.
   ``The last of the crew to get off said they watched the ship
sink,'' Wolf said.
   Rescuers searching for survivors were hindered by heavy rains, 40
to 45 mph winds and 25-foot seas, the Coast Guard said.
   At first light Thursday, a Navy pilot spotted what he thought was
a man waving from a life raft, but when rescuers reached the raft
they found nobody on board, Wolf said.
   Three hours later, rescuers spotted another man but, because of
choppy seas and floating debris, could not get close enough to tell
if he was alive. By the time a rescue helicopter reached him four
hours later, the man was floating face down, Coast Guard Petty
Officer Brandy Ian said.
   His body was recovered and taken to Nantucket Island for
post-mortem examination by a state medical examiner.
   The container ship was one of the three main vessels that bring
food and other supplies to Bermuda, said Ian Clark, harbor master in
Hamilton, Bermuda.
   The captain of the ship was American and the crew was a mix of
nationalities, John W. Moore of the Meyer Agencies Ltd., the ship's
agent in Bermuda, said in a telephone interview from Hamilton.
   The Lloyd Bermuda, registered in Cyprus, made a run to Bermuda
every week, and had left Port Elizabeth, N.J., Tuesday night, Moore
said.
   The Rev. Barbara Crafton, an Episcopal priest at the Seamen's
Church Institute Center in Port Newark, N.J., who spent Christmas
with the men before their ship departed, said most were from Central
America and the Philippines.
   Wolf said crew members told him they abandoned ship in two
lifeboats, but only one was recovered.
   Shortly after midnight Wednesday a Coast Guard jet spotted three
people in the water waving flashlights. Rescuers aboard the merchant
ship Eagle were able to pull two from the water about 1:45 a.m. but
the third ``slipped from his life jacket, fell back into the water
and was not seen again by his rescuers,'' Wolf said.
   The two men were treated for mild hypothermia but were otherwise
unharmed. Their identies were not released.
   About 4 a.m., Coast Guard frogmen rescued two more men drifting
in the water without life rafts. They were flown by helicopter to
Falmouth Hospital, but one, who was not identified, was pronounced
dead on arrival, apparently of hypothermia, or loss of body heat, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
   The other man, Dario Macio-Lopez, 35, was in fair condition and
was being treated for hypothermia, spokeswoman Marie Johnson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1946EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Palme     12-29 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Palme,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weapons Linked to Man Held in Palme Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have seized several large-caliber
pistols that could be linked to a suspect accused of killing Prime
Minister Olof Palme, the Dagens Nyheter newspaper reported Thursday.
   The murder weapon has been a key piece of missing evidence in the
nearly 3-year-old case.
   The paper quoted Chief Detective Hans Olvebro as saying a number
of weapons were test-fired to compare the slugs with those found at
the scene of the assassination. Only some were ruled out as the
murder weapon, he said.
   Christer Pettersson, 41, the man arrested on Dec. 14, could have
had access to the pistols, Dagens Nyheter said.
   Pettersson, who has a long history of violent crime and of drug
and alcohol abuse, was to remain in custody until Friday.
Prosecutors said they will seek an extension from the courts.
   Several witnesses reportedly have identified Pettersson, with
varying degrees of certainty, as being at the scene when Palme was
shot while walking home with his wife Lisbet from a Stockholm movie
theater on Feb. 28, 1986. Mrs. Palme is the key witness.
   Two bullets were found at the scene, but a massive search failed
to turn up the weapon itself.
</TEXT>
