<HEAD>Inmate: Prisons Filled With TV Addicts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, `Warden Don ..., with addtional
warden quotes, ADDS time element; picks up 5th graf: `About 40 ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate who says the state is turning
prisoners into TV addicts failed in a bid to have televisions banned
behind bars.
   ``Wisconsin prisons are chock-full of inmates who are completely
addicted to television, soap operas and all,'' Adrian Lomax, an
inmate at an Oshkosh prison, said in a letter to The Milwaukee
Journal. ``Most male inmates spend almost all their free time
watching television.''
   Without television, inmates would be more likely to better
themselves and ``develop the tools necessary to become productive
members of society,'' he said.
   Warden Don Gudmanson rejected the complaint filed Nov. 7, and an
appeal to the state health and social services secretary also
failed. Gudmanson said television has a pacifying influence and
gives inmates something to do in their idle time.
   ``I don't think the inmates are any more addicted to TV than
anyone else in the community. I think watching television is a
healthy release,'' Gudmanson said Thursday. ``I don't know of any
prison in the country that doesn't allow personal televisions.''
   About 40 percent of the 400 inmates at Oshkosh have personal TV
sets, which are permitted as long as the screen is no larger than 13
inches and speakers are disconnected and headphones used. TV sets
are also in the prison day rooms.
   Lomax, who is serving a life sentence for murder, taught himself
Spanish while behind bars, and his prison job is translating prison
manuals into Spanish for Hispanic inmates. He had predicted his
request would not get far.
   A frequent filer of inmate complaints, Lomax has three others
pending, but officials said they are kept confidential unless
revealed by the inmate.
   ``He's come up with a lot of good ideas, but he's come up with
some bad ones, too,'' Gudmanson said.
</TEXT>
