<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BaseClosings-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0682 12-29 0893</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0682,0912</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Towns Decry Base Closings, Others Celebrate Reprieve</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf, `I would...' to UPDATE with
more reaction; picks up 9th graf: `New York ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Predictions ranged from economic disaster to inconvenience as
communities speculated Thursday on how they would be affected by a
federal commission's recommendation to close or reorganize 145
military installations.
   For towns whose military bases were spared or even slated to
expand, the commission's report brought unalloyed relief.
   The commission called for closing 34 installations, partially
closing five others and reorganizing 54 others that would get new
missions and additional personnel. The panel said the measures would
save $5.6 billion over 20 years.
   California was the state most affected by the Commission on Base
Realignment and Closure report, which recommended that six
installations be shut: Norton, George and Mather air force bases,
the Presidio Army Base, Hamilton Army Air Field and the Salton Sea
Test Base.
   Plans to build Hunter's Point Naval Station at San Francisco also
would be scrapped if the panel's report is approved by Congress.
   ``The closure of Mather will certainly have an adverse economic
impact on our community,'' said Paul Salemi, a Sacramento
Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce official. ``If you look at an
industry that employs close to 7,000 people and has a payroll of
$154 million, what else can you say?''
   The shutdown of George, an air base in the desert 70 miles
northeast of Los Angeles, would signal hard times for the
surrounding communities, where the base contributes an estimated
$516 million to the economy, said U.S. Rep. Jerry Lewis.
   ``I would dread the fiscal impact it would have on the entire
high desert,'' said Adelanto City Administrator Pat Chamberlaine.
   ``We just won't survive,'' said Anita Hilton, a longtime employee
of Wright Cleaners, an establishment adjacent to Fort Dix, N.J.,
that advertises ``3 Hour Service For Fatigues And Khakis.''
   ``More than 95 percent of our business is Army. If they cut back
Fort Dix, we'll all be looking for new jobs,'' she said.
   Similar sentiments echoed through Wrightstown's four-block
downtown strip, which begins at the Fort Dix boundary and includes
several bars, a tatoo parlor, fast food restaurants, a store called
GI Joe's and a barber shop that advertises military haircuts. The
area also has a high school that is being expanded at a cost of $16
million to serve military families, school board President Thomas
Bridge said.
   New York City, which has three military installations within its
city limits, would lose one, a largely administrative naval station
in Brooklyn, but personnel would simply move to a new base on Staten
Island 20 miles away.
   ``On balance it could have been a lot worse,'' said Rep. Guy
Molinari, a Republican whose district includes the Staten Island
port.
   For some, effects of a facility closing were impossible to
predict.
   ``We've never been through one of these,'' said Col. Walt Siders,
a spokesman for the Arizona National Guard, which operates the
Navajo Army Depot slated for closing. ``It came as a complete
surprise when we heard about it on the radio this morning.''
   Salt Lake City Mayor Palmer DePaulis said he wasn't surprised the
commission recommended closing historic Fort Douglas, built in 1862
to protect stagecoach travelers and keep watch on Mormon settlers.
   It had long been criticized as contributing little to the
nation's defense.
   He said the fort, with 44 buildings registered as national
historic landmarks, would ``be perfect for an Olympic village'' if
the city is selected as host of the 1998 Winter Olympic Games.
   For many the states, the commission news was a mix of good and
bad.
   In Massachusetts, officials and merchants in Ayer were relieved
that the Fort Devens Army Base escaped the budget ax, but Watertown
residents lamented the passing of an Army facility that has been a
neighbor since the War of 1812.
   The Army Materials Technology Laboratory in Watertown, which
oversees development of metals and other materials for use in
weapons, armor, bridges and military structures, had long been
rumored to be on the verge of closing.
   Harold Laye, an employee since 1956, said workers regarded former
House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill to be the lab's protector.
O'Neill retired two years ago. ``We knew it was coming,'' Laye said.
``It's a sad day.''
   Ayers residents found that Fort Devens, also mentioned as a
candidate for closing, was instead recommended for enlargement. ``I
think we ought to be celebrating today,'' said Ed Kelley, owner of a
card shop and a director of the chamber of commerce. ``It's the best
news we could have for a New Years.''
   In Virginia, Cameron Station in Alexandria and the Defense
Mapping Agency in Herndon were recommended for closing, but state
leaders were relieved that four larger bases considered vulnerable
were untouched: Fort Monroe in Hampton, Fort Pickett in Blackstone,
Fort Lee in Petersburg and Vint Hill Farms near Warrenton.
   Fort Belvoir in Fairfax County was recommended for a major
expansion.
   ``I am extremely happy,'' said Arlene Crittenden, a dress shop
owner in Hampton Roads who had led efforts to save nearby Fort
Monroe. ``I don't even care if I sell a dress today.'' She said
community leaders would go ahead with plans for a party Thursday
night to celebrate the fort's survival.
</TEXT>
