<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1948EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-29 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet and Windy in the West, Icy Temperatures in the North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A windy and sometimes wet day in the West kept people indoors
Thursday, while freezing temperatures did the trick along the
nation's northern tier.
   A cold front brought rain to the Pacific Northwest, especially
along the coast, and warnings of freezing rain and snow were posted
inland. At Astoria, Ore., more than an inch and a quarter of rain
fell in six hours Thursday morning.
   In the mountains of northern California and western Nevada, a
winter storm watch was posted for Friday, in anticipation of up to 2
feet of new snow.
   Farther east, high winds buffeted the eastern slopes of the
Rockies in Montana and Wyoming. Wind gusts greater than 80 mph were
reported in southeastern Wyoming's Curt Gowdy State Park near
Cheyenne.
   In southern California, gusty Santa Ana winds howled again, with
advisories posted for mountain areas in the northern part of the
region and along the canyons east of Los Angeles.
   Unseasonably cold weather chilled the Southwest as half a dozen
cities reported record low temperatures for the date, including
Tucson, Ariz., where the 20-degree reading broke the record of 23
set in 1966. A freeze warning was posted for part of the Arizona
desert.
   Icy temperatures gripped the northern United States from New
England and the Ohio Valley across the Great Lakes region and middle
and upper Mississippi Valley to the northern and central Plains.
Afternoon readings were in the single digits or below zero across
much of the area from eastern Montana to Wisconsin and Michigan's
Upper Peninsula.
   The warm spots were Texas' lower Rio Grande Valley, where it was
in the 60s, and the Florida Peninsula, where it was generally in the
60s and 70s.
   Snow showers dampened the Great Lakes area, while skies were
sunny from the Southwest to the central Plains. Partly cloudy to
cloudy skies prevailed elsewhere.
   The overnight low for the nation was 33 degrees below zero at
Hibbing, Minn.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees below zero at Ely and International Falls, both in
Minnesota, to 83 degrees at Sanford, Fla.
   On Friday, rain and snow were expected to spread from the
northern and central Pacific coast to the northern Rockies, with
heavy snow possible at higher elevations. Light snow was forecast
for the north-central states and the Great Lakes region. Showers and
thunderstorms were predicted from southern Texas and the central
Gulf coast into the lower Mississippi Valley, with scattered rain
and snow showers north along the river valley into the Ohio Valley.
Elsewhere, it will be fair to partly sunny.
   Temperatures were expected to stay below 32 degrees throughout
the day from the northern Plateau and central Rockies through the
Dakotas and much of the Great Lakes to northern New England. The
forecast called for temperatures to rise into the 50s and low 60s
from the central coast of California to southern Arizona and from
the Rio Grande Valley to the southern Atlantic coast, but reach the
70s and low 80s in Florida.
</TEXT>
