<2ND_LINE>AM-Seat Belts,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Says 1988 Pontiac LeMans Seat Belt Buckles May Be Defective</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you own a 1988 Pontiac LeMans, your seat
belt buckles may be defective and should be replaced, the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Thursday.
   LeMans owners should contact their dealers to have the buckles
replaced ``as soon as possible,'' NHTSA administrator Diane K. Steed
said in a statement.
   There will be no charge for the replacements.
   ``To our knowledge, no one has yet been injured, but the
potential exists for safety belt failure at the worst possible
moment,'' said Steed.
   On Dec. 9, General Motors recalled about 85,000 of the cars to
replace the defective buckles because they may appear to be latched
when they are not.
   NHTSA said 46 percent of Americans use safety belts, and the
devices saved about 4,000 lives in 1987.
