<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Goodbye, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Find Bodies Of Missing Grandfather, Grandson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 12th graf, `Instead of ..., to ADD
quotes from mother; picks up 13th graf: `After Ms. ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollis Day gave his daughter an extra warm
hug the last morning of her Christmas visit and told her he would
watch her 2-year-old handicapped son, Dylan, while she packed for
the trip home.
   The 75-year-old man then drove off with his only grandson,
leaving a note that said only: ``Gramps and Dylan have gone bye-bye
together.''
   On Thursday, two days later, Hollis Day and his grandson were
found shot to death in a locked vehicle on wooded, family-owned land
50 miles away, Sheriff Bill Logan said. The gun was near the bodies.
Both were shot in the head.
   ``At this point, the evidence appears consistent with a
homicide-suicide theory,'' Logan said. Autopsies were scheduled for
Friday.
   Debbie Day said she had realized a few hours after her father
left with Dylan that he may have been saying goodbye forever. ``He
told me what a wonderful girl and mother I was,'' she said of the
exchange Tuesday.
   Ms. Day, 40, said she called police a few hours after her father
left.
   ``It's hard to believe he would hurt anybody, much less his
grandson, but he'd written me a number of letters, talking about
dreams he'd had about flying with Dylan into the hereafter,'' Ms.
Day said. ``He had a hard time with the fact the boy was such a
burden to me.
   ``He wasn't a burden to me because I love him, but he wanted me
to be free of this responsibility, which was all-consuming.''
   Day had tried to give his daughter some time off, most recently
offering to hire a nurse or a nanny for the boy while she went on a
Hawaiian vacation.
   Dylan was developmentally disabled, his mother said. He couldn't
walk or talk, and the right side of his body was limp because of
palsy. Hollis Day was scheduled for cataract surgery Thursday and
was anxious about his own future, she said.
   ``Dad was going to watch my little boy for a few minutes while I
packed'' to return home to Portland, Ore., with Dylan and his
father, Al Berreth, said Ms. Day. They had been visiting her father,
the retired president of a clothing company, and his wife, Uwarda,
for Christmas.
   Instead of watching Dylan, Day bundled the pajama-clad boy in a
coat and hat, loaded the tot into his Jeep Wagoneer and took off.
   ``My son was beginning to talk. He was doing just fine,'' said
Ms. Day, who said Dylan was in a hospital therapy program.
   ``He was a gregarious, outgoing, happy, loving, affectionate
child. He was a beautiful child. He had all the support and love of
both parents and all of his family members,'' she said.
   Ms. Day said she believes her father was trying to help.
   ``He was the kind of person who didn't want to be burdened in his
own life and didn't want me to be burdened by my child,'' Ms. Day
said.
   ``When you have a handicapped child they're a little bit more
work and he thought that having a child like that would be a total
altering of my lifestyle that he didn't want to see imposed upon a
daughter that he loved dearly. But it wasn't in my wildest dreams
that he'd do this.''
   After Ms. Day called police, law enforcement authorities
statewide were alerted. Logan said a family member called his office
Wednesday and asked for a search of the family property near
Packwood in the Cascade Mountains.
   ``It was definitely premeditated,'' Ms. Day said before the pair
was found. ``He had the car all warmed up and ready to go so he
could sneak my little boy out of the house.''
</TEXT>
