<HEAD>Libyan Ambassador Predicts Better Ties with Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Libyan ambassador to Tunisia was quoted
Thursday as saying George Bush's administration may usher in better
relations between America and Libya, which are at odds over
terrorism and chemical warfare.
   The weekly magazine Realites quoted Ambassador Abdelati Laabidi
as saying in an interview that Libyan-U.S. relations may soon ``make
a slight improvement'' with Bush as president.
   Libya was ``ready for any dialogue which will succeed in opening
up better relations with Washington,'' the magazine quoted him as
saying.
   It said Laabidi repeated Libyan denials of U.S. charges that a
remote desert factory is producing chemical arms and insisted the
factory makes only medicines.
   President Reagan has threatened military action against the plant.
   The ambassador said Tunisia might eventually help mediate the
dispute, according to Realites.
   The ambassador also was quoted as saying Libya did not support
terrorism but ``would not stop at anything to support the just
causes of Palestine, Namibia, etc.''
   Separate guerrilla groups have been fighting to establish a
Palestinian state and to win independence for South African-ruled
Namibia. A U.N.-brokered accord providing for Namibian independence
was signed this month.
   The United States bombed Libya in 1986 for terrorism it blamed on
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   This week, suspicion fell on Libya when British authorities
announced that Pan Am Flight 103 crashed on Dec. 21 because of a
bomb explosion.
   Terrorism specialists said Abu Nidal's Fatah Revolutionary
Council, a Palestinian guerrilla group allied with Libya, may have
planted the explosive.
   Other possible culprits mentioned included professional assassins
recruited by Libya or Syria.
