<DOCNO> AP881229-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 2043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TowingIndictments     12-29 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Towing Indictments,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18 Indicted in Illegal Towing and Insurance Fraud Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen people, including six current or former
police officers, were indicted Thursday on 1,500 charges in an
alleged towing scam that bilked at least 600 people from 1982 to
1987, authorities said.
   Sgt. William H. Kelley Jr., 51, head of the Boston police auto
theft unit, was charged with six counts of conspiracy, perjury and
writing a false police report, according to indictments returned by
a Suffolk County grand jury.
   The suspects allegedly participated in several schemes to tow
legally and illegally parked cars and overcharge owners who
retrieved them, said David Rodman, a spokesman for Suffolk County
District Attorney Newman Flanagan.
   ``I was very disturbed by the arrogance and disrespectful
attitude that some police officers had _ a total disregard for the
public trust,'' Boston Police Commissioner Francis X. Roache said.
``It really sickens me.''
   Also indicted were three other Boston police officers, one
Metropolitan District Commission police officer, one former Boston
police captain, two employees of the city's abandoned car division,
two former inspectors at the state Registry of Motor Vehicles, a
special agent with the National Auto Theft Bureau and the owners of
two city garages.
   The defendants face charges ranging from larceny to concealing
stolen motor vehicles to perjury, conspiracy and insurance fraud,
according to the indictments.
   Kelley and Officer William R. Cantin, 40, who was indicted on 535
charges, have been suspended without pay, Boston police spokesman
Jim Jordan said.
   Two other indicted officers, Peter Doherty, 47, and John Ulrich,
44, were put on administrative leave guns pending a departmental
hearing, Jordan said.
   The indictments cap a two-year investigation by the Suffolk
County district attorney's office with help from the Boston Police
Anti-Corruption Unit, the MDC police and other law enforcement
agencies, officials said.
   Rodman said one alleged scheme profited from different charges
levied on cars towed by the Boston police and those towed by the
Registry of Motor Vehicles, which charges more to retrieve cars,
Rodman said.
   He said Boston police would tow a car that was parked illegally
but the defendants would tell the owner the car had been towed by
the registry.
   Another scheme, Rodman said, would be to tow a legally parked car
and wait several weeks after the owner reported it stolen to collect
daily storage charges, often as much as $600.
   He said the scheme affected at least 600 people. The indictment
does not say how much money was lost in the alleged schemes.
</TEXT>
