<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CaliforniaFirings 1stLd-Writethru a0683 12-29 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-California Firings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Restricts Suits by Fired Employees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Chief Justice ..., with 2 grafs to give
context of `commercial stability' quote; picks up 5th graf: `The
court ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court, citing the
need for ``commercial stability,'' on Thursday limited the right of
wrongfully fired employees to collect big damage awards.
   The ruling by the conservative-dominated court moved away from
the course the California judiciary has taken since 1980, when a
court then controlled by liberals led the nation in restricting an
employer's right to fire at will.
   The court ruled 4-3 that a worker who is fired without good
cause, in violation of a company's express or implied promise, can
sue only for reinstatement and back pay, not for emotional distress
and punitive damages.
   ``Initially, predictability of the consequences of actions
related to employment contracts is important to commercial
stability,'' wrote Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas in the majority
decision.
   ``In order to achieve such stability, it is also important that
employers not be unduly deprived of discretion to dismiss an
employee by the fear that doing so will give rise to potential tort
recovery (for additional damages) in every case,'' the opinion said.
   The court allowed employees to seek additional damages when their
firings involved violations of public policy, such as a worker's
refusal to break a law.
   Justice Allen Broussard, who wrote one of three dissenting
opinions, accused the majority of ``a radical attempt to rewrite
California law'' in a way that will leave wrongfully fired workers
without adequate relief.
   ``This court is only concerned with stability of the corporation
and not the slightest bit with stability of everyday working
people,'' said Cliff Palefsky, a lawyer for employees and labor
unions.
   Victor Schachter, an employers' attorney, said the ruling
``provides a welcome bridle to unwarranted and costly termination
claims.''
   The ruling reinstates but sharply limits a suit by Daniel Foley,
who was fired from his $56,164-a-year job as Los Angeles branch
manager of Interactive Data Corp. in 1983, after telling the company
that his boss was being investigated by the FBI for embezzlement
from a former employer.
   Lucas said Foley could sue only on the grounds that his
encouraging treatment during nearly seven years of employment may
have amounted to a promise that he wouldn't be fired without good
cause.
   Under Thursday's ruling, his damages would be limited to lost pay.
   Since the court's 1980 ruling allowing wrongful-termination
suits, more than 40 other states have allowed some types of claims
by fired workers.
   But few have gone as far as California appellate court rulings
allowing emotional distress and punitive damages for workers
wrongfully fired.
   Those rulings were repudiated by the court majority Thursday.
   Most plaintiffs are managerial employees; union members generally
cannot sue, but must seek reinstatement through their labor
contracts.
   About 1,000 wrongful-termination suits were filed statewide in
1986; studies have shown employees winning about two-thirds of the
cases that go to trial, with damages averaging $177,000 for 120
winning plaintiffs in a 1980-86 Rand Corp. survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881229-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 2050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AirTravel     12-29 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Travel,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crash Having No Effect on Bookings, Airlines Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airline reservations and ticket sales indicate
travelers have been undeterred by the bombing last week of Pan Am
Flight 103, the carriers said Thursday.
   Spokesmen for TWA, British Airways and Pan Am said there has been
no appreciable change in ticket sales, reservations or telephone
inquiries.
   ``Business is normal,'' said Margie Vodopia, a spokeswoman for
British Airways. ``The airline has just come out of what is
traditionally our busy holiday period and business was normal and we
are entering what is traditionally a slower time, and it has been
business as usual for that time too.''
   ``We have not seen any effect,'' TWA spokesman Robert Blattner
agreed.
   ``This is of course a quiet period,'' said Pan Am spokesman Jeff
Kriendler, ``and we see no effect on future bookings.''
   Kevin Murphy, an airline analyst with Morgan Stanley, said that
while there was no evident change in business during the
post-holiday season, he wonders about long-range consequences,
particularly for summer vacationers who are more sensitive to safety
and economic concerns.
   ``My guess is that summer '89 travel will not be as good as
summer '88 because of those two factors, the weaker dollar and fear
of terrorism,'' Murphy said.
   While the fear of terrorism might deter some discretionary
travelers and cause some business travelers to switch to
European-based airlines, Murphy said growing fears of poor
maintenance and old aircraft might have an even bigger impact on the
airline industry.
   ``In a way, it was good news that it was a bomb and not metal
fatigue, because if it was metal fatigue, people really wouldn't
trust the rest of the fleet,'' Murphy said.
   Travel agents say some flyers have voiced concerns about aging
jetliners, but not enough to cause cancellations.
   ``I was booking someone today on Eastern to Lima (Peru) and their
only question was: `How old is the airplane?' But they still
booked,'' Iris Carroll, vice president of Adventure Travel in
Pompano Beach, Fla., said Thursday.
   ``Sophisticated clients know these things happen and that they
have no control over it,'' said Jack Bloch, president of JB's World
Travel in New York. ``If they were afraid, they couldn't travel.''
   It's the infrequent, leisure flyer who is most susceptible to
post-crash jitters, Bloch said.
   ``It's an immediate reaction, but if nothing happens in the next
month or two, they'll forget about it, which they always do,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
