<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-29 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Moratorium Looms As Parliament Rejects Austerity Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia may have to declare a
moratorium on foreign debt payments after parliament refused to pass
a law the IMF demanded for continued financial support, a newspaper
said Thursday.
   The major Yugoslav Communist Party daily Borba quoted an
unidentified Cabinet minister as saying the government should resign
as a result.
   It said parliament on Wednesday voted against a government
austerity law to limit wages in hard-pressed public services such as
health and education.
   Deputies defied warnings from Premier Branko Mikulic of
``Yugoslavia's obligations to the International Monetary Fund,'' the
newspaper said.
   Mikulic reportedly said the IMF insisted on the law before
agreeing in June to grant Yugoslavia a one-year standby credit of
$416 million.
   About $260 million of that credit already has been used,
according to official statistics.
   Parliament's decision ``destroys the standby arrangement with the
IMF, which in turn carries a series of other consequences,'' Borba
quoted the Cabinet minister as saying. ``After this, the government,
if it is intelligent enough, should submit its resignation,'' it
quoted the minister as saying.
   The Mikulic government faces widespread public calls to resign or
be swiftly replaced because of its inability to resolve Yugoslavia's
economic and social crisis.
   It is standard practice for the IMF to insist on curbing public
spending in inflation-ridden countries to reduce the rate of price
increases.
   With unemployment at 15 percent and inflation around 250 percent,
the standby loan was designed to help Yugoslavia meet payments on
its $21 billion foreign debt and reach agreements on loan
rescheduling with Western creditors.
   Western commercial banks and governments usually follow the IMF's
lead in judging whether to continue supporting a debtor country.
   The Cabinet minister was quoted as saying parliament's decision
``could endanger the rescheduling of $1.6 billion of Yugoslavia's
foreign debt falling due next year,'' which had been agreed
tentatively with foreign creditors.
   ``If that should happen, according to preliminary estimates, the
gross national product would decrease next year by eight percent,
thus presenting us with the possibility of declaring a moratorium,''
the Cabinet minister reportedly said.
   Borba said the Cabinet convened an emergency session immediately
after the vote late Wednesday ``to discuss the resulting
situation.'' The closed meeting published no statement by Thursday.
   Meanwhile, thousands of workers in different parts of the country
were reported on strike Thursday, protesting low wages and living
standards that officially have dropped to mid-1960s levels.
</TEXT>
