<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0647 12-29 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President-elect Vows Punishment of Plane Bombers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs bgng, `Bush was,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with additional fish caught, Bush returns to Washington; SUBS 22nd
graf pvs bgng, `In fact,' to DELETE 2nd full reference to Hart</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PINTLALA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush, expressing ``horror''
that a U.S. jetliner was downed by a bomb, said Thursday he would
``seek hard and punish firmly'' those responsible, if they can be
found.
   But Bush said it would be ``imprudent'' for him or any other
official to discuss ``what kind of action can be taken'' to
retaliate against terrorists.
   Bush, who has been secluded at a 10,000-acre south Texas ranch
hunting quail for three days, said he had no other information than
what was in the ``public domain'' about the bomb that blew up a Pan
American jetliner over Scotland last week. The crash killed 259
passengers and crew members and 11 people on the ground.
   The vice president made his comments as he left Chase Naval Air
Station in Beeville, Texas, headed for Pintala, about 15 miles from
Montgomery.
   Bush spent a few hours here fishing for bass on a private 55-acre
lake owned by Ray Scott, head of the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society
and founder of Bassmasters.
   ``Oh-oh ... real trouble,'' the president-elect said as he
snagged a tree by mistake. But, casting from the back of a boat, he
caught a two-pound fish a few minutes later.
   Bush caught nine fish by the end of the day, the largest of which
weighed three pounds, and he threw them all back, said Bush's
spokesman, Steve Hart.
   The president-elect arrived back to Washington in the evening.
   Asked about the British investigators' conclusion that a bomb
destroyed the Pan Am jumbo jet, Bush said he felt ``horror'' at the
finding.
   Pressed by reporters on what action should be taken, he
responded, ``Seek hard and punish firmly, decisively those who did
this, if you can ever find them.'' He added: ``When I say punish
severely, that's what I mean.''
   Despite his tough rhetoric, Bush acknowledged that stopping
terrorism was virtually impossible.
   ``When you're dealing with something as cowardly as that it's
almost impossible to guarantee there will never be another terrorism
act,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, we've seen that happen several
times.''
   To stop terrorist acts, officials need to ``continue and step up
'' anti-terrorism policies, including improved intelligence and
heightened worldwide awareness to the problem, Bush said.
   As vice president, Bush headed a presidential task force on
terrorism, and he referred to that role Thursday.
   ``We have a fine anti-terrorism policy,'' he said. ``I take great
pride in having coordinated ... the anti-terrorism report and
setting high standards for people around the world,'' he said.
   At Chase Naval Air Station, Bush took a few minutes to mount a
restored TBM Avenger, a torpedo bomber like the one he flew on World
War II missions over the Pacific.
   Clutching a white marking pen, he signed and underlined his
wife's name, Barbara, just below the cockpit. He then wrote,
``George Bush.''
   All of Bush's planes during were named for the vice president's
then-fiancee, Barbara Pierce. The plane will be transported to the
Corpus Christi, Texas, Naval Air Station for display.
   Attending the ceremony was Leo Nadeau of San Diego, Bush's
regular tail gunner on bombing missions. Nadeau's name and that of
his wife, Ginny, also were written on the plane.
   Bush said his annual hunting trip was enjoyable, particularly the
exercise from walking. The shooting wasn't up to past years, though.
   ``The drought, I think, caught up with the quail this year.'' The
hunting party shot about 10 birds a day instead of the usual 30 to
40, he said.
   While Bush enjoys most outdoor sports, he said fishing is his
favorite.
   In fact, Hart said the vice president planned another two-day
fishing trip to Florida before the Jan. 20 inauguration, possibly
over the Martin Luther King Birthday holiday.
   The next trip will be to Islamorada in the Florida Keys, about 75
miles south of Miami.
   During this stay at the Lazy F Ranch, Bush said he and his fellow
hunter and nominee for secretary of state, James Baker III,
discussed some ``personnel matter'' as well as policies after Bush
is sworn in.
   In Washington, Bush said he will ``finish the Cabinet, start
fleshing out the (deputy) secretary and undersecretary levels and,
most important, formulating definitive plans for the first 100
days.''
   He said he is ``fairly close'' to naming an energy secretary and
a drug czar, the two Cabinet-level posts that remain vacant.
   Bush said he didn't know if he would make any personnel
announcements Friday, but his aides indicated that was a possibility.
</TEXT>
