<HEAD>$250,000 Bail for Alleged Drunken Driver Unlicensed Since 1983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with 10 drunken driving convictions
who lost his license for the offense in 1983 had his bail set at
$250,000 Thursday in a new drunken driving case.
   The bail for William Raymond Hilbert, 43, of Pomona was raised
from $15,000 at the request of a deputy of Los Angeles County
District Attorney Ira Reiner, who called the defendant a hazard to
the community.
   ``This is a blatant example of the kind of driver we must keep
off the roads and freeways, especially over the holiday weekend, for
the safety of other drivers,'' Reiner said.
   Municipal Court Commissioner Richard Grey ordered Hilbert jailed
when he couldn't post the bond on new misdemeanor charges.
   Hilbert was arrested Oct. 2 after a breath test showed his blood
alcohol level was .27 percent, nearly triple the legal maximum of
.10 percent, said Al Albergate, the district attorney's spokesman.
He is charged with drunken driving and with driving on a revoked
license.
   Since 1981, he has been convicted 10 times of drunken driving,
and has been sentenced twice to the maximum one-year term, Albergate
said. His license was revoked in 1983 on one such conviction, the
spokesman said, adding that he didn't know how much time Hilbert has
served on the various convictions.
   In six of his convictions, Hilbert's blood alcohol level
registered .28 percent or higher, according to the prosecutor on the
case, Deputy District Attorney Gary Hernsberger.
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' Hernsberger said. ``What's
amazing is that he hasn't killed somebody.''
</TEXT>
