<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Taxes-Poll     12-29 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taxes-Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Americans Unwilling To Pay More Taxes To Cut Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than 10 percent of Americans would be
willing to pay a higher federal income tax to reduce the national
deficit, but most believe President-elect Bush will ask for one,
according to a newspaper poll released Thursday.
   The nationwide survey of 611 adults _ conducted for USA Today
which will publish the complete results in Friday's editions _
showed only 9 percent of Americans favor a tax hike to reduce the
national deficit, but 75 percent say Bush is somewhat or very likely
to seek one.
   However, higher percentages of Americans would favor raising
taxes on gas, alcohol and tobacco if the money were earmarked solely
to reduce the government's red ink. Fifty-six percent would favor a
higher gasoline tax and 83 percent a higher tax on alcohol and
tobacco.
   Most of those surveyed _ 72 percent _ say the way to cut the
deficit is to reduce government spending, with defense spending
singled out by 50 percent as the category most easily targeted for
cutting.
   The poll, conducted Dec. 14-16, had a 4 percent margin or error.
</TEXT>
