<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-UN     12-29 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-UN,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola Sends Aid Request to U.N., Rebels Claim Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos
formally asked the United Nations on Thursday for aid to finance the
withdrawal of approximately 50,000 Cuban troops, the state news
agency ANGOP reported.
   A report monitored in Lisbon said dos Santos sent a letter to
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar requesting
international aid for the $800 million the Luanda government says it
will cost to send the Cubans home.
   The troops have supported Marxist Angola in its 13-year civil war
against U.S.- and South African-backed rebels. They are being
withdrawn as part of a peace plan for southern Africa.
   Angola, Cuba and South Africa signed pacts Dec. 22 that foresee
the gradual pullout of the Cubans and implementation of an
independence plan for neighboring South-West Africa, better known as
Namibia, which South Africa has ruled for 73 years.
   ``Because of the economic difficulties faced by Angola and Cuba,
(their economies) cannot bear the costs alone,'' ANGOP quoted dos
Santos as saying.
   In Lisbon, rebels of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) said they planted a bomb that
exploded Tuesday in downtown Luanda, killing one person and injuring
13.
   Angola on Thursday accused the rebels of killing 31 civilians and
kidnapping 92 in terrorist attacks over an unspecified period, ANGOP
reported.
   It said troops killed 69 rebels and captured six in clashes
across Angola during the last week, with 11 soldiers killed, 33
wounded and two missing .
   Soldiers also freed 129 civilians from rebel captivity, the
report said.
   No independent confirmation was available.
   In South Africa, Foreign Affairs Minister Roelof Botha said peace
in neighboring Mozambique would mean more to his country's
international position than ending hostilities in Angola and Namibia.
   This would strengthen South Africa's role as a regional power,
Botha said in an interview broadcast on state radio.
   For years, Mozambican officials have accused the Pretoria
government of supporting rightist Mozambican National Resistance
guerrillas in their fight to topple the Marxist-oriented Maputo
government.
   Relations between the two countries improved this year, with
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano playing host to South African
President P.W. Botha at a summit in September. Mozambican officials
still refer to elements in South Africa, however, who they charge
aid the rebels' sabotage campaign.
</TEXT>
