<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Referendum     12-29 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Referendum,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Intellectuals Attack Referendum Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Cuban intellectuals on Thursday sharply
criticized a proposal by more than 100 writers, artists, and
scientists living abroad that President Fidel Castro hold a
referendum on extending his rule.
   Roberto Retamar, a longtime supporter of Castro who heads a
cultural center in this city, said the appeal was tainted because it
likened Cuba's situation to that of Chile. In Chile, military
President Augusto Pinochet was defeated last October in a yes-or-no
vote on extending his 15-year rule.
   Speaking at a news conference with four other intellectuals,
Retamar rejected the comparison and called Pinochet an ``assassin.''
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman made a similar criticism earlier
this week when he was quoted as rejecting the proposal.
   Retamar said many who signed the open letter asking for a
referendum ``would applaud the establishment of a fascist regime in
the entire world.''
   Abriel Prito, an essayist at the news conference, said such a
plebiscite is unnecessary because few societies have undergone a
period of self-examination as profound as Cuba has over the past two
years. He said Cuba has carried out perhaps ``the purest revolution
in history.''
   Those who signed the open letter to Castro asking for the
referendum come from the United States, Europe and Latin America.
The appeal was also signed by about 50 Cubans exiles.
   The letter was made public earlier this week as Castro prepares
to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the Cuban revolution on Sunday.
</TEXT>
