<HEAD>Police Charge Man With Conspiracy To Cause Explosions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with bomb attack in Northern Ireland.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, Police found ... with minor editing to
conform</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 35-year-old hospital porter was charged with
conspiracy and withholding information about terrorism ``regarding
Northern Ireland affairs'' after police uncovered a bomb factory in
a south London apartment, Scotland Yard said Thursday.
   In Bangor, Northern Ireland, a bomb planted by the Irish
Republican Army exploded Thursday night under a policeman's car
outside his home, police said. The bomb, containing about three
pounds of explosives, destroyed the car but the officer was inside
his home with his family and no one was hurt, they said.
   The IRA claimed responsibility in a message to Belfast news
organizations.
   Many police officers live in Bangor, a predominantly Protestant
seaside resort 10 miles northeast of Belfast, the provincial capital.
   In London, Scotland Yard identified the hospital porter as Edward
Wadley of north London and said police arrested him on Dec. 22, the
day after the arsenal was found in the Clapham area.
   A brief Scotland Yard statement gave no arrest details and did
not indicate any link with two fugitive IRA suspects being sought by
police in connection with the arsenal.
   Police found the haul after an incident in which an 18-year-old
man was shot in the stomach after breaking the window of a car
parked outside the apartment.
   Authorities say a man inside the car, a suspected IRA member,
apparently was asleep or keeping watch in the back seat when the
would-be thief tried to break in.
   A police sweep resulted and officers reported finding a cache of
Czechoslovak-made Semtex explosive, often used by the IRA; machine
guns; rifles; handguns and bomb-making equipment.
   Police say they believe two fugitive IRA suspects rented the
apartment recently.
   In Belfast, police said soldiers and police on Thursday found a
4OO-pound bomb hidden in a stone wall near the main Belfast-Dublin
railroad line in South Armagh.
   A spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping with
British practice, said the explosives _ in eight bags and primed for
use _ were found about 250 yards from where a Dec. 16 bomb damaged
rail track at Kilnasaggart Bridge.
   The bomb apparently was intended for security forces moving about
the area after the bridge attack.
   ``We were expecting a booby trap of some sort,'' said the
spokesman.
   No claim of responsibility was advanced. Suspicion, however, fell
on the IRA, which uses explosives widely in its battle to drive the
British from the Protestant-dominated province and unite it with the
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Republic of Ireland to the south.
</TEXT>
