<DOCNO> AP881229-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Aerosols     12-29 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Aerosols,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harrods, Other Stores to Stop Selling Aerosols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harrods and 65 sister department stores will stop
selling aerosols that damage the Earth's ozone shield, the store
chain announced Thursday.
   Mohamed Fayed, chairman of the House of Fraser chain that owns
Harrods, said he hoped other businesses and industries would follow
suit.
   ``The preservation of the environment is the responsiblity of
every one of us,'' he said. He did not announce a date by which the
aerosols would be off the shelves.
   Marks and Spencer PLC, a large clothing and food retailer that
purchased the U.S. Brooks Brothers chain this year, already has
vowed to stop selling aerosols by the end of the year.
   Prince Charles, who is known for his environmental concerns,
announced lsat summer that his household would give up aerosols.
   On Dec. 16, Britain, seven other European countries, and the
European Economic Community ratified a treaty limiting production of
ozone-destroying chemicals. The treaty goes into effect Jan. 1.
   Chlorofluorocarbon compounds in aerosols are one of a number of
non-toxic chemicals that can last for more than a century in the
atmosphere. They rise slowly to the ozone layer, 15-25 miles high,
where their chlorine atoms destroy ozone.
   The ozone layer protects the Earth's surface from the harmful
ultraviolet rays of the sun. Other damaging chemicals that destroy
the ozone layer include refrigeration fluids, foam-blowing agents,
and cleaning solvents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
