<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Copper7Jury     12-29 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copper 7 Jury,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Questions Jurors About Copper 7 Damage Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge questioned jurors Thursday to
determine if a $8.15 million damage award against the G.D. Searle &
Co. drug firm should be overturned because of possible jury
misconduct.
   Esther Kociemba of Elk River won the award in September after a
three-month trial and almost 10 days of jury deliberations. The
verdict supported her claim that a Searle Copper-7 intrauterine
birth control device had triggered a pelvic infection that left her
infertile.
   But three of the eight jurors later signed affidavits alleging
they were the victims of verbal harassment and intimidation and had
been bullied into an ``unjust'' verdict.
   The affidavits also said newspaper accounts of the trial had been
smuggled into the jury room along with information from a medical
dictionary. U.S. District Judge Robert Renner had specifically told
the jurors not to discuss the case, read about it or consult medical
dictionaries.
   Renner questioned the jurors one at a time. He did not say when
he would issue a ruling. Under federal law, the hearing could not
delve into the process of deliberations, including the allegations
of intimidation, but only into evidence of improper outside
influence.
   In an interview following the hearing, Searle attorney, Paul
Strain, said the jurors' testimony definitely points to misconduct.
   ``The record of misconduct is even more extensive than we
thought,'' including one juror discussing the case with a relative
who is a doctor, Strain said.
   ``What is striking is the tremendous degree of use of extraneous,
prejudicial information,'' he said. ``It clearly infected the entire
deliberative process.''
   Kociemba's attorney, Michael Ciresi, said there is no basis to
Searle's motion to impeach the verdict. Ciresi and other lawyers for
Kociemba had complained in a previous, open hearing that Searle
refuses to accept its defeat and is trying to retry the case outside
the court room.
   ``I didn't believe there was any basis for the motion before the
hearing. And I don't believe anything happened during the hearing to
change that opinion,'' Ciresi said Thursday. ``Indeed, what took
place during the hearing supported the plaintiff's (Kociemba's)
position.''
   The Kociemba verdict was the first time punitive damages had been
awarded against Chicago-based Searle over the Copper-7 and Ciresi
said the verdict was a victory not only for Kociemba, but for the
more than 500 women who have suits pending against Searle over the
IUD.
</TEXT>
