<HEAD>Greek Premier Says Scandals Won't Make Him Quit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou shurgged off
calls for his resignation on Thursday and struck back at the
opposition and press in the face of widening financial scandals that
are rocking his Socialist government.
   Addressing 140 members of his party's central committee,
Papandreou also spurned demands for immediate elections. He said
general elections would be held in June 1989, as scheduled.
   ``I repeat, with even greater emphasis this time, that I will
remain in active politics,'' he said during an hourlong speech at an
Athens hotel.
   Both conservative and Communist opposition parties have united in
demanding Papandreou's resignation and immediate elections.
   Papandreou said Thursday his Panhellenic Socialist Movement
(PASOK) was going through its worst crisis since he founded it in
1974, and accused opposition parties of plotting to undermine the
government.
   ``We do not have the right to remain passive and defensive
against the deterioration of PASOK which is being pursued,'' said
the 69-year-old premier.
   Popular support for PASOK has been eroding following a series of
multimillion-dollar financial scandals. Most of Greece's usually
pro-government press has chided the governing party.
   The latest scandal involves the sale of weapons to Iraq by a
state-owned operation. Finance Minister Dimitris Tsovolas denied
newspaper allegations that he and Papandreou gave the state-owned
arms industry permission to pay kickbacks to foreign arms dealers.
   Another scandal is swirling around the Bank of Crete and its
ousted chairman, George Koskotas. He is accused of fraud or
embezzlement involving millions of dollars, and his ties to
government leaders have created an embarrassment. Seven ministers
have quit over the scandal.
   Papandreou accused the domestic press Thursday of orchestrating
``an unhealthy and destabilizing climate by creating forged,
fabricated and unfounded stories.''
   In an effort to shore up his government, Papandreou threatened to
resign earlier in the month and asked Parliament for a vote of
confidence during debate on the 1989 budget. The deficit budget was
approved by a narrow margin.
</TEXT>
