<HEAD>Contras Offer to Renew Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels offered to renew peace talks
with the Sandinista government in Washington on Jan. 25, a leader of
the Nicaraguan Resistance said in Miami.
   But ``if the Sandinista government does not reach a peace accord,
the Nicaraguan Resistance will be obligated to renew the war,''
Aristides Sanchez said in a tape recording played for The Associated
Press bureau in Managua.
   Sanchez is a director of the political organization of the
U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras. Radio Liberation reporter
Alejandro Acevedo in Miami played the recording during a telephone
call to Managua.
   Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Ortega Saavedra said on Tuesday
that the government is ready to resume talks with the Contras.
   Efforts to reach government spokesmen following the rebel
announcement Thursday were unsuccessful.
   Sanchez said the proposed talks would renew negotiations that
broke down in Sapoa, Nicaragua, in June. An attempt to resume talks
in Guatemala failed in September.
   He said the rebels will give a copy of the peace proposal to
Central American presidents on Jan. 3. Sanchez suggested the talks
be held at the headquarters of the Organization of American States
in Washington.
   Agreements reached in Sapoa last March established a 60-day
cease-fire that has been renewed several times. This month, the
Sandinistas unilaterally extended the cease-fire until next June and
the rebels said they would support the continued truce.
   However, minor armed confrontations have continued.
   The Defense Ministry said on Thursday that Honduran soldiers
attacked Sandinista border guards in eastern Chinandega province,
firing M-16 rifles from Honduran territory. It did not say when the
alleged attack took place.
   In the Honduran capital, Tegucigalpa, the Foreign Ministry
meanwhile announced Thursday that less than half the 104 Nicaraguan
prisoners released by the Contras on Honduran territory on Dec. 23
had returned to Nicaragua.
   Others said they want to go to the United States, Mexico and
Canada, said ministry spokesman Eugenio Castro.
   He said 44 former prisoners crossed the border from Honduras to
Nicaragua at Las Manos.
   Those who did not return will remain in Honduras while awaiting
visas, Castro said.
   The Contras said the 96 men and eight women, some of them
Sandinista troops, were captured a year ago during battles in the
Nicaraguan provinces of Chontales, Matagalpa and Madriz.
   On Dec. 20, Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said Honduras
would not let armed groups hold prisoners illegally in Honduras.
   The rebels say they no longer hold any captives.
   More than 55,000 people have died in seven years of civil war in
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
