<HEAD>Review Board Forwards Seven of 115 Police Brutality Complaints</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``Everyone's going ..., to CORRECT spelling of
Reppetto, sted Repetto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven of 115 complaints of police misconduct
stemming from a riot at a park on a hot August night have been
forwarded for departmental trial, a civilian review board said
Thursday.
   The Civilian Complaint Review Board said it has taken up 22 of
the 115 complaints, and has recommended to Police Commissioner
Benjamin Ward that departmental trials be held for six officers on
seven allegations of brutality.
   At least 52 officers and 18 civilians required hospital treatment
for injuries received during the Aug. 7 riot at Tompkins Square
Park. A police chief accused of poor supervision resigned and two
policemen were indicted this month on assault charges.
   Most of the complaints not forwarded to the commissioner were
dropped for lack of substantiation, with complainants failing to
follow up their allegations, the board said in an interim report.
   ``Everyone's going to be disappointed about this investigation,''
said Thomas Reppetto, the head of the Citizens Crime Commission, a
nonprofit group that monitors crime in New York City.
   ``Civilian Complaint Review Boards around the country tend to be
very legalistic, that's the way they have to be,'' Reppetto added.
``That has a tendency to disappoint people who thought a civilian
review board was going to work a miracle.''
   The report expressed frustration that no police officers had
volunteered evidence.
   ``Here you've got over 100 complaints in the presence of 400
police officers and 40 sergeants over a period of about six hours in
about a six-block area and no police officer has come forward to
either defend one of his fellow officers or to provide evidence that
one of these things happened,'' board member Dan Johnston said at a
news conference.
   Johnston accused the Policeman's Benevolent Association of
recommending officers not cooperate, which police union President
Phil Caruso denied.
   Chairwoman Mary Burke Nicholas said the board would hear 27 more
complaints on Jan. 18 and should resolve the rest by February.
   She said at the news conference that of the 15 cases closed
without disciplinary charges, eight were dropped because
complainants or victims were uncooperative or unavailable. Three
other complaints were withdrawn, two were found to be outside the
board's jurisdiction, one was unsubstantiated and one was closed
because the officer could not be identified, the report said.
   ``In my judgment, we're going to end up with a large number of
cases where we believe the abuse occurred, and where we can't
identify the officer,'' said Johnston.
   Videotapes taken by residents showed that several officers
covered their badges with dark tape to keep from being identified.
   The melee between police and demonstrators was sparked by
enforcement of a curfew in Tompkins Square Park.
   The park, in a Lower East Side neighborhood called the East
Village, is a gathering place for musicians, drug dealers, homeless
people and teen-agers. Its neighbors range from squatters to owners
of luxury condominiums, the latter group favoring the curfew.
</TEXT>
