<1ST_LINE>a f PM-OnTheMoney Adv29   12-29 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On The Money, Adv 29,0680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Dec. 29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Little-Known Tax Change Could Cause Big Problems For Firms,
Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Picture this: You've just undergone extensive
surgery for which the insurance company has picked up most of the
tab. But by year's end you're suddenly forced to pay taxes on those
benefits just as if they were part of your regular income.
   Then you're socked with taxes on other company-sponsored extras,
like the group life insurance policy or the subsidized day-care
program and night classes. Even those daily meals in the company
cafeteria aren't safe.
   Welcome to Section 89, known to some tax experts and companies as
the ``Twilight Zone'' of the 1986 tax reform law.
   While it's unlikely such a nightmarish scenario could occur, the
potential is in place under the little-known provision that mandates
changes in corporate America's employee-benefit structure starting
next year.
   The intention of the new rules had been to encourage employers to
offer health insurance and other benefits to more of their workers _
and more democratically. But many tax experts say the opposite is
likely to occur, and the harsh penalties for companies that break
the law could create a slew of tax hardships for employees.
   Section 89 is divided into two parts. One requires businesses to
communicate to their employees exactly what benefits are being
offered and the qualifications for receiving them. Failure to spell
these out means employees must include the entire value of the
benefits in their gross income.
   ``If an employee's health insurance paid out $50,000 for surgery
... he could be taxed on that amount,'' explained Thomas J. Zesk, a
senior manager with Deloitte Haskins & Sells.
   And if companies fail to report that income on their employee's
W-2 tax form, they can be fined, he said.
   Most big companies already have written benefit plans in place,
so their employees need not worry about paying taxes on important
health benefits or on the savings derived from company-subsidized
child-care programs or meals in the cafeteria, tax experts say.
   Those requirements of Section 89 will hit small businesses the
hardest.
   Even if companies fail to comply, the penalties are ``so
Draconian'' that they probably wouldn't be imposed, said Thomas
Veal, a senior manager with the accounting firm of Touche Ross & Co.
   But the other portion of Section 89, which deals with
``discriminatory'' benefits plans, has many companies concerned,
experts say.
   The new law says that if top-paid company executives _ those
making around $52,230 a year or more _ are given more health or life
insurance benefits than lesser-paid employees, the top brass must
pay taxes on the ``excess.''
   The idea was to encourage companies to distribute benefits
equally, especially to the 37 million Americans who currently don't
have health insurance.
   ``The intent was somewhat noble, but I think they went overboard.
It's a prime example of overkill,'' Zesk said.
   In order to comply with this part of the new rules companies must
submit to a lengthy testing procedure that determines whether
benefits are available to at least 90 percent of the work force,
including part-timers who work at least 17.5 hours a week.
   Tax experts say that many companies may just find it cheaper to
pay their executives more money to make up for the taxes they'll pay
on the cushier benefits, than to provide more benefits for the
rank-and-file employees.
   Others may decide to cut back on the core benefits provided to
everyone or else make do with fewer part-timers, they say.
   For now, companies across the country are working with accounting
firms to prepare for Section 89.
   ``Some clients have gathered the data (for the testing procedure)
and are going forward ... and some are still at the stumped and
disbelief stage,'' said Veal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Dec. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
