<2ND_LINE>BC-FNN-Dow Jones,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FNN Stock Rises on Report Dow Jones Seeking Stake in Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock in Financial News Network soared Thursday
after a published report said Dow Jones & Co. was seeking a stake in
the cable television service.
   USA Today reported that Dow Jones, which publishes the Wall
Street Journal, was interested in buying the 45 percent stake in FNN
owned by Infotechnology Inc., also known as Infotech, a New
York-based media company.
   FNN stock was sharply higher in over-the-counter trading Thursday
afternoon, rising $1.87{ to $8.62{.
   However, Infotech Chairman Earl Brian, who is also chairman of
United Press International, denied the USA Today report, saying, ``I
have no plans to sell the block of stock.''
   A spokesman for Dow Jones, Jim Ambrosio, said he could not
comment on the USA Today report.
   Brian said FNN has been discussing joint programming ventures
with a number of large media companies, but he declined to say
whether Dow Jones was among them.
   ``We don't comment on who we're talking to, simply because we're
talking to a lot of people,'' he said.
   The USA Today report also said Dow Jones was discussing producing
business shows with FNN. Dow Jones already is involved in broadcast
ventures, including the syndicated Wall Street Journal Report.
   FNN provides 18 hours of business news each weekday, as well as
sports and home shopping programming.
   Infotech's other subsidiaries include Data Broadcasting Corp.;
Questech Capital Corp.; TV Value Mart Corp.; and Comtex Scientific
Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
