<DOCNO> AP881229-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     12-29 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in narrow, quiet European
trading Thursday as markets wound down for the year. Gold prices
were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar remained stable, with
firm U.S. interest rates continuing to hold the currency at
relatively high levels.
   They said trading was extremely quiet, even stagnant, as many
market players and dealers remained on vacation between Christmas
and New Year's holidays.
   A dealer said a steep decline in the dollar at the beginning of
the Frankfurt session was more a reflection of thin seasonal trading
than any market bearishness.
   Little dollar movement was also expected on Friday, the last
trading day of the year.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.76 yen to a closing 126.03. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.80 yen.
   The British pound was quoted at $1.7900, unchanged from Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Wednesday's prices,
1.7875 West German marks, down from 1.7960; 1.5125 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5177; 6.0975 French francs, down from 6.1225; 2.0190
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0255; 1,314.50 Italian lire, down from
1,320.90; and 1.19225 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1963.
   In London, gold traded at a late bid price of $408.25 a troy
ounce, down from $413.95 late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was $410.75, down from $412.25 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.38 to close at a bid $416.07
a troy ounce.
