<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Lilco     12-29 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lilco,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Dividend Payments, Company Downplays Impact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge presiding over a rate-hike suit
against the Long Island Lighting Co. issued an order Thursday
temporarily barring the financially shaky utility from paying
dividends to shareholders.
   Company spokesman Joseph McDonnell sought to minimize the impact
of the order, saying the company had not paid dividends since 1984.
He said Lilco had no immediate plans to resume payments.
   The temporary restraining order issued by U.S. District Judge
Jack B. Weinstein of Brooklyn is in effect until next Wednesday when
Weinstein has scheduled a hearing for Lilco to argue why it should
be lifted.
   Weinstein is seeking a settlement of Suffolk County's successful
civil racketeering suit against Lilco, an accord that could possibly
include closing the controversial Shoreham nuclear power plant in
the Long Island county.
   Closed negotiations have been held for about two weeks.
   A jury earlier this month found that the utility had lied to
state officials about the progress of the Shoreham plant to obtain
rate increases in 1978 and 1984. The jury awarded $22.8 million in
damages to Suffolk.
   ``I think this is really the judge trying to assert his authority
and to show everybody how tough he's going to be and to force the
parties to negotiate a settlement to this whole thing,'' said Barry
Abramson, a senior utilities analyst with Prudential-Bache.
   Abramson downplayed the effect the order may have on Wall Street.
   ``The actual order is not significant in my opinion because Lilco
couldn't pay the dividends anyway,'' he said. ``I think that LILCO
has no ability and no desire to pay any dividends in the short run.''
   The restraining order was issued in response to a request by
Judith Vladeck, an attorney representing ratepayers.
   In Albany on Wednesday, the state Public Service Commission
denied Lilco's request for an immediate 5.4 percent rate increase
and said it would reconsider the utility's request again on Jan. 25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
