<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed little changed
Thursday in the last full session of the year on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   The exchange, like most other U.S. futures exchanges, will close
at noon local time Friday and reopen on Tuesday.
   Many analysts had expected strong gains in the grain markets
following the Agriculture Department's confirmation after
Wednesday's close of large purchases of corn and soybean meal by the
Soviet Union.
   Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York, said the corn business was expected and
the meal sale was offset by losses in the soybean oil pit.
   ``We've also had a lot of overhead resistance'' to higher soybean
and meal prices,'' she said. ``Once you take out those levels, the
market's going to go like gangbusters but until you breach them,
people are taking a more cautious approach.''
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.36{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 2} cents lower with March at $2.82{ a bushel; oats were { cent to
1{ cents higher with March at $2.39{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent
to 5 cents lower with January at $7.89 a bushel.
