<2ND_LINE>BC-Interco,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Sells Londontown Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. said Thursday that it has completed
the sale of its Londontown Corp. subsidiary to Eldersberg
Acquisition Corp. for $178 million in cash.
   Eldersberg Acquisition is comprised of a group organized by
senior management personnel of Londontown.
   Londontown, based in Eldersberg, Md., manufactures London Fog
rainwear.
   The sale was part of a defensive restructuring program announced
earlier this year by Interco to contest a hostile takeover bid by
brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington, D.C. The takeover
bid failed earlier this month.
   Interco has estimated that costs associated with the
restructuring will exceed $65 million. The company plans to sell off
all but its Converse Inc. and Florsheim Shoe Co. subsidiaries,
Broyhill Furniture Industries Inc. and Lane Co. furniture companies
and possibly the Central Hardware home-improvement stores.
   The sale of Londontown leaves Interco with 10 apparel companies,
five retail stores, four footwear companies and four furniture
companies.
   On Wednesday, Interco turned down a $190 million cash offer for
Londontown from Burlington Coat Factory Warehouse Inc.
   The St. Louis-based Interco said the proposal did not meet its
requirements of an assured, timely closing, and that uncertainties
surrounding the Burlington proposal and the risks of any delay could
harm the business of Londontown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
