<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 1705EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-US-EECCopper     12-29 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-EEC Copper,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Probes Complaint of Unfair Practice by EEC In Copper Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has started an investigation
into complaints that Britain and other European countries unfairly
restrict imports of American copper scrap, the government announced
Wednesday.
   If the investigation and proposed mediation efforts fail to
resolve the dispute within 18 months, the United States can then
retaliate against the Europeans.
   In accordance with procedures for investigating such complaints,
the U.S. Trade Representative has asked European Economic Community
to agree to consultations.
   If consultations with the Europeans fail to yield satisfactory
results, said USTR spokesman Cary Walker, the United States will
take its case to international arbitration.
   The investigation comes at a time of strained relations between
the United States and the EEC over a ban which the Europeans plan to
implement Jan. 1 on U.S. meat treated with hormones. The United
States plans to retaliate against the Europeans with 100 percent
duties on a variety of imported foods and beverages.
   Walker said the copper scrap investigation is not related in any
way to the hormone dispute. The petition was filed on Nov. 14, and
by law the USTR had to respond within 45 days, he said.
   The Copper and Brass Fabricators Council, which represents
American manufacturers, contends its members lose $180 million
annually in revenues because of quotas set by the Europeans.
   Copper scrap is used to make such products as door knobs, brass
lamps and guard rails.
   Since September 1985, the United States has accepted 65 to 70
petitions of complaint from U.S. manufacturers against foreign
competitors, and acted on 27 either through international mediation
or retaliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
