<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-29 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heated Demand Pushes Coffee Futures To 25-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices surged to their highest levels in more than
two years Thursday on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange amid
strong demand for tight supplies of green, unroasted coffee beans.
   On other markets, in uniformly light, pre-holiday trading, gold,
silver and energy futures retreated; grains and soybeans were mixed;
livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures
advanced.
   Thursday marked the last full day of trading this year on most
U.S. futures markets. Most markets will close at noon local time
Friday and reopen on Tuesday.
   Coffee settled 3.80 cents to 6.94 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $1.5898 a pound. During the session, the
March contract traded as high as $1.596 a pound, the highest coffee
futures price since Nov. 14, 1986.
   Poor growing and harvesting conditions in Central and South
America have cut deeply into the availability of green coffee,
forcing U.S. roasters to pay higher prices to obtain supplies for
the winter months, when coffee consumption reaches its annual peak.
   The recent, rapid rise in prices _ a gain of more than 30 cents a
pound since Dec. 1 _ has also prompted roasters to buy March coffee
futures as a hedge against futher price increases on the cash
market, analysts said.
   Bert Ruiz, a coffee broker with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New
York, said the widening price gap between the March and May coffee
contracts indicated that demand for near-term supplies was
continuing to grow. The March contract's price rose by nearly 7
cents a pound Wednesday while May deliveries advanced by just over
4.8 cents.
   ``This is a demand-driven market,'' Ruiz said. ``Roasters are
flocking to March and selling May because they believe there's going
to be an acute tightness of quality beans in March, whereby by May
it should be relieved.''
   The tight-supply situation should ease during the second quarter
of 1989 as more newly harvested beans reach the market and
consumption begins a seasonal decline, he said.
   Platinum futures prices rebounded after hitting resistance near
$500 a troy ounce on the New York Mercantile Exchange but gold and
silver futures posted significant losses on New York's Commodity
Exchange.,
   Rumors that the Soviet Union would sell physical gold to pay for
new grain purchases kept the gold and silver markets under pressure
although trading volume was extremely thin, said John O'Connell,
manager of futures research for Refco Inc. in New York.
   Platinum settled $1.30 to $4.30 higher with January at $514.30 a
troy ounce; gold was $6.10 to $8 lower with February at $415.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 9.1 cents to 10 cents lower with March at
$609.3 cents a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices fell moderately on the New York Mercantile
Exchange amid profit-taking and book-squaring ahead of the New
Year's weekend, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 20 cents to 23 cents
lower with February at $16.77 a barrel; heating oil was .69 cent to
.83 cent lower with January at 52.77 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .03 cent to .60 cent lower with January at 47.01 cents
a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures were little changed on the Chicago
Board of Trade despite a surge in sales of U.S. wheat, corn and
soybean meal to the Soviet Union.
   The corn and wheat business had been expected and a
600,000-metric ton meal sale was offset by losses in the soybean oil
pit, said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York,
   Wheat settled 1\ cents lower to 1\ cent higher with March at
$4.36} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with March at
$2.82{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1{ cents higher with March at
$2.39{ a bushel; soybeans were } cent to 5\ cents lower with January
at $7.88} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures ended narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on position-evening ahead of the long weekend,
analysts said.
   Live cattle settled .07 cent lower to .05 cent higher with
February at 73.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower
to .15 cent higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs
were .15 cent to .32 cent lower with February at 46.82 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .20 cent higher
with February at 43.12 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures made moderate gains on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 1.75 points higher at 282.10. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
