<HEAD>Pontiac LeMans Owners Urged To Get New Safety Belt Buckles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Detroit filed</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of 1988 Pontiac LeMans automobiles are
being urged by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to
have their cars checked for defective safety belt buckles,
administrators said Thursday.
   NHTSA Administrator Diane K. Steed said General Motors Corp.
recalled 85,000 model year 1988 Pontiac LeMans vehicles to correct
the problem.
   The defective buckles could appear to be latched when in fact
they are not, NHTSA said in a Thursday news release.
   ``Safety belts are the most important safety equipment in a car
and more Americans than ever before _ 46 percent _ now use them,''
Steed said. ``Safety belts saved about 4,000 lives in 1987 and if
everyone used them every trip, about 15,000 lives could be saved
each year.''
