<2ND_LINE>BC-Lorimar,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sale of Puerto Rico TV Stations Final</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorimar Telepictures Corp. said it has
completed the sale of two television stations in Puerto Rico in a
deal the TV production company says removes a major obstacle to its
$1.2 billion merger with Warner Communications Inc.
   Lorimar, producer of ``Dallas,'' ``Alf'' and other TV series,
said Thursday it sold WLII-TV in San Juan and WSUR-TV in Ponce to a
Florida investment group headed by Timothy Brumlik of Orlando, Fla.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   Lorimar's ownership of the Puerto Rican stations and of WPGH-TV
in Pittsburgh had stymied New York-based Warner's plan to buy
Lorimar for approximately $1.2 billion in stock.
   Warner's biggest shareholder, Chris-Craft Industries Inc., got a
court order in August blocking the deal on grounds it violated a
1984 agreement signed when Warner and Chris-Craft bought shares in
each other. The agreement, which gave Warner 42.5 percent of
Chris-Craft's BHC Inc. television subsidiary, barred Warner from
owning other television stations.
   Lorimar owned six stations when it agreed to merge with Warner.
Sale of the Puerto Rican stations leaves only WPGH, and the company
has reached an agreement in principle to sell that to Renaissance
Communications, organized by investor Michael Finkelstein and
Warburg Pincus Capital.
   The Warner buyout is expected to be consummated in January,
Lorimar said in a news release, apparently indicating sale of the
Pittsburgh station will be completed by then.
   A call to Chris-Craft's New York offices late Thursday was not
returned.
</TEXT>
