<1ST_LINE>u f AM-S&LBailouts 1stLd-Writethru f0240 12-29 1075</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Bailouts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0240,1099</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Announce Sale of 13 S&Ls in Texas and Illinois</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 15 new grafs to UPDATE with additional S&L bailouts;
PICKS UP 10th graf pvs bgng, `In virtually'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators, working against a year-end
tax deadline, announced the sale of 13 more insolvent savings and
loan institutions in Texas and Illinois on Thursday.
   The latest deals brought to 197 the number of insolvent S&Ls
which have been dealt with by federal officials this year, a
post-Depression record, far surpassing the 48 S&Ls closed in 1987.
   Officials predicted that they are sure to top the target of
dealing with 200 failed S&Ls this year before a midnight deadline
Saturday, when tax breaks for the buyers of ailing S&Ls will be cut
in half.
   The latest takeovers included the first purchase of Texas
institutions by foreigners. A group of investors from Taiwan agreed
to buy eight insolvent Texas institutions.
   The latest deals followed two of the largest bailouts of S&Ls.
The government announced Wednesday it was pledging assistance
totaling $6.8 billion to the purchasers of a huge California
institution and five of the most financially troubled Texas S&Ls.
   The agreements Thursday were announced after the three-member
Federal Home Loan Bank Board spent the day huddled behind closed
doors reviewing offers.
   In one of the deals, eight insolvent Texas S&Ls were sold to
Pacific USA Holdings Corp., a Texas subsidiary of a Taiwanese
company, which agreed to invest $37.5 million to purchase the S&Ls.
The branches will be operated under the name Pacific Southwest
Savings Bank F.S.B., headquartered in Corpus Christi.
   The bank board agreed to provide $566.2 million in government
assistance to the purchasers.
   Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall hailed the sale to the
Taiwanese investors, saying, ``We welcome our first non-U.S. owned
investor to the Southwest Plan (the program for dealing with sick
S&Ls in Texas). Their interest in investing in the future of Texas
is a further indication of the attractiveness of the state's thrift
industry as well as it's business climate, which is what we've been
saying all along.''
   The S&Ls being purchased were Charter Savings and Loan of Corpus
Christi; Keystone Savings and Loan of Lampasas; Bayview Federal
Savings Association of Corpus Christi; First Federal Savings and
Loan of Luling; Independence Savings and Loan of Gonzales; Yoakum
Federal Savings and Loan of Yoakum; Union Savings Association of San
Antonio; and Sequin Savings Association of Sequin.
   A second sale involved four insolvent Texas thrifts, which were
purchased by the Centex Corp., a Dallas home builder, who will
operate the former branches as Texas Trust Savings Bank F.S.B. In
that transaction, the bank board will provide $429 million in
government assistance and Centex will invest $26.5 million.
   The insolvent S&Ls purchased by Centex were Burnet Savings and
Loan of Burnet; Lee Savings Association of Giddings; Ranchers
Savings Association of Johnson City; and Peoples Savings and Loan of
Llano.
   The third deal involved the sale of American Savings Bank of
Springfield, Ill., at a cost to the government of $187.9 million.
The insolvent S&L was being taken over by Citizens Federal Bank of
Miami, which will operate American's 23 offices as branches of
Citizens Federal. Citizens Federal is investing no money in the deal.
   Federal regulators faced new criticism on Thursday about their
year-end rush to close insolvent S&Ls, but they continued to insist
that the cost to the government of simply closing the institutions
and paying off depositors would far exceed the sales being arranged
which use tax breaks and direct federal assistance as a lure for
private investors.
   The tax benefits will be effectively cut in half after midnight
Saturday. The provisions that will expire allow firms who purchased
failed S&Ls to deduct the previous losses of those associations from
profits the firms earned on other operations.
   In virtually all of transactions completed in 1988, the firms
taking over the S&Ls will qualify for tax breaks that will far
exceed what they are paying for the institutions.
   Congressional critics have questioned these tax benefits,
contending that the bank board is rushing the sales through without
a proper analysis of the revenue loss to the federal government.
   In a letter to Wall, Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn. and the new
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, said ``I have serious
questions about the impact your plans will have on the federal
budget, the competitive balance of the remaining thrift industry and
the concentration of power without our financial systems.''
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas and the new chairman of the House
Banking Committee, said he plans to hold a series of hearings,
looking especially at the two largest bailouts announced this week
involving $6.8 billion in government assistance in the sale of a
California S&L to Texas billionaire Robert Bass and the purchase of
five deeply troubled Texas S&Ls by a group headed by Revlon
cosmetics chairman Ronald Perelman.
   ``All of the bank board's eleventh-hour deals will be reviewed by
the House Banking Committee,'' he said in a statement. ``We will be
looking at whether the bank board has been getting the best deals
possible.''
   Wall called the Bass purchase ``a major achievement of an
extremely eventful 1988'' because it took off the government's hands
American Savings of Stockton, Calif., the country's largest
insolvent S&L.
   Congress and the incoming Bush administration will be looking for
ways to finance the remaining 400 insolvent S&Ls. Estimates of the
total cost to the government of resolving the S&L mess range from
$50 billion to $112 billion with even the low figure certain to
swell the federal budget deficit.
   Industry losses from the insolvent institutions are mounting by
$1 billion a month.
   For this reason, analysts said, President-elect Bush cannot
afford to delay dealing with the problem. Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady, who is remaining in his job in the new
administration, has already launched a study to find ways to finance
the rescue effort.
   ``The Bush administration will be committing political suicide if
it doesn't candidly address this problem immediately after taking
office,'' said Bert Ely, a financial consultant based in Alexandria,
Va.
   All of the S&Ls being taken over this week have been insolvent
for several years but have been kept open because the government's
insurance fund, the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., did
not have enough cash to pay off depositors and shut the institutions
down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
