<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-88 2246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   12-29 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0142</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES with morning dollar close, comments</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
in morning trading in Tokyo Friday, the last day of foreign exchange
dealings for 1988.
   The dollar opened at 125.75 yen, down 0.28 yen from Thursday's
close, but moved to 125.93 yen by the end of the morning session.
   Dealers said the dollar weakened in Tokyo following a similar
trend on overseas markets Thursday, where the West German central
bank intervened with dollar-selling to prop up the West German mark.
   A dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo described currency
trading as ``very thin'' ahead of a three-day New Year holiday
starting Saturday.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange held its last session for the year on
Wednesday and will reopen on Jan. 4.
</TEXT>
